window.CELPIP_BANK_GEN = {"reading":{"correspondence":[{"id":"landlord-boiler-shutdown-notice","title":"Notice from the Building Manager","instructions":"Read the following email and answer the questions.","passage":"Hi Renuka,\n\nI'm writing to let you know that the heating contractor will be replacing the main boiler in our building at 84 Maplewood Court next Tuesday, March 12. To do the work safely, they'll need to shut off the hot water and heat for the whole building between 8:00 a.m. and roughly 4:00 p.m.\n\nI realize this is an inconvenience, especially with the cold snap we've been having, so I want to give everyone plenty of warning. If you work from home, you may want to plan to be out for part of the day, or at least keep a few extra sweaters handy. The lobby washroom will stay open, but please don't run the taps in your unit during the shutdown, as the pressure needs to stay low for the crew.\n\nOnce the new boiler is in, the heat should actually be more reliable than the patchwork we've been dealing with all winter. I'll post an update in the lobby by Wednesday morning confirming everything is back to normal.\n\nIf this date is a serious problem for you, reply to this email by Friday and I'll see what can be arranged.\n\nBest,\nDoug Pham\nBuilding Manager","questions":[{"q":"What is the main purpose of this email?","options":["To warn residents about a temporary loss of heat and hot water during boiler work","To announce that the building's rent will be increasing next month","To ask residents to volunteer to help the heating contractor","To complain about how cold the winter has been this year"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The opening states the contractor will replace the boiler on March 12 and shut off heat and hot water from 8 a.m. to 4 p.m.; the rest of the email supports this warning."},{"q":"What does Doug ask residents NOT to do during the shutdown?","options":["Leave their apartment for the whole day","Run the taps in their unit","Use the lobby washroom","Turn on any extra heaters"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Paragraph two says 'please don't run the taps in your unit during the shutdown, as the pressure needs to stay low for the crew.'"},{"q":"In this email, the word \"patchwork\" is closest in meaning to","options":["a permanent, well-designed solution","an unreliable system made of temporary fixes","a decorative repair to the lobby","a written maintenance schedule"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The new boiler 'should actually be more reliable than the patchwork we've been dealing with all winter,' contrasting reliability with a pieced-together set of temporary fixes."},{"q":"How does Doug appear to feel about the disruption?","options":["Indifferent to how it affects residents","Apologetic and considerate toward residents","Annoyed at residents for complaining","Uncertain whether the work is really needed"],"answer":1,"explanation":"He writes 'I realize this is an inconvenience,' cites the cold snap, gives 'plenty of warning,' and offers to rearrange the date, all signalling an apologetic, considerate tone."},{"q":"What should a resident do if the chosen date is a serious problem for them?","options":["Post a note in the lobby by Wednesday","Call the heating contractor directly","Reply to the email by Friday","Leave their unit for the entire day"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The final paragraph says 'If this date is a serious problem for you, reply to this email by Friday and I'll see what can be arranged.'"},{"q":"When will residents learn that heat and hot water are back to normal?","options":["Through a lobby posting by Wednesday morning","Through a text message on Tuesday night","Through a follow-up email on Friday","Through a notice slipped under each door"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Doug writes he will 'post an update in the lobby by Wednesday morning confirming everything is back to normal.'"}]},{"id":"friend-cabin-weekend-invite","title":"An Invitation to the Lake","instructions":"Read the following email and answer the questions.","passage":"Hey Marco,\n\nLong time no talk! My family's cabin up near Bracebridge is finally open for the season, and a few of us are heading up the weekend of June 21. I'd love for you to come — it's been ages since we did one of these trips.\n\nHere's the plan: drive up Friday evening, spend Saturday on the water, and head back Sunday afternoon. There's a spare room with your name on it, so no need to worry about a tent. Bring a swimsuit, but honestly the lake can still be freezing in June, so pack a hoodie too.\n\nThe only thing I'll ask is that everyone chips in for groceries — probably around forty bucks each — and brings one thing to share for a group dinner. I'm doing a big pot of chili on Saturday night, so maybe you could handle dessert?\n\nThere's no cell service once you're past the highway turnoff, which honestly is half the appeal. Let me know by June 14 if you can make it so I can give the neighbour a final headcount for the boat.\n\nCan't wait,\nJesse","questions":[{"q":"Why is Jesse writing to Marco?","options":["To invite him to a weekend trip at the family cabin","To ask him to help repair the cabin before summer","To sell him a share in a lakeside property","To apologize for missing an earlier trip"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Jesse says the cabin is open and 'I'd love for you to come,' then lays out the plan for the June 21 weekend — a straightforward invitation."},{"q":"What does Jesse ask each guest to contribute?","options":["A tent and camping gear","About forty dollars for groceries plus a dish to share","Gas money for the boat","Their own bedding and towels"],"answer":1,"explanation":"He asks that 'everyone chips in for groceries — probably around forty bucks each — and brings one thing to share for a group dinner.'"},{"q":"In the email, \"chips in\" is closest in meaning to","options":["contributes money toward a shared cost","arrives late to an event","brings snacks to eat on the drive","complains about the arrangements"],"answer":0,"explanation":"'Everyone chips in for groceries — probably around forty bucks each' means each person contributes money toward the shared grocery cost."},{"q":"How does Jesse seem to feel about the lack of cell service at the cabin?","options":["Worried it could be dangerous","Embarrassed about the poor location","Pleased, seeing it as part of the appeal","Determined to get it fixed soon"],"answer":2,"explanation":"He calls the lack of service 'half the appeal,' framing it positively as part of getting away."},{"q":"What specific item does Jesse suggest Marco bring for the group dinner?","options":["A pot of chili","A swimsuit","Dessert","A hoodie"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Jesse is making chili himself and asks, 'maybe you could handle dessert?' for the Saturday dinner."},{"q":"What should Marco do next?","options":["Reserve the boat with the neighbour himself","Let Jesse know by June 14 whether he can come","Pay Jesse forty dollars right away","Drive up on his own on Saturday morning"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Jesse writes 'Let me know by June 14 if you can make it so I can give the neighbour a final headcount for the boat.'"}]},{"id":"community-centre-class-cancellation","title":"Update About Your Pottery Class","instructions":"Read the following email and answer the questions.","passage":"Dear Ms. Osei,\n\nThank you for registering for the Thursday evening Intermediate Pottery class at the Riverbend Community Centre. Unfortunately, I'm writing with some disappointing news. Our instructor, Lena, has had to step away unexpectedly for family reasons, and we haven't been able to find a qualified replacement in time. As a result, we've made the difficult decision to cancel the Thursday session for the upcoming spring term.\n\nI know how much our regulars look forward to this class, and I'm genuinely sorry for the letdown. We do have a couple of options for you. First, there are still three spots open in the Tuesday morning Intermediate class, which follows the same curriculum. If mornings don't work with your schedule, we're happy to issue a full refund to your original payment method within ten business days.\n\nEither way, we'd like to offer you a fifteen-percent discount on any summer-term course as a thank-you for your patience.\n\nCould you let me know your preference by April 3? Just reply to this email or call the front desk. We hope to see you back in the studio soon.\n\nWarm regards,\nHannah Reyes\nPrograms Coordinator","questions":[{"q":"What is the main reason for this email?","options":["To inform Ms. Osei that her pottery class has been cancelled","To remind Ms. Osei that her class fee is overdue","To advertise a new summer pottery program","To ask Ms. Osei to become a volunteer instructor"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Hannah states 'we've made the difficult decision to cancel the Thursday session for the upcoming spring term'; the options and discount all follow from that news."},{"q":"Why was the Thursday class cancelled?","options":["Not enough people had registered","The instructor had to leave for family reasons and no replacement was found","The community centre is closing for renovations","The pottery equipment was damaged"],"answer":1,"explanation":"'Lena has had to step away unexpectedly for family reasons, and we haven't been able to find a qualified replacement in time.'"},{"q":"In this email, \"the letdown\" is closest in meaning to","options":["the disappointment","the extra cost","the scheduling change","the long wait"],"answer":0,"explanation":"'I'm genuinely sorry for the letdown' follows the phrase 'disappointing news,' so it refers to the disappointment of losing the class."},{"q":"What can be inferred about how Hannah feels about the cancellation?","options":["She is relieved to have fewer classes to manage","She is regretful and wants to make it up to registrants","She is confident students won't mind at all","She blames the students for the problem"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Her apology ('genuinely sorry'), the alternative class, the full refund option, and the discount together show regret and a wish to make amends."},{"q":"What is one option offered to Ms. Osei?","options":["A private lesson with a new instructor","A transfer to the Tuesday morning class with the same curriculum","A free summer course of her choice","A voucher for the centre's gift shop"],"answer":1,"explanation":"'There are still three spots open in the Tuesday morning Intermediate class, which follows the same curriculum.'"},{"q":"What is Ms. Osei asked to do next?","options":["Show up to the Tuesday class without confirming","Wait for a second email with more details","Reply or call by April 3 with her preference","Fill out a refund form at the front desk in person"],"answer":2,"explanation":"'Could you let me know your preference by April 3? Just reply to this email or call the front desk.'"}]},{"id":"coworker-shift-swap-request","title":"A Message from a Coworker","instructions":"Read the following email and answer the questions.","passage":"Hi Priya,\n\nI hope your week is going okay. I wanted to reach out before I put in a formal request with Sandeep. My sister's convocation is on Saturday the 18th, and it completely slipped my mind that I'm scheduled to close the store that evening. I'd hate to miss the ceremony, so I'm hoping we can swap.\n\nWould you be willing to take my Saturday closing shift (2 to 10 p.m.) in exchange for one of yours? I'm happy to cover your Sunday opening on the 26th, or the Wednesday evening shift the week after — whichever is easier for you. I know Saturdays are usually busier, so I really appreciate you even considering it.\n\nIf it doesn't work for you, no worries at all — I completely understand, and I'll ask around to see if anyone else can help. Sandeep said any swap needs to be confirmed with him at least a week ahead, so it would help if I could sort this out in the next few days.\n\nLet me know what you think whenever you get a chance. Thanks a million.\n\nCheers,\nDaniel","questions":[{"q":"What is Daniel's main reason for writing?","options":["To ask Priya to swap shifts so he can attend a family event","To complain to Priya about the closing schedule","To tell Priya that Sandeep changed the store hours","To invite Priya to his sister's convocation"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Daniel wants to attend his sister's convocation on the 18th and writes 'I'm hoping we can swap' the Saturday closing shift."},{"q":"Which shift is Daniel asking Priya to take?","options":["The Sunday opening on the 26th","The Wednesday evening shift the following week","The Saturday closing shift from 2 to 10 p.m.","A Monday morning shift"],"answer":2,"explanation":"'Would you be willing to take my Saturday closing shift (2 to 10 p.m.)'; the Sunday and Wednesday shifts are what he offers in return."},{"q":"In this email, the phrase \"slipped my mind\" is closest in meaning to","options":["was forgotten","was cancelled","was rescheduled","was misunderstood"],"answer":0,"explanation":"'It completely slipped my mind that I'm scheduled to close' means he had forgotten about the shift."},{"q":"How does Daniel come across in this message?","options":["Demanding and impatient","Grateful and considerate of Priya's choice","Angry that he has to work weekends","Indifferent about whether Priya agrees"],"answer":1,"explanation":"He thanks her ('really appreciate,' 'Thanks a million'), offers flexible return shifts, and says 'no worries at all' if she can't — grateful and considerate."},{"q":"According to the email, what does Sandeep require for a shift swap?","options":["That both employees fill out a paper form","That the swap be confirmed with him at least a week in advance","That a manager work the closing shift instead","That the swap happen only on weekdays"],"answer":1,"explanation":"'Sandeep said any swap needs to be confirmed with him at least a week ahead.'"},{"q":"What does Daniel ask Priya to do?","options":["Confirm the swap directly with Sandeep herself","Cover his shift without any exchange","Let him know what she thinks when she has a chance","Find another coworker to take the shift"],"answer":2,"explanation":"He closes with 'Let me know what you think whenever you get a chance.'"}]},{"id":"neighbour-fence-repair-letter","title":"A Note from Next Door","instructions":"Read the following letter and answer the questions.","passage":"Dear Tom and Alison,\n\nI hope you're both keeping warm. I'm writing about the wooden fence between our two backyards. After that big windstorm last week, I noticed that three of the posts on the shared section near the maple tree are leaning quite badly, and one panel has come loose entirely. I'm a little worried it could blow over onto someone's car in the alley if we get another gust like that.\n\nSince the fence sits right on the property line, I think it's fair that we share the cost of fixing it. I called a contractor named Wes, who came by yesterday and quoted $640 for the whole repair, materials included. Split down the middle, that's $320 each — which seems very reasonable to me.\n\nBefore I give Wes the go-ahead, though, I wanted to check that you're comfortable with the price and the timing. He said he could start next Thursday if we confirm by Monday.\n\nWould you mind popping a note in my mailbox or texting me at 604-555-0148 to let me know? No rush beyond Monday.\n\nThanks so much,\nGrace (from number 12)","questions":[{"q":"What is the main purpose of Grace's letter?","options":["To propose sharing the cost of repairing the shared fence","To complain about noise coming from the neighbours' yard","To ask the neighbours to remove the maple tree","To report that a car was damaged in the alley"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Grace raises the storm-damaged shared fence and writes 'I think it's fair that we share the cost of fixing it.'"},{"q":"What damage did Grace notice after the windstorm?","options":["The maple tree fell across the alley","Three posts are leaning and one panel has come loose","The entire fence blew down onto a car","The gate lock was broken off"],"answer":1,"explanation":"'Three of the posts on the shared section near the maple tree are leaning quite badly, and one panel has come loose entirely.'"},{"q":"In this letter, \"give Wes the go-ahead\" is closest in meaning to","options":["pay Wes in advance","give Wes permission to start the work","ask Wes for a lower price","cancel the appointment with Wes"],"answer":1,"explanation":"'Before I give Wes the go-ahead' is followed by checking the neighbours are comfortable, so it means giving him permission to proceed."},{"q":"What can be inferred about Grace's attitude toward the neighbours?","options":["She is resentful and expects them to pay everything","She is fair-minded and wants their agreement before proceeding","She is suspicious that they caused the damage","She is uninterested in fixing the fence at all"],"answer":1,"explanation":"She proposes an even split, calls it 'fair' and 'reasonable,' and checks 'that you're comfortable' before booking Wes — a fair, cooperative attitude."},{"q":"How much is Grace asking each household to pay?","options":["$640","$320","$160","The full amount, to be decided later"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The quote is $640 total, 'Split down the middle, that's $320 each.'"},{"q":"What does Grace ask the neighbours to do?","options":["Call the contractor Wes directly","Leave a note or text her by Monday","Meet her in the alley on Thursday","Send the payment before the work begins"],"answer":1,"explanation":"'Would you mind popping a note in my mailbox or texting me at 604-555-0148 to let me know? No rush beyond Monday.'"}]},{"id":"service-internet-outage-followup","title":"Follow-Up on Your Service Issue","instructions":"Read the following email and answer the questions.","passage":"Hello Mr. Cardinal,\n\nThank you for your patience while we looked into the repeated internet dropouts you reported at your home on Willow Bend Road. I'm following up personally because I know how frustrating an unstable connection can be, especially when you mentioned you rely on it for your remote work.\n\nOur technicians traced the problem to an aging junction box on your street that has been affecting several households, not just yours. The good news is that this explains why restarting your modem never solved anything — the fault was never inside your home. A crew is scheduled to replace the box on Thursday, June 5, and we expect the work to take about three hours, likely in the morning.\n\nDuring that window, your service will be down completely, but once the new box is in, your connection should be noticeably steadier. As an apology for the trouble over the past month, we've applied a one-time credit of $45 to your account, which you'll see on your next bill.\n\nThere's nothing you need to do on your end, but if you're still seeing dropouts after June 5, please reply to this email and I'll escalate it right away.\n\nSincerely,\nOmar Haddad\nCustomer Care Team","questions":[{"q":"What is the main purpose of this email?","options":["To explain the cause of the customer's internet problem and the planned fix","To sell Mr. Cardinal a faster internet plan","To inform Mr. Cardinal that his account is overdue","To ask Mr. Cardinal to return his modem"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Omar identifies the faulty junction box as the cause and describes the scheduled June 5 repair and a credit — an explanation and fix."},{"q":"According to the email, what was causing the internet dropouts?","options":["A defective modem inside the home","An aging junction box on the street affecting several homes","Too many devices connected at once","Bad weather along Willow Bend Road"],"answer":1,"explanation":"'Our technicians traced the problem to an aging junction box on your street that has been affecting several households,' and the fault 'was never inside your home.'"},{"q":"In this email, \"escalate it\" is closest in meaning to","options":["raise the issue to a higher priority for action","increase the monthly bill","send a technician to install a new modem","close the account permanently"],"answer":0,"explanation":"'If you're still seeing dropouts after June 5, please reply... and I'll escalate it right away' means he will raise it to a higher priority for urgent action."},{"q":"What can be inferred about how Omar wants the customer to feel?","options":["Blamed for not restarting the modem correctly","Reassured that the company takes the problem seriously","Encouraged to switch to a competitor","Uncertain about whether the issue will be fixed"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The personal follow-up, clear diagnosis, $45 apology credit, and offer to escalate are all aimed at reassuring the customer."},{"q":"What compensation has the company provided?","options":["A free upgrade to a faster plan","A one-time $45 credit on the next bill","A replacement modem at no charge","Two months of free service"],"answer":1,"explanation":"'We've applied a one-time credit of $45 to your account, which you'll see on your next bill.'"},{"q":"What is Mr. Cardinal advised to do?","options":["Restart his modem again before June 5","Nothing for now, but reply if dropouts continue after June 5","Call a technician to schedule the box replacement","Unplug his equipment during the repair window"],"answer":1,"explanation":"'There's nothing you need to do on your end, but if you're still seeing dropouts after June 5, please reply to this email.'"}]}],"diagram":[{"id":"riverside-swim-timetable","title":"Riverside Community Centre — Swim Schedule","instructions":"Read the swim timetable and the email. Answer the questions based on both.","passage":"RIVERSIDE COMMUNITY CENTRE — POOL SCHEDULE (Fall Session)\nAll drop-in swims are held in the main pool unless noted.\n\n----------------------------------------------------------\nMONDAY\n  6:00–7:30 AM   Lane Swim (adults)\n  9:00–10:30 AM  Aqua Fit (adults 55+)\n  4:00–5:30 PM   Family Swim\n  7:00–8:30 PM   Lane Swim (adults)\n\nWEDNESDAY\n  6:00–7:30 AM   Lane Swim (adults)\n  10:00–11:00 AM Parent & Tot (leisure pool)\n  5:30–7:00 PM   Family Swim\n  7:30–9:00 PM   Lane Swim (adults)\n\nSATURDAY\n  8:00–9:30 AM   Lane Swim (adults)\n  10:00–11:30 AM Family Swim\n  12:00–1:30 PM  Public Swim (all ages)\n  2:00–3:30 PM   Parent & Tot (leisure pool)\n----------------------------------------------------------\n\nFEES (per drop-in visit):\n  Adult ............... $6.50\n  Senior (55+) ........ $4.00\n  Child (2–12) ........ $3.25\n  Family (up to 5) .... $14.00\n\nNOTES:\n- Children under 8 must be within arm's reach of an adult at all times.\n- Parent & Tot is for caregivers with children under 3.\n- A 10-visit pass saves 15% off the drop-in rate.\n\n---\n\nHi there,\n\nI'm hoping to bring my two kids swimming this weekend. My daughter is 6 and my son is 18 months old. My husband works Saturday mornings, so it would just be me with both of them. I'd love something where the little one can splash around in shallow water, but I also want my daughter to have space to actually swim a bit.\n\nSince I'll be on my own, I'm a little nervous about keeping an eye on both of them at once. I probably can't manage the very early slots. Could you let me know which sessions might work and roughly what it would cost me for the three of us? I might come regularly, so if there's a way to save money over time, I'd like to hear about it.\n\nThanks so much,\nPriya","questions":[{"q":"Priya wants a session where her 18-month-old can splash in shallow water. Which listed program is specifically designed for a child that age?","options":["Family Swim","Parent & Tot","Public Swim","Aqua Fit"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The notes state Parent & Tot is for caregivers with children under 3, and it is held in the leisure pool — suitable for an 18-month-old."},{"q":"Given that she can only come on the weekend and cannot manage the earliest slot, which single session offers both a family-friendly swim and space for her daughter to swim?","options":["Saturday 8:00–9:30 AM Lane Swim","Saturday 10:00–11:30 AM Family Swim","Saturday 2:00–3:30 PM Parent & Tot","Wednesday 5:30–7:00 PM Family Swim"],"answer":1,"explanation":"She can only come on weekends, ruling out Wednesday. The Saturday 8:00 AM slot is Lane Swim (adults only) and is also the early slot she wants to avoid. The Saturday 10:00–11:30 AM Family Swim fits her availability and lets her daughter swim."},{"q":"If Priya pays the regular drop-in rate for herself and both children separately, what would one visit cost?","options":["$13.00","$12.75","$14.00","$9.75"],"answer":3,"explanation":"One adult is $6.50. The Child rate ($3.25) applies to ages 2–12, so her 6-year-old daughter is $3.25, while her 18-month-old son is under 2 and not charged. Total: $6.50 + $3.25 = $9.75."},{"q":"What is the concern the schedule raises about Priya supervising her 6-year-old?","options":["Children under 8 must be within arm's reach of an adult at all times","Children under 12 are not allowed at Family Swim","A parent may only supervise one child at a time","Children must pass a swim test before entering the main pool"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The notes state children under 8 must be within arm's reach of an adult at all times, which directly bears on her worry about watching a 6-year-old and a toddler alone."},{"q":"Priya mentions she might come regularly and wants to save money. What should you tell her?","options":["Seniors receive a discounted rate","A 10-visit pass saves 15% off the drop-in rate","Family Swim is free after the first visit","Weekend swims are half price"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The notes state a 10-visit pass saves 15% off the drop-in rate — the money-saving option relevant to a regular visitor."}]},{"id":"maple-heights-moving-fees","title":"Maple Heights Apartments — Move-In Information","instructions":"Read the building's move-in information sheet and the tenant's email. Answer the questions using both.","passage":"MAPLE HEIGHTS APARTMENTS — NEW TENANT MOVE-IN GUIDE\n\n========================================\nELEVATOR BOOKING (for moving furniture)\n  Must be booked at least 3 business days in advance.\n  Available time blocks (Mon–Sat only):\n    Block A ... 9:00 AM – 12:00 PM\n    Block B ... 12:30 PM – 3:30 PM\n    Block C ... 4:00 PM – 7:00 PM\n  No elevator bookings on Sundays or statutory holidays.\n========================================\n\nFEES & DEPOSITS\n  Elevator booking deposit ....... $150 (refundable)\n  Key fob (per fob) .............. $25\n  Parking permit (visitor) ....... $10 / day\n  Late move-in fee (after 7 PM) .. $75\n\nWHAT TO BRING ON MOVE-IN DAY\n  - Signed lease agreement\n  - Void cheque or pre-authorized payment form\n  - Two pieces of government-issued photo ID\n  - Proof of tenant insurance\n\nOFFICE HOURS\n  Monday–Friday .... 9:00 AM – 5:00 PM\n  Saturday ......... 10:00 AM – 2:00 PM\n  Sunday ........... Closed\n\nNOTE: The elevator deposit is returned within 5 business days after staff confirm no damage to shared hallways or the elevator.\n\n---\n\nHello,\n\nWe're moving into unit 704 and I want to make sure I book everything correctly. Our movers are only available in the afternoon — they told us they'd arrive around 1:00 PM and would need about two and a half hours. I'd like to reserve the elevator for that window.\n\nWe're planning the move for Saturday the 18th. Also, my partner and I will each need a key fob, and we'll have a moving truck plus my brother's car that day, so he'll need somewhere to park. Could you confirm what we owe up front and what documents to bring? I want to avoid any surprise charges. One more thing — I've heard the elevator deposit comes back to us; is that right?\n\nThanks,\nDaniel","questions":[{"q":"Daniel's movers arrive at 1:00 PM and need about two and a half hours. Which elevator block should he book?","options":["Block A (9:00 AM – 12:00 PM)","Block B (12:30 PM – 3:30 PM)","Block C (4:00 PM – 7:00 PM)","Any block, since all are three hours long"],"answer":1,"explanation":"A 1:00 PM start lasting about 2.5 hours runs to roughly 3:30 PM, fitting entirely within Block B (12:30–3:30 PM). Block A ends at noon and Block C does not start until 4:00 PM."},{"q":"Daniel plans to move on Saturday the 18th. What must he do about the elevator booking timing?","options":["Book it on the same day as the move","Book it at least 3 business days in advance","Book it only through the Sunday office","No booking is needed for afternoon moves"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The sheet states the elevator must be booked at least 3 business days in advance. Saturday moves are permitted, but advance booking is still required."},{"q":"For the two key fobs Daniel and his partner need, what is the total cost?","options":["$25","$50","$75","$10"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Key fobs are $25 each, so two fobs cost $50."},{"q":"Daniel's brother will bring a car and needs to park for the day. What will that cost, and under what item?","options":["$75 late move-in fee","$150 elevator deposit","$10 for a one-day visitor parking permit","Nothing — visitor parking is free"],"answer":2,"explanation":"A visitor parking permit is $10 per day, which covers the brother's car for the move day."},{"q":"Daniel asks whether the elevator deposit comes back. What is the correct response?","options":["No, the $150 deposit is non-refundable","Yes, it is returned within 5 business days if there is no damage","Yes, but only if he books a weekday block","It is refunded immediately at the end of the move"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The note states the $150 deposit is refundable and returned within 5 business days after staff confirm there is no damage to shared hallways or the elevator."}]},{"id":"harvest-workshop-flyer","title":"Greenfield Library — Fall Workshop Series","instructions":"Read the workshop flyer and the message. Answer the questions using both.","passage":"GREENFIELD PUBLIC LIBRARY — FALL WORKSHOP SERIES\nAll workshops held in the Community Room (2nd floor). Registration required.\n\n******************************************\n1) RESUME & COVER LETTER CLINIC\n   Tuesdays, 6:30–8:00 PM\n   Oct 7, 14, 21 (3 sessions)\n   Cost: FREE   |   Bring: a draft resume (printed)\n\n2) INTRO TO SMARTPHONE PHOTOGRAPHY\n   Thursdays, 2:00–3:30 PM\n   Oct 9 & 16 (2 sessions)\n   Cost: $15   |   Bring: your own smartphone\n\n3) BEGINNER CONVERSATION FRENCH\n   Saturdays, 10:00–11:30 AM\n   Oct 4 – Nov 8 (6 sessions)\n   Cost: $40   |   Bring: notebook & pen\n\n4) HOME BUDGETING BASICS\n   Wednesdays, 7:00–8:30 PM\n   Oct 8 & 15 (2 sessions)\n   Cost: $10   |   Bring: a calculator\n******************************************\n\nREGISTRATION NOTES:\n- Register online or at the front desk up to 2 days before the first session.\n- A library card is required to register for any workshop.\n- Paid workshops: fees are due at registration and are non-refundable after the first session.\n- Seating is limited to 12 participants per workshop.\n\n---\n\nHi,\n\nI just moved to Greenfield and I'm trying to settle in. I'm currently job hunting, so anything that helps me polish my application materials would be really useful — and free would be a bonus while I'm between paycheques. I can only do evenings during the week, since I look after my niece on weekends and my afternoons are taken up with appointments this month.\n\nI don't have a library card yet — is that going to be a problem? Also, I want to make sure I sign up in time. If a session I want starts on a certain date, how late can I leave it before registering? Thanks for any guidance.\n\nBest,\nMarcus","questions":[{"q":"Based on Marcus's goals and availability, which workshop best fits him?","options":["Intro to Smartphone Photography","Resume & Cover Letter Clinic","Beginner Conversation French","Home Budgeting Basics"],"answer":1,"explanation":"He wants help with job application materials, so the Resume & Cover Letter Clinic fits. It is free (the bonus he mentions) and runs Tuesday evenings, matching his weekday-evening availability."},{"q":"Why can Marcus NOT attend Intro to Smartphone Photography?","options":["It costs $15, which he cannot afford","It is held Thursday afternoons, when he has appointments","It requires equipment he does not own","It is only open to library members over 55"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The photography workshop runs Thursdays 2:00–3:30 PM, but Marcus says his weekday afternoons are taken up with appointments this month, so he can only do evenings."},{"q":"What must Marcus bring to the workshop that suits him?","options":["A calculator","A printed draft resume","His own smartphone","A notebook and pen"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The Resume & Cover Letter Clinic lists 'Bring: a draft resume (printed).'"},{"q":"Marcus does not yet have a library card. What should he be told?","options":["A library card is required to register for any workshop","Library cards are only needed for paid workshops","He can register now and get a card later","Non-members pay a $5 surcharge instead"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The registration notes state a library card is required to register for any workshop, so he will need to get one first."},{"q":"Marcus asks how late he can leave registration. What is the deadline relative to a workshop's start?","options":["Up to the day the first session begins","Up to 2 days before the first session","Up to 1 week before the first session","There is no deadline; walk-ins are welcome"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Registration is open online or at the front desk up to 2 days before the first session."}]},{"id":"go-transit-connection","title":"Regional Transit — Weekday Bus Schedule","instructions":"Read the bus schedule and the traveller's message. Answer the questions using both.","passage":"LAKESHORE REGIONAL TRANSIT — ROUTE 12 (WEEKDAYS)\nDirection: Downtown Terminal → Airport (northbound)\nAll times are departures.\n\n+---------------------------------------------------------------+\n| Downtown | Elm St | Hospital | Mall Loop | Airport |\n|  Terminal|        |          |           |         |\n|----------|--------|----------|-----------|---------|\n|  6:15 AM | 6:28   | 6:41     |  6:55     | 7:20    |\n|  7:00 AM | 7:13   | 7:26     |  7:40     | 8:05    |\n|  7:45 AM | 7:58   | 8:11     |  8:25     | 8:50    |\n|  8:30 AM | 8:43   | 8:56     |  9:10     | 9:35    |\n|  9:30 AM | 9:43   | 9:56     | 10:10     | 10:35   |\n+---------------------------------------------------------------+\n\nFARES (one way):\n  Adult ................ $5.75\n  Senior/Youth ......... $3.90\n  Child (under 5) ...... Free\n  Day Pass ............. $12.50 (unlimited rides, one day)\n\nNOTES:\n- Exact change or a tap card is required; drivers cannot make change.\n- The 6:15 AM and 7:00 AM trips are express and do NOT stop at Elm St or Mall Loop... they still pass these stops but do not pick up or drop off.\n- Bicycles are permitted on the front rack, first come first served (2 per bus).\n\n---\n\nHi,\n\nI have a flight on a weekday and I need to be at the airport no later than 9:15 AM to leave enough time to check in. I'll be getting on at the Mall Loop stop, since that's closest to my place. I'd rather not arrive super early and sit around forever, so I want the latest bus that still gets me there in time.\n\nI'll be travelling with my 4-year-old, and I'm planning to make just this one trip up — no return the same day. I want to bring my folding bike too, if that's allowed. Could you help me figure out the right departure and what I'll pay? Thanks!\n\nJordan","questions":[{"q":"Jordan boards at Mall Loop and must reach the airport no later than 9:15 AM, taking the latest possible bus. Which departure works?","options":["The bus reaching the airport at 8:50 AM (Mall Loop 8:25)","The bus reaching the airport at 9:35 AM (Mall Loop 9:10)","The bus reaching the airport at 8:05 AM (Mall Loop 7:40)","The bus reaching the airport at 7:20 AM (Mall Loop 6:55)"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The 8:25 AM Mall Loop departure arrives at the airport at 8:50 AM, before the 9:15 deadline. The next bus (Mall Loop 9:10, airport 9:35) arrives too late, so 8:50 is the latest that works."},{"q":"Why can Jordan NOT take the 6:15 AM or 7:00 AM trips from Mall Loop?","options":["Those trips are full during rush hour","Those trips are express and do not pick up at Mall Loop","Those trips do not run on weekdays","Those trips cost extra as express service"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The note says the 6:15 and 7:00 AM express trips do not stop to pick up or drop off at Elm St or Mall Loop, so Jordan cannot board there."},{"q":"What will Jordan pay in fares for this one-way trip?","options":["$11.50 (two adults)","$5.75 (one adult; the child is free)","$9.65 (adult plus youth)","$12.50 (day pass)"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Jordan is one adult ($5.75). The 4-year-old is a child under 5, who rides free. Since it is one trip only, the day pass is unnecessary."},{"q":"Jordan wants to bring a folding bike. What does the schedule say?","options":["Bikes are not allowed on this route","Bicycles are permitted on the front rack, first come first served, 2 per bus","Bikes require a reservation 24 hours ahead","Only folding bikes stored as carry-on are allowed"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The note states bicycles are permitted on the front rack, first come first served, with 2 per bus."},{"q":"What does Jordan need to know about paying the fare on board?","options":["Fares can be paid by phone app only","Drivers accept credit cards at the door","Exact change or a tap card is required; drivers cannot make change","Cash is not accepted at any time"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The note specifies exact change or a tap card is required because drivers cannot make change."}]},{"id":"farmers-market-vendor-form","title":"Bridgewater Farmers' Market — Vendor Registration","instructions":"Read the vendor registration information and the applicant's email. Answer the questions using both.","passage":"BRIDGEWATER FARMERS' MARKET — 2026 VENDOR REGISTRATION\nSaturdays, 8:00 AM – 1:00 PM | Riverside Park | May–October\n\n############################################\nSTALL OPTIONS (per market day)\n  Half stall (5' x 5') ......... $25\n  Full stall (10' x 10') ....... $40\n  Full stall + power outlet .... $55\n  Food truck spot .............. $70\n\nSEASON PASS (all 24 markets)\n  Half stall ................... $480\n  Full stall ................... $780\n############################################\n\nWHAT VENDORS MUST PROVIDE\n  - Their own tent, tables, and weights (min. 25 lb per leg)\n  - Valid liability insurance ($2 million minimum)\n  - Food vendors: a copy of their public health permit\n\nSETUP & RULES\n  - Setup begins at 6:30 AM; vehicles must be off the field by 7:30 AM.\n  - Stalls must be staffed until 1:00 PM; no early teardown.\n  - Power outlets are limited — reserve in advance.\n  - Cancellations with less than 48 hours' notice forfeit the day's fee.\n\nHOW TO APPLY\n  Submit the online form and payment by Wednesday for that Saturday's market.\n\n---\n\nHello,\n\nI make and sell hot soups and stews, so I'll be running a small electric warmer at my table — I'll definitely need access to power. I'm not a food truck; I just use a regular canopy tent and a couple of tables. I'd like to try a single Saturday first to see how it goes before committing to the whole season.\n\nI already have my tent and weights, and I carry $2 million liability insurance. Since I'm preparing food, I assume there's something extra I need to submit? Also, I run a tight schedule on Saturday mornings — what's the latest I can have my vehicle on the field, and when do I need to get everything submitted to make it into this Saturday's market? Thanks!\n\nRosa","questions":[{"q":"Rosa needs power for her warmer and uses a regular tent (not a food truck), trying just one day. Which option fits and what does it cost?","options":["Food truck spot — $70","Full stall + power outlet — $55","Full stall season pass — $780","Half stall — $25"],"answer":1,"explanation":"She is not a food truck and needs a power outlet for a single day. The full stall with power outlet at $55 per market day fits; the food truck spot and season passes do not apply, and the half stall has no power."},{"q":"As a food vendor, what extra document must Rosa submit?","options":["A copy of her public health permit","A business number certificate","A second insurance policy","A signed waiver of liability"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The requirements state food vendors must provide a copy of their public health permit, in addition to insurance."},{"q":"What is the latest Rosa's vehicle can be on the field?","options":["6:30 AM","7:30 AM","8:00 AM","1:00 PM"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Setup begins at 6:30 AM, but the rules state vehicles must be off the field by 7:30 AM."},{"q":"By when must Rosa submit her form and payment to be in this Saturday's market?","options":["The Friday before","By Wednesday for that Saturday's market","At least 48 hours before setup","On the market morning at 6:30 AM"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The application instructions state the online form and payment are due by Wednesday for that Saturday's market."},{"q":"Rosa mentions she needs power. What extra step does the schedule require for that?","options":["Bring her own generator","Reserve the power outlet in advance","Pay a $15 electricity deposit on site","Apply for a separate food truck spot"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The rules note that power outlets are limited and must be reserved in advance."}]}],"information":[{"id":"community-garden-program","title":"The Riverside Community Garden Program","instructions":"Read the following article about a community garden program. Then answer the questions below. For each question, decide which paragraph (A, B, C, or D) gives the information. If the information is not given in any paragraph, choose \"This information is not given.\"","passage":"A) The Riverside Community Garden began nine years ago when a group of neighbours transformed a vacant lot behind the local recreation centre into a shared growing space. What started as a dozen raised beds has since expanded to more than eighty plots, along with a small orchard and a greenhouse donated by a regional hardware chain. The garden is now managed by a volunteer committee that meets on the first Tuesday of each month. Anyone living within the Riverside neighbourhood may apply for a plot, though newcomers are placed on a waiting list that typically clears within one growing season.\n\nB) Renting a plot costs forty dollars per year, which covers water, shared tools, and a supply of compost delivered each spring. Gardeners are expected to keep their plots reasonably tidy and to contribute four hours of communal work over the season, such as weeding the shared pathways or helping at the fall harvest festival. Members who leave a plot untended for more than three weeks without notice may have it reassigned to someone on the waiting list. Payment is due by the end of April, and a limited number of fee waivers are available for households facing financial hardship.\n\nC) The greenhouse has allowed the garden to extend its season considerably. Seedlings are started there in March, well before the last frost, and are later distributed to members at cost. During the coldest months, the greenhouse hosts free workshops on topics ranging from seed saving to composting. Last winter, a retired botanist led a popular six-week series on growing vegetables in containers, which drew participants from several surrounding neighbourhoods. The committee hopes to install solar panels to heat the greenhouse more efficiently, but funding has not yet been secured.\n\nD) Beyond growing food, the garden has become a social hub. A shaded seating area near the orchard is a gathering spot on summer evenings, and the annual harvest festival in September draws hundreds of visitors for music, a produce sale, and a children's scavenger hunt. Surplus vegetables that members cannot use are donated to a nearby food bank; last year the garden contributed over six hundred kilograms of fresh produce. Several local schools also bring classes to tour the garden in the spring as part of their science curriculum.","questions":[{"q":"The garden donates leftover vegetables to a food bank.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Paragraph D states that surplus vegetables members cannot use are donated to a nearby food bank."},{"q":"There is a cost for renting a plot for the year.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Paragraph B says renting a plot costs forty dollars per year."},{"q":"A frost-free structure lets the garden start growing earlier in the year.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Paragraph C explains that the greenhouse lets seedlings be started in March, well before the last frost, extending the season."},{"q":"The garden has grown much larger than it originally was.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Paragraph A describes how the garden grew from a dozen raised beds to more than eighty plots."},{"q":"Members must do a set number of hours of shared work each season.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Paragraph B states gardeners must contribute four hours of communal work over the season."},{"q":"An educational session on container gardening attracted people from outside the neighbourhood.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Paragraph C describes a retired botanist's six-week series on growing vegetables in containers that drew participants from several surrounding neighbourhoods."},{"q":"The garden holds an event in the autumn that many people attend.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Paragraph D describes the September harvest festival that draws hundreds of visitors; only Paragraph D states the attendance."},{"q":"The committee plans to raise plot fees next year.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":4,"explanation":"No paragraph mentions any plan to raise fees; the forty-dollar fee is stated but no increase is discussed."}]},{"id":"winter-transit-service","title":"Changes to City Winter Transit Service","instructions":"Read the following notice about winter transit service. Then answer the questions below. For each question, decide which paragraph (A, B, C, or D) gives the information. If the information is not given in any paragraph, choose \"This information is not given.\"","passage":"A) Beginning December 1, the city transit authority will introduce its seasonal winter schedule across all bus and light-rail routes. The most noticeable change is the addition of extra buses on the three busiest downtown corridors during morning and evening rush hours, a response to the crowding riders reported last winter. Frequency on these routes will improve from every twelve minutes to every eight minutes. Routes serving suburban areas will keep their current timetables, though riders are advised that snow conditions may cause occasional delays that are difficult to predict.\n\nB) To help buses run reliably in poor weather, the authority has expanded its fleet of snow-clearing vehicles and will prioritize plowing along major transit corridors before residential streets. A new online map, updated every fifteen minutes, will let riders see which routes are experiencing delays and by roughly how long. The authority encourages passengers to check the map before leaving home during snowstorms. In the event of a severe storm, certain hillside routes may be suspended entirely for safety reasons, with replacement service provided along flatter alternative streets.\n\nC) Fares will remain unchanged this winter, but the authority is expanding its discount programs. Seniors and post-secondary students can now purchase a monthly pass at half price, and a new low-income pass offers a forty percent reduction for eligible households. Applications for the low-income pass require proof of address and income and can be submitted online or at any customer service centre. The authority notes that the popular day pass, which allows unlimited travel for twenty-four hours, will now also be valid on the airport express route.\n\nD) Heated shelters will be installed at twenty of the network's busiest stops before the end of November, each equipped with a real-time arrival display and improved lighting. The authority selected these locations based on ridership data and the number of transfers made at each stop. Additional shelters are planned for the following winter, pending budget approval. Riders can suggest priority locations for future shelters through a feedback form on the authority's website or by calling its customer information line.","questions":[{"q":"Some routes may be shut down completely during a bad storm.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Paragraph B says certain hillside routes may be suspended entirely for safety reasons in a severe storm."},{"q":"The price of a single ride will not change this winter.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Paragraph C states fares will remain unchanged this winter."},{"q":"Buses will come more often on the busiest downtown routes at peak times.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Paragraph A describes improved frequency from every twelve to every eight minutes on the busiest downtown corridors during rush hours."},{"q":"Warm waiting areas will be added at selected stops.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Paragraph D describes heated shelters being installed at twenty of the busiest stops."},{"q":"Riders can check current delays using an online tool.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Paragraph B describes an online map, updated every fifteen minutes, showing which routes are delayed."},{"q":"A pass with a large discount is available to households that qualify by income.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Paragraph C describes the new low-income pass with a forty percent reduction for eligible households."},{"q":"Riders can propose where future shelters should be placed.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Paragraph D says riders can suggest priority locations for future shelters through a feedback form or by phone."},{"q":"The transit authority will hire additional drivers for the winter season.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":4,"explanation":"No paragraph mentions hiring drivers; extra buses and snow-clearing vehicles are noted, but not additional staff."}]},{"id":"apartment-building-profiles","title":"Four Rental Buildings in the Maple Heights Area","instructions":"Read the following profiles of four rental buildings. Then answer the questions below. For each question, decide which paragraph (A, B, C, or D) gives the information. If the information is not given in any paragraph, choose \"This information is not given.\"","passage":"A) The Beckett is a twelve-storey building close to the Maple Heights transit station, popular with commuters who work downtown. Its one- and two-bedroom units were fully renovated three years ago, with new appliances and large windows. Rent includes heat and water, but tenants pay for their own electricity and internet. The building has an on-site laundry room on every third floor and a small fitness area in the basement. Pets are not permitted, and the waiting list for two-bedroom units is currently several months long.\n\nB) Cedar Court is a low-rise complex of townhouse-style units arranged around a shared courtyard, making it a favourite among families. Each unit has a private entrance and a small fenced yard, and the courtyard contains a playground and a community garden plot available to residents. Parking is included at no extra cost, with one space per unit and visitor spots near the entrance. The building is a fifteen-minute walk from an elementary school and a grocery store. Cedar Court welcomes pets, though a refundable deposit is required.\n\nC) The Aldergrove markets itself to students and young professionals, offering compact studio and one-bedroom apartments at some of the lowest rents in the neighbourhood. Units are furnished, which appeals to tenants who plan to stay for only a year or two. The building provides high-speed internet in the monthly rent and has a shared rooftop lounge with seating and a barbecue. There is no dedicated parking, but the building sits directly on a major bus line. Leases as short as four months are available, which is unusual for the area.\n\nD) Sterling House is the newest of the four, having opened last spring. It features a mix of one-, two-, and three-bedroom suites with in-unit laundry and energy-efficient heating. Amenities include an underground parking garage, a party room residents can book for events, and a secure package room for deliveries. Rent is the highest in the neighbourhood, but the building offers a discount to tenants who sign a two-year lease. A concierge is on duty from early morning until late evening, seven days a week.","questions":[{"q":"This building offers furnished apartments.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Paragraph C says The Aldergrove's units are furnished."},{"q":"This building gives a price reduction to tenants who commit to a longer lease.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Paragraph D says Sterling House offers a discount to tenants who sign a two-year lease."},{"q":"This building is especially convenient for people who travel downtown for work.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Paragraph A describes The Beckett as popular with commuters who work downtown and close to the transit station."},{"q":"This building includes a private yard with each unit.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Paragraph B says each Cedar Court unit has a small fenced yard."},{"q":"This building does not allow pets.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Paragraph A states pets are not permitted at The Beckett."},{"q":"This building allows tenants to sign unusually short leases.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Paragraph C notes leases as short as four months are available at The Aldergrove, which is unusual for the area."},{"q":"This building has staff available on site during most of the day.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Paragraph D describes a concierge on duty from early morning until late evening at Sterling House."},{"q":"This building charges tenants a monthly fee for using the parking garage.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":4,"explanation":"No paragraph mentions a monthly parking fee; Sterling House's garage is described but no separate charge for it is stated."}]},{"id":"workplace-wellness-report","title":"Annual Workplace Wellness Report","instructions":"Read the following summary of a company's wellness report. Then answer the questions below. For each question, decide which paragraph (A, B, C, or D) gives the information. If the information is not given in any paragraph, choose \"This information is not given.\"","passage":"A) This year's employee wellness survey drew responses from just over eighty percent of staff, the highest participation rate since the program began. Overall satisfaction with the workplace rose slightly compared with last year, with employees pointing to the flexible work arrangements introduced in the spring as a major factor. However, the survey also revealed that many employees feel they receive too little feedback on their day-to-day performance, an issue the management team has committed to addressing over the coming year through more regular check-ins.\n\nB) The report highlights a marked increase in the use of the company's mental health benefits. The confidential counselling service, which offers a set number of free sessions per year, was accessed by nearly a quarter of staff, up from fifteen percent the previous year. The wellness committee attributes this rise partly to a campaign that reduced the stigma of seeking help and made the booking process simpler. The company plans to increase the number of covered sessions next year in response to the growing demand.\n\nC) Physical health initiatives saw mixed results. The subsidized gym membership remained popular, but attendance at the lunchtime fitness classes declined, which organizers believe is because many employees now work from home two or three days a week. In response, the company will move several classes online and offer them at different times of day. A new standing-desk program, allowing employees to request adjustable desks at no cost, was launched in the fall and has already received more than two hundred requests.\n\nD) Finally, the report addresses workplace social connection, which some employees said had weakened with the shift to hybrid work. To help, the company reintroduced monthly team lunches and created several interest-based clubs, from a book club to a cycling group. Attendance at these events has been strong, though the report cautions that participation is uneven across departments. The wellness committee will survey staff again in six months to measure whether these efforts have improved the sense of community at work.","questions":[{"q":"More employees used the counselling service than in the previous year.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Paragraph B reports counselling use rose from fifteen percent to nearly a quarter of staff."},{"q":"Employees said they want more feedback about their performance.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Paragraph A notes employees feel they receive too little feedback on their day-to-day performance."},{"q":"The company introduced clubs based on shared interests.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Paragraph D describes interest-based clubs such as a book club and a cycling group."},{"q":"Fewer people attended midday exercise classes than before.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Paragraph C says attendance at the lunchtime fitness classes declined."},{"q":"The survey had record participation this year.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Paragraph A states this was the highest participation rate since the program began."},{"q":"The company will offer more covered counselling sessions next year.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Paragraph B says the company plans to increase the number of covered sessions next year."},{"q":"A program lets staff request adjustable desks for free.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Paragraph C describes the standing-desk program that lets employees request adjustable desks at no cost."},{"q":"The company gave employees a cash bonus for completing the survey.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":4,"explanation":"No paragraph mentions any cash bonus or incentive for completing the survey."}]},{"id":"provincial-park-guide","title":"A Visitor's Guide to Pinewood Provincial Park","instructions":"Read the following guide to a provincial park. Then answer the questions below. For each question, decide which paragraph (A, B, C, or D) gives the information. If the information is not given in any paragraph, choose \"This information is not given.\"","passage":"A) Pinewood Provincial Park covers a large area of forest and lakeshore about two hours north of the city. The park is open year-round, but its services vary by season. From May to October, the main gate is staffed daily, and visitors pay a daily vehicle fee or use an annual pass valid at all provincial parks. In the off-season, the gate is unstaffed and entry is free, though most facilities are closed and only a few trails are maintained. A visitor centre near the entrance offers maps, exhibits on local wildlife, and washrooms.\n\nB) The park has three campgrounds, together offering more than two hundred sites. The largest, Birch Bay, has electrical hookups and is suitable for trailers and recreational vehicles, while the smaller Loon Point campground is reserved for tents only and appeals to visitors seeking a quieter stay. Reservations open five months in advance and are strongly recommended for summer weekends, which fill quickly. A limited number of walk-in sites are held back for visitors who arrive without a booking, but these cannot be guaranteed during peak periods.\n\nC) Pinewood is known for its extensive trail network, with routes ranging from a short, wheelchair-accessible boardwalk around a marsh to a challenging full-day hike up Ridge Mountain. Trail maps colour-code routes by difficulty, and signs at each trailhead estimate the time required. Cyclists are welcome on designated multi-use trails but must yield to hikers. During spring, some lower trails may be closed temporarily due to flooding, and visitors are asked to check current conditions at the visitor centre before setting out.\n\nD) A range of activities draws visitors throughout the warmer months. Canoes and kayaks can be rented by the hour or day at the main beach, where a supervised swimming area operates in July and August. The park runs guided nature walks on weekends, led by staff naturalists, as well as evening programs at the outdoor amphitheatre. Fishing is permitted with a valid provincial licence, and the park store near Birch Bay sells basic supplies, firewood, and snacks. Alcohol is prohibited in day-use areas at all times.","questions":[{"q":"One campground is set aside only for tents.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Paragraph B says the Loon Point campground is reserved for tents only."},{"q":"Visitors can rent boats near the beach.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Paragraph D says canoes and kayaks can be rented at the main beach."},{"q":"Entry to the park is free during part of the year.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Paragraph A states that in the off-season the gate is unstaffed and entry is free."},{"q":"Some trails may be closed in spring because of water.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Paragraph C notes some lower trails may be closed temporarily due to flooding in spring."},{"q":"Campsite bookings can be made several months ahead of time.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Paragraph B says reservations open five months in advance."},{"q":"There is a trail suitable for people using wheelchairs.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Paragraph C describes a short, wheelchair-accessible boardwalk around a marsh."},{"q":"Staff lead nature walks on weekends.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Paragraph D says the park runs guided nature walks on weekends led by staff naturalists."},{"q":"Dogs must be kept on a leash throughout the park.","options":["Paragraph A","Paragraph B","Paragraph C","Paragraph D","This information is not given"],"answer":4,"explanation":"No paragraph mentions any rule about dogs or leashes in the park."}]}],"viewpoints":[{"id":"viewpoints-four-day-workweek","title":"Should Canada Move to a Four-Day Workweek?","instructions":"Read the following article and answer the questions about the viewpoints it presents.","passage":"Every few years, the idea of a four-day workweek resurfaces in Canadian workplaces, and lately it has gained real momentum. Several municipalities and private firms in Ontario and British Columbia have run pilot programs in which employees work thirty-two hours across four days while keeping their full salaries. Supporters point to encouraging results. During a widely cited trial, participating companies reported that productivity held steady or even improved, while staff turnover dropped noticeably. Employees said they slept better, spent more time with family, and returned to work on Monday feeling genuinely rested rather than merely recovered from the previous week.\n\nCritics, however, urge caution. They argue that the glowing pilot reports come mainly from office-based industries where output is easy to reorganize around fewer hours. In sectors such as health care, retail, and manufacturing, where a shift must physically be covered, cutting a day simply shifts the burden onto weekends or forces employers to hire additional staff. One hospital administrator noted that a compressed schedule sounds appealing until you try to staff an emergency department that never closes.\n\nHaving weighed both sides, I believe the four-day week deserves broader trials, but only when tailored to each workplace rather than imposed as a single national rule. The office studies are promising, yet they cannot be stretched to cover every kind of job. What works for a marketing agency may be unworkable for a long-term care home. A sensible path forward would let sectors experiment with their own models and share honest data, including the failures.\n\nWhat troubles me most is the tendency to treat the shorter week as either a miracle cure or an obvious folly. Neither framing helps workers. The real question is not whether fewer days are always better, but which arrangements genuinely protect both wellbeing and service. Answering that will take patience, and a willingness to admit that one schedule cannot fit an entire economy.","questions":[{"q":"What is the main idea of the article?","options":["The four-day workweek has been proven to fail in most Canadian industries.","The four-day workweek is a promising idea whose value depends heavily on the type of workplace.","Canadian municipalities have already adopted the four-day workweek nationwide.","Office workers are the only group that benefits from any change to work schedules."],"answer":1,"explanation":"The article presents supporting evidence and criticism, then argues the concept is worth pursuing but must be tailored to each sector — making its value context-dependent. It never claims proven failure, nationwide adoption, or that only office workers benefit."},{"q":"What is the author's own position on the four-day workweek?","options":["It should be adopted immediately as a single national rule.","It should be rejected because pilot results are unreliable.","It should be tested more widely, but tailored to the needs of each type of workplace.","It should be limited permanently to marketing and office jobs."],"answer":2,"explanation":"In paragraph three the author states the week 'deserves broader trials, but only when tailored to each workplace rather than imposed as a single national rule.' The other options misstate this balanced, sector-specific stance."},{"q":"According to the article, what did companies in the cited trial report?","options":["Productivity stayed the same or improved while staff turnover dropped.","Productivity fell sharply but employees were happier.","Salaries had to be reduced to make the schedule affordable.","Turnover increased because staff wanted even shorter weeks."],"answer":0,"explanation":"Paragraph one says productivity 'held steady or even improved, while staff turnover dropped noticeably,' and notes employees kept full salaries. The other options contradict the reported results."},{"q":"In the third paragraph, the phrase 'cannot be stretched to cover every kind of job' most nearly means that the office studies","options":["require more funding before they can continue.","should be extended to include longer working hours.","cannot reasonably be applied to all types of work.","prove that all jobs benefit equally from shorter weeks."],"answer":2,"explanation":"'Cannot be stretched to cover' means the findings do not generalize to every job. The following sentence contrasts a marketing agency with a care home, reinforcing limited applicability."},{"q":"What can be inferred about the hospital administrator's comment?","options":["Emergency departments would run more smoothly under a four-day week.","Some workplaces cannot easily reduce hours because their service must operate continuously.","Hospitals have already fully adopted the compressed schedule.","Health-care staff prefer working weekends to weekdays."],"answer":1,"explanation":"The administrator notes an emergency department 'never closes,' implying that continuous-service workplaces cannot simply drop a day. The other options are unsupported."},{"q":"The paragraph that most likely follows would discuss","options":["specific examples of sector-by-sector pilot designs and the data that would make future trials trustworthy.","a detailed history of the eight-hour workday in the nineteenth century.","why marketing agencies should abandon flexible scheduling entirely.","the personal daily routine of the hospital administrator quoted earlier."],"answer":0,"explanation":"The article closes by calling for patience, honest data including failures, and arrangements that fit different workplaces. A logical continuation would detail how such tailored, evidence-based trials could work. The other options break from that thread."}]},{"id":"viewpoints-screen-time-classrooms","title":"Tablets in the Classroom: Progress or Distraction?","instructions":"Read the following article and answer the questions about the viewpoints it presents.","passage":"A decade ago, handing every student a tablet felt like the future of Canadian education. Today, as several school boards in Alberta and Nova Scotia review their technology budgets, that confidence has cooled. The debate over screens in the classroom has grown more thoughtful, and more divided.\n\nAdvocates insist that devices open doors traditional textbooks cannot. A student in a small northern community can tour a museum in Ottawa, run a science simulation, or receive instant feedback on a math problem. Teachers describe how well-designed apps let them adjust lessons to each learner's pace, something that is nearly impossible with thirty paper worksheets. For students with certain learning disabilities, text-to-speech tools and adjustable fonts can be the difference between struggling and thriving.\n\nSkeptics counter that the promise has often outrun the evidence. Some studies suggest that reading comprehension is weaker on screens than on paper, and that constant notifications fracture the sustained attention deep learning requires. Several teachers report spending more energy policing games and messaging apps than teaching. A parent group in Halifax recently argued that districts bought expensive hardware without training teachers to use it well, leaving classrooms with costly distractions rather than tools.\n\nIn my view, the technology itself is neither villain nor saviour; the deciding factor is how deliberately it is used. A tablet handed out with no plan becomes a toy, while the same device folded into a clear lesson can genuinely deepen understanding. The boards now trimming their budgets are not wrong to demand results, but the answer is rarely to remove screens entirely. It is to invest in the teacher training and thoughtful design that were skipped the first time.\n\nWhat frustrates me is how quickly the conversation slides toward all-or-nothing positions. Ban the devices, or buy more of them. Real classrooms are messier than that, and the students inside them deserve a policy shaped by evidence rather than by whichever slogan is loudest this year.","questions":[{"q":"What is the main idea of the article?","options":["Tablets should be removed from all Canadian classrooms as soon as possible.","Whether classroom technology helps depends far more on how it is used than on the devices themselves.","Paper textbooks are always superior to digital tools for every student.","School boards in Alberta and Nova Scotia have already banned tablets."],"answer":1,"explanation":"The article weighs benefits and drawbacks and concludes the deciding factor is deliberate use plus teacher training, not the hardware. It rejects both banning and blindly buying more devices."},{"q":"What is the author's own stance?","options":["Technology is inherently harmful and classrooms are better without it.","Technology is inherently beneficial and more devices should always be purchased.","Technology's value depends on deliberate use, so investment should focus on training and lesson design.","The debate is unimportant and boards should simply keep spending as before."],"answer":2,"explanation":"The author writes that the technology 'is neither villain nor saviour' and that the answer is to invest in teacher training and thoughtful design. The extreme options misrepresent this."},{"q":"According to the article, what specific benefit do devices offer students with certain learning disabilities?","options":["They eliminate the need for any teacher supervision.","They provide text-to-speech tools and adjustable fonts.","They guarantee higher test scores in every subject.","They replace the need for classroom instruction entirely."],"answer":1,"explanation":"Paragraph two states that 'text-to-speech tools and adjustable fonts can be the difference between struggling and thriving' for such students. The other options overstate or invent claims."},{"q":"In the fourth paragraph, the phrase 'the technology itself is neither villain nor saviour' suggests that the author believes the devices are","options":["dangerous tools that must be feared.","perfect solutions to every classroom problem.","neutral tools whose effect depends on how people use them.","too expensive to be considered at all."],"answer":2,"explanation":"Calling the technology neither villain nor saviour frames it as neutral, with outcomes decided by usage — directly supported by the following sentence about deliberate use."},{"q":"What can be inferred about the Halifax parent group's complaint?","options":["They believed teachers were given enough training to use the devices well.","They felt money was spent on hardware without the preparation needed to make it useful.","They wanted every student to receive a second tablet.","They opposed all forms of digital learning on principle."],"answer":1,"explanation":"The group argued districts 'bought expensive hardware without training teachers to use it well,' implying poor preparation — not opposition to all technology or a desire for more devices."},{"q":"The paragraph that most likely follows would discuss","options":["concrete examples of effective teacher-training programs or lesson designs that make classroom technology work.","the history of the printing press in medieval Europe.","why northern communities should stop building schools.","a list of the most popular video games among adults."],"answer":0,"explanation":"The author ends by urging investment in teacher training and thoughtful design shaped by evidence. A natural next paragraph would offer concrete examples of such approaches. The other options are unrelated."}]},{"id":"viewpoints-urban-density-housing","title":"Building Up: The Debate Over Denser Neighbourhoods","instructions":"Read the following article and answer the questions about the viewpoints it presents.","passage":"As housing costs climb across Canada's cities, one solution keeps returning to city-council agendas: allowing taller, denser buildings in neighbourhoods once reserved for single-family homes. Recent zoning reforms in cities like Vancouver and Toronto now permit fourplexes and low-rise apartments on lots that previously held one house. The reaction has been anything but unanimous.\n\nSupporters frame density as a matter of fairness. When only detached houses are allowed near transit, jobs, and good schools, those areas become affordable to almost no one. Adding gentle density, they argue, lets teachers, nurses, and young families live in the communities where they work rather than commuting two hours each way. Denser neighbourhoods also tend to support more local shops and better transit, since services need customers within walking distance to survive.\n\nLonger-term residents often see it differently. Some worry that rapid construction will strain aging water and sewer lines, crowd street parking, and erase the quiet character that drew them to the area. Others point out that a new fourplex is not automatically affordable; developers may simply build pricier units and pocket the difference. A homeowner in a leafy Toronto neighbourhood put it bluntly: change the zoning all you like, but without rules on price, density can enrich builders more than it helps renters.\n\nI find myself persuaded that density is necessary, yet unconvinced it is sufficient on its own. Blocking apartments in desirable areas keeps housing scarce and prices high, and that outcome is neither fair nor sustainable. But the critics raise a fair point: zoning changes alone do not guarantee affordability. Cities that upzone must pair the new rules with investment in infrastructure and with genuine incentives for below-market housing.\n\nThe temptation is to treat density as a slogan, for or against. The harder and more useful work is designing the conditions under which denser neighbourhoods actually deliver on their promise.","questions":[{"q":"What is the main idea of the article?","options":["Denser neighbourhoods should be banned to protect existing residents.","Allowing denser housing is necessary but must be paired with other measures to truly improve affordability.","Single-family homes are the only fair form of housing.","Vancouver and Toronto have solved their housing crises through zoning reform."],"answer":1,"explanation":"The article presents both sides and concludes density is necessary but not sufficient, requiring infrastructure and affordability measures. It neither bans density nor claims the crisis is solved."},{"q":"What is the author's own viewpoint?","options":["Density is unnecessary and harmful to cities.","Density alone will automatically make housing affordable.","Density is necessary but not sufficient by itself and must be paired with other policies.","Zoning should never be changed in established neighbourhoods."],"answer":2,"explanation":"The author writes that density is 'necessary, yet unconvinced it is sufficient on its own,' and calls for pairing upzoning with infrastructure and affordability incentives."},{"q":"According to supporters cited in the article, why do denser neighbourhoods tend to support more local shops and transit?","options":["Because governments require every apartment to include a store.","Because services need enough customers within walking distance to survive.","Because denser areas ban cars entirely.","Because shops are cheaper to build in tall buildings."],"answer":1,"explanation":"Paragraph two explains services 'need customers within walking distance to survive,' which density provides. The other options are not stated."},{"q":"In the third paragraph, the phrase 'erase the quiet character that drew them to the area' refers to residents' fear that new construction will","options":["lower their property taxes.","change the peaceful atmosphere they originally valued.","improve local transit service too quickly.","force them to sell their homes to the city."],"answer":1,"explanation":"'Erase the quiet character' means losing the calm, peaceful quality that attracted them. The surrounding context lists strained utilities and crowded parking as related worries."},{"q":"What can be inferred from the Toronto homeowner's remark about zoning and price?","options":["Changing zoning alone may not lower housing costs for renters.","Developers always build affordable units when allowed to.","Renters prefer detached houses to apartments.","Density laws should never include any rules."],"answer":0,"explanation":"The homeowner says that without rules on price, density can 'enrich builders more than it helps renters,' implying zoning changes alone may not help renters."},{"q":"The paragraph that most likely follows would discuss","options":["specific policies, such as infrastructure funding or affordability incentives, that could make upzoning succeed.","the geological history of the land Toronto was built on.","why all apartment buildings should be demolished.","a review of popular house paint colours in Vancouver."],"answer":0,"explanation":"The author closes by calling for designing the conditions under which density delivers, pointing toward specific supporting policies. The other options are off-topic."}]},{"id":"viewpoints-gig-economy-work","title":"The Gig Economy: Freedom or Precarity?","instructions":"Read the following article and answer the questions about the viewpoints it presents.","passage":"Open almost any Canadian city map at dinnertime and you will see them: cyclists and drivers ferrying meals, groceries, and parcels from door to door. Gig work has become a familiar feature of urban life, and it has sparked an equally familiar argument about whether these jobs represent opportunity or exploitation.\n\nThose who defend the model highlight flexibility. A driver can log on between classes, a parent can work while children nap, and a newcomer to Canada can start earning within days rather than waiting months for a traditional posting. Platform companies note that many workers value being their own boss and choosing their own hours, freedoms a fixed shift rarely allows. For some, gig work is a welcome supplement to other income, not a sole livelihood.\n\nLabour advocates see a harsher reality behind the marketing. Because gig workers are usually classified as independent contractors, they receive no minimum wage guarantee, no paid sick days, and no employer contributions to pensions or insurance. When an app quietly adjusts its pay formula, workers have little recourse. A courier in Montreal described the arrangement plainly: the flexibility is real, but so is the fear of getting injured with no coverage at all.\n\nMy own conclusion is that the flexibility is genuine and worth preserving, but it should not come at the cost of basic protections. The choice being offered — total independence or nothing — is a false one. Other countries have begun creating a middle category that keeps flexible scheduling while guaranteeing minimum earnings and injury coverage. Canada would be wise to study those models seriously rather than pretending workers must accept the current bargain as it stands.\n\nWhat I resist is the habit of framing this as freedom versus safety, as if we must choose one. The more honest question is how to keep what workers genuinely value about gig work while removing the very real risks that too often come attached.","questions":[{"q":"What is the main idea of the article?","options":["Gig work should be banned across Canada immediately.","Gig work offers genuine flexibility but should be reformed to provide basic worker protections.","Gig workers already receive the same benefits as traditional employees.","Flexibility in work is never worth preserving."],"answer":1,"explanation":"The article balances the appeal of flexibility against the lack of protections and concludes flexibility is worth keeping while adding basic safeguards. It does not call for a ban or claim benefits already exist."},{"q":"What is the author's own position?","options":["Flexibility should be eliminated to protect workers.","Workers must simply accept the current arrangement as it is.","Flexibility should be preserved while adding minimum protections such as injury coverage.","Gig platforms already provide adequate pensions and sick days."],"answer":2,"explanation":"The author says flexibility is 'genuine and worth preserving, but it should not come at the cost of basic protections,' and praises a middle category with guaranteed earnings and injury coverage."},{"q":"According to the article, why do gig workers typically lack sick days and pension contributions?","options":["Because they are usually classified as independent contractors.","Because they refuse to accept such benefits.","Because Canadian law forbids these benefits for all workers.","Because they earn too much to qualify."],"answer":0,"explanation":"Paragraph three states that because gig workers are 'usually classified as independent contractors,' they receive no minimum wage guarantee, sick days, or employer contributions."},{"q":"In the fourth paragraph, the phrase 'a false one' describes the author's view that the choice between total independence and nothing is","options":["an accurate description of the only options available.","a misleading either-or that ignores better alternatives.","a legal requirement in most provinces.","a temporary problem that will disappear on its own."],"answer":1,"explanation":"Calling the choice 'a false one' means the author rejects the either-or framing, immediately pointing to a middle category as a better alternative."},{"q":"What can be inferred from the Montreal courier's statement?","options":["Gig workers face real financial danger if they are injured while working.","Couriers in Montreal earn more than traditional employees.","Flexibility is not actually valued by any gig worker.","Injury coverage is automatically provided to all couriers."],"answer":0,"explanation":"The courier says the flexibility is real 'but so is the fear of getting injured with no coverage at all,' implying genuine financial risk from injury."},{"q":"The paragraph that most likely follows would discuss","options":["specific examples of how other countries have created a middle category of worker protections.","the invention of the bicycle in the nineteenth century.","why customers should stop ordering food delivery entirely.","a detailed recipe for a popular takeout meal."],"answer":0,"explanation":"The author urges Canada to study foreign models that keep flexibility while adding protections. A logical next paragraph would detail those models. The other options are irrelevant."}]},{"id":"viewpoints-community-garden-parkland","title":"Turning Public Parks Into Community Gardens","instructions":"Read the following article and answer the questions about the viewpoints it presents.","passage":"In cities from Winnipeg to Halifax, residents are asking their councils for a slice of public parkland to grow vegetables. Community gardens, where neighbours rent small plots to raise their own food, have surged in popularity since the pandemic. The requests sound modest, yet they have opened a surprisingly heated debate about who public green space is really for.\n\nGardeners describe benefits that reach well beyond fresh produce. Plots give apartment dwellers, who often have no yard of their own, a place to dig in the soil and meet their neighbours. Seniors report that tending a garden keeps them active and connected, while newcomers use shared plots to grow foods from home that local stores rarely stock. Organizers add that a well-run garden can transform a neglected corner of a park into a lively, cared-for space.\n\nNot everyone is convinced. Some park users argue that turning open lawn into fenced, assigned plots quietly privatizes land meant for everyone. A family that once played soccer on that grass may find it locked behind a gate reserved for plot-holders. Critics also note that waiting lists for plots can stretch for years, so the benefit reaches relatively few people while the whole neighbourhood gives up shared space. One resident asked why a public field should be handed to a lucky few with a key.\n\nWeighing these claims, I support community gardens, but I share the worry that they can drift toward exclusion if planned carelessly. The solution is not to reject them; the social and health benefits are too valuable for that. It is to design them as genuinely public amenities — with open pathways, shared harvest days, and a fair share of the park left as truly common ground.\n\nWhat I want to avoid is the lazy framing that pits gardeners against everyone else. Handled thoughtfully, a garden can enrich a park rather than fence it off.","questions":[{"q":"What is the main idea of the article?","options":["Community gardens should be removed from all public parks.","Community gardens are valuable but must be designed so they do not exclude other park users.","Public parks should be reserved only for playing sports.","Only seniors benefit from community gardens."],"answer":1,"explanation":"The article weighs the benefits of gardens against concerns about exclusion and concludes they are worth supporting if designed as genuinely public amenities."},{"q":"What is the author's own stance on community gardens?","options":["They should be rejected because they privatize public land.","They should be supported but designed to remain genuinely public.","They should replace all other uses of public parks.","They are unimportant and not worth debating."],"answer":1,"explanation":"The author writes, 'I support community gardens, but I share the worry that they can drift toward exclusion,' and proposes open pathways and a fair share of common ground."},{"q":"According to the article, how do newcomers particularly benefit from shared garden plots?","options":["They can sell their produce for a large profit.","They can grow foods from home that local stores rarely stock.","They are given priority over all other applicants.","They receive free housing near the park."],"answer":1,"explanation":"Paragraph two says newcomers 'use shared plots to grow foods from home that local stores rarely stock.' The other options are not mentioned."},{"q":"In the third paragraph, the phrase 'quietly privatizes land meant for everyone' expresses the critics' concern that garden plots","options":["make public land noisier for nearby residents.","turn shared public space into areas restricted to a few individuals.","increase the cost of nearby housing.","improve the soil quality of the entire park."],"answer":1,"explanation":"'Privatizes land meant for everyone' means converting common space into plots reserved for plot-holders, as illustrated by the locked gate and the displaced soccer-playing family."},{"q":"What can be inferred from the resident's question about 'a lucky few with a key'?","options":["The resident believes garden access is limited and may be unfair to the wider public.","The resident wants to join the garden waiting list immediately.","The resident thinks everyone in the city already has a plot.","The resident supports fencing off the entire park."],"answer":0,"explanation":"Referring to 'a lucky few with a key' implies limited, possibly unfair access to space that belongs to the whole public, echoing the critics' point about years-long waiting lists."},{"q":"The paragraph that most likely follows would discuss","options":["specific design features or rules that would keep community gardens open and fair to all park users.","the chemical composition of common garden fertilizers.","why cities should stop building parks altogether.","a history of professional soccer leagues in Canada."],"answer":0,"explanation":"The author ends by advocating thoughtful design — open pathways, shared harvest days, common ground — so a natural continuation would detail such features. The other options stray from the topic."}]}]},"listening":{"problemSolving":[{"id":"wrong-couch-delivery","title":"A Furniture Delivery Mix-Up","instructions":"Listen to the conversation, then answer the questions. Choose the best answer for each question.","setup":"Priya has just received a furniture delivery at her apartment and is calling the store to report a problem.","transcript":[{"speaker":"Agent (Marcus)","line":"Thanks for calling Maple Home Furnishings, this is Marcus. How can I help you today?"},{"speaker":"Priya","line":"Hi Marcus. I ordered a grey three-seater sofa last week, and it was just delivered about an hour ago, but the one sitting in my living room is blue. Definitely not what I picked out."},{"speaker":"Agent (Marcus)","line":"Oh no, I'm sorry about that. Let me pull up your order. Can I get your name and the order number?"},{"speaker":"Priya","line":"Sure, it's Priya Anand, and the order number is 4-4-8-2-1."},{"speaker":"Agent (Marcus)","line":"Okay, I've got it here. Yep, you're right — the invoice clearly says charcoal grey, three-seater. So the warehouse must have loaded the wrong item onto the truck."},{"speaker":"Priya","line":"That's what I figured. The thing is, I've got family coming to stay this weekend, so I really need the right couch before Saturday."},{"speaker":"Agent (Marcus)","line":"I completely understand. Here's what I can do. I can schedule a swap — our driver brings the grey one and takes the blue one back in the same trip. The soonest slot would be Thursday afternoon."},{"speaker":"Priya","line":"Thursday works, but do I have to be home the whole afternoon? I've got a doctor's appointment at two."},{"speaker":"Agent (Marcus)","line":"No need to wait around all day. I can put you down for the first slot, so between noon and one. The driver will call twenty minutes before he arrives."},{"speaker":"Priya","line":"Perfect, that's before my appointment. And just to be clear, there's no extra charge for the redelivery, right? This wasn't my mistake."},{"speaker":"Agent (Marcus)","line":"Absolutely not. The swap is completely free, and I'll also add a fifty-dollar credit to your account for the inconvenience."},{"speaker":"Priya","line":"Oh, that's really kind, thank you. So Thursday, noon to one, grey sofa in, blue sofa out. I'll make sure someone's here."},{"speaker":"Agent (Marcus)","line":"You got it. I'll send a confirmation email with all those details in the next few minutes. Have a great day, Priya."}],"questions":[{"q":"What is Priya's main problem?","options":["The sofa she received was damaged during delivery","She was delivered the wrong colour of sofa","The sofa was delivered to the wrong address","Her sofa order never arrived"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Priya ordered a grey three-seater but the sofa delivered is blue, and Marcus confirms the invoice says charcoal grey, so it is the wrong colour."},{"q":"Why does Priya need the problem fixed before Saturday?","options":["She is moving to a new apartment","Family is coming to stay for the weekend","She is hosting a birthday party","The store's return window closes Saturday"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Priya says she has family coming to stay that weekend, so she needs the correct couch before Saturday."},{"q":"What does Marcus suggest to solve the problem?","options":["Refund the order and cancel the sofa","Send the grey sofa and take the blue one back in one trip","Have Priya drive the blue sofa back to the store","Ship a replacement cover for the sofa"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Marcus offers to schedule a swap in which the driver brings the grey sofa and takes the blue one back in the same trip."},{"q":"Why does the noon-to-one time slot work well for Priya?","options":["She only works in the mornings","It is before her two o'clock doctor's appointment","The driver charges less for early slots","Her family arrives at one o'clock"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Priya has a doctor's appointment at two, and she confirms the noon-to-one first slot is before that appointment."},{"q":"What extra thing does Marcus offer Priya?","options":["A fifty-dollar credit to her account","Free assembly of the new sofa","A one-year extended warranty","A discount on her next purchase of twenty percent"],"answer":0,"explanation":"On top of the free swap, Marcus says he will add a fifty-dollar credit to her account for the inconvenience."}]},{"id":"gym-class-clash","title":"A Scheduling Clash at the Community Centre","instructions":"Listen to the conversation, then answer the questions. Choose the best answer for each question.","setup":"Devon is at the front desk of his local community centre, sorting out a problem with two classes he signed up for.","transcript":[{"speaker":"Devon","line":"Hi, I think there's a problem with my class registrations. I signed up for the Tuesday evening pottery class and the intermediate swim lessons, but I just realized they're both at seven on Tuesdays."},{"speaker":"Staff (Lena)","line":"Ah, let me take a look. What's the name on the account?"},{"speaker":"Devon","line":"Devon Clarke. I registered online last Monday, and I honestly didn't notice the times overlapped until I printed out my schedule."},{"speaker":"Staff (Lena)","line":"Okay, I see both here. Yeah, you're right — pottery runs seven to nine, and swim is seven to seven forty-five, both Tuesdays. That won't work."},{"speaker":"Devon","line":"Right. I'd really like to keep both if I can. Is there another day for either one?"},{"speaker":"Staff (Lena)","line":"Let me check. Pottery is only offered Tuesdays this session, unfortunately. But the intermediate swim class has a second section on Thursday evenings, same time, seven to seven forty-five."},{"speaker":"Devon","line":"Oh, that could work. Thursdays are usually free for me. Is there space in the Thursday one?"},{"speaker":"Staff (Lena)","line":"Let me see... yes, there are a couple of spots left. I can move you from the Tuesday swim section to the Thursday one, and you'd keep your Tuesday pottery."},{"speaker":"Devon","line":"That sounds great. Does moving cost anything extra?"},{"speaker":"Staff (Lena)","line":"No, it's the same class and same fee, just a different night, so there's no charge to switch. I'll just need you to confirm the change."},{"speaker":"Devon","line":"Yes, please go ahead and switch me to Thursday swim. Thanks so much for sorting that out."},{"speaker":"Staff (Lena)","line":"No problem at all. Done. You're now in Thursday swim and Tuesday pottery. I'll email you an updated schedule this afternoon so you have it in writing."},{"speaker":"Devon","line":"Perfect. I appreciate it."}],"questions":[{"q":"What problem does Devon bring to the front desk?","options":["He was charged twice for one class","Two of his classes are at the same time","His class was cancelled without notice","He forgot which classes he registered for"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Devon signed up for pottery and swim lessons that both start at seven on Tuesdays, so the two classes overlap."},{"q":"When did Devon first notice the scheduling clash?","options":["When he arrived for the first class","When he printed out his schedule","When the centre called him","When he registered online"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Devon says he didn't notice the times overlapped until he printed out his schedule."},{"q":"Why can't Devon simply move the pottery class to another day?","options":["The pottery class is full on other days","Pottery is only offered on Tuesdays this session","Pottery costs more on other days","He already missed the first pottery class"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Lena explains that pottery is only offered on Tuesdays this session, so it cannot be moved to another day."},{"q":"What solution does Lena offer?","options":["Refunding the swim class","Moving Devon to the Thursday swim section","Cancelling the pottery class","Adding an extra pottery day"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Lena moves Devon from the Tuesday swim section to the Thursday evening section so he can keep his Tuesday pottery."},{"q":"What does Lena say about the cost of the switch?","options":["There is a small transfer fee","It is the same fee with no charge to switch","Devon must pay for the new class in full","The change earns Devon a discount"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Lena says it is the same class and same fee on a different night, so there is no charge to switch."}]},{"id":"broken-washing-machine","title":"A Broken Washing Machine in the Building","instructions":"Listen to the conversation, then answer the questions. Choose the best answer for each question.","setup":"Amara has stopped by the building manager's office because a shared laundry machine has malfunctioned.","transcript":[{"speaker":"Amara","line":"Hi Tom, sorry to bother you. I just had a problem in the laundry room. The middle washer, number three, took my two dollars in coins and then wouldn't start. The door's locked and my clothes are stuck inside."},{"speaker":"Manager (Tom)","line":"Oh, that's frustrating. Number three, you said? It's been acting up on and off for a couple of weeks. I'm sorry it swallowed your money."},{"speaker":"Amara","line":"Yeah, and my work clothes are in there. I really need that shirt for tomorrow morning."},{"speaker":"Manager (Tom)","line":"Understood. Let me grab the master key — I can pop the door open manually so you can get your clothes out. Then we'll figure out the rest."},{"speaker":"Amara","line":"Oh, that would be a huge relief. Thank you. And what about my two dollars?"},{"speaker":"Manager (Tom)","line":"I'll refund that to you directly. I keep a little petty cash for exactly this kind of thing. Two dollars, right?"},{"speaker":"Amara","line":"Yes, two dollars, thanks. And is the machine going to keep eating people's money? Maybe put a sign on it?"},{"speaker":"Manager (Tom)","line":"Good idea. I'll tape an out-of-order sign on number three right now so nobody else loses their coins. I'll also call the repair company first thing tomorrow."},{"speaker":"Amara","line":"That makes sense. In the meantime, are the other two washers working okay? I still need to actually do this load."},{"speaker":"Manager (Tom)","line":"Washers one and two are both fine, I used one this morning myself. Go ahead and move your load into one of those once we get the door open."},{"speaker":"Amara","line":"Great, I'll do that. Thanks so much for handling this so quickly, Tom."},{"speaker":"Manager (Tom)","line":"Happy to help. Give me two minutes to get the key and the cash, and I'll meet you down in the laundry room."}],"questions":[{"q":"What is Amara's problem?","options":["A washing machine took her money and locked her clothes inside","She lost her laundry room key","The laundry room is closed for cleaning","Someone took her clothes from a dryer"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Washer number three took her two dollars in coins, wouldn't start, and its locked door has trapped her clothes inside."},{"q":"Why is Amara especially worried about getting her clothes out?","options":["She needs a shirt for work the next morning","She is leaving on a trip that night","The clothes belong to a friend","She has no other clothes to wear"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Amara says her work clothes are inside and she really needs that shirt for the next morning."},{"q":"How will Tom get Amara's clothes out of the machine?","options":["By restarting the machine's cycle","By opening the door with the master key","By calling the repair company immediately","By waiting for the cycle to finish"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Tom offers to grab the master key and pop the door open manually so she can get her clothes out."},{"q":"What does Amara suggest that Tom agrees to do?","options":["Put an out-of-order sign on the machine","Refund everyone in the building","Replace all the washers","Lock the laundry room"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Amara suggests putting a sign on the machine, and Tom agrees to tape an out-of-order sign on number three right away."},{"q":"What does Tom say about the other washers?","options":["They are also broken","Washers one and two are working fine","They are reserved for other tenants","They only take cards, not coins"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Tom says washers one and two are both fine — he used one that morning — and tells Amara to move her load into one of those."}]},{"id":"catering-order-mixup","title":"A Catering Order Mix-Up for the Office","instructions":"Listen to the conversation, then answer the questions. Choose the best answer for each question.","setup":"Nadia is calling a cafe to sort out a catering order for her office lunch meeting.","transcript":[{"speaker":"Nadia","line":"Hi, this is Nadia from Brightline Consulting. I placed a catering order for delivery at eleven-thirty today, and I just want to double-check it, because the confirmation email I got says twelve sandwich platters, but I only ordered two."},{"speaker":"Cafe (Rob)","line":"Oh, let me pull that up. Brightline, you said? ... Okay, here it is. Yeah, the system has you down for twelve platters. That's a big difference."},{"speaker":"Nadia","line":"Right, twelve would feed an army. We're a team of eight, so two platters is plenty. I think a zero got added by mistake somewhere."},{"speaker":"Cafe (Rob)","line":"That could well be it. When the order went in over the phone, the extra digit probably slipped in. I'm really sorry about the confusion."},{"speaker":"Nadia","line":"No harm done, as long as we fix it before it's made. Twelve platters would be a disaster for our budget."},{"speaker":"Cafe (Rob)","line":"Good news — nothing's been prepped yet, the kitchen doesn't start on catering until ten. So I can just change it to two platters right now."},{"speaker":"Nadia","line":"That's a relief. Two platters, and can you keep the delivery time the same, eleven-thirty?"},{"speaker":"Cafe (Rob)","line":"Yes, eleven-thirty still works. And since the order's much smaller now, would you like me to add anything else — maybe a fruit tray or some cookies?"},{"speaker":"Nadia","line":"You know what, a fruit tray sounds nice. Let's add one medium fruit tray to the two platters."},{"speaker":"Cafe (Rob)","line":"Great choice. So that's two sandwich platters and one medium fruit tray, delivered at eleven-thirty to Brightline Consulting. I'll resend the corrected confirmation."},{"speaker":"Nadia","line":"Perfect. Can you make sure the new email shows the right total? I want to pass it to accounting."},{"speaker":"Cafe (Rob)","line":"Absolutely. The corrected total will be on it, and it'll be much friendlier to your budget. It'll be in your inbox within ten minutes."},{"speaker":"Nadia","line":"Wonderful. Thanks for catching that so quickly, Rob."}],"questions":[{"q":"What was wrong with Nadia's catering order?","options":["The delivery time was set too late","The confirmation listed twelve platters instead of two","The wrong type of food was ordered","The order was sent to the wrong company"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Nadia only ordered two sandwich platters, but the confirmation email listed twelve."},{"q":"How does Rob explain how the mistake likely happened?","options":["An extra digit slipped in when the phone order was taken","A different customer's order was merged with hers","The email system duplicated the order","Nadia gave the wrong number originally"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Rob says that when the order went in over the phone, the extra digit probably slipped in."},{"q":"Why is it easy to fix the order?","options":["The platters can be returned after delivery","Nothing has been prepped since the kitchen starts catering at ten","Another customer will take the extra platters","The cafe always makes extra food"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Rob says nothing has been prepped yet because the kitchen doesn't start on catering until ten, so he can change it right now."},{"q":"What does Rob suggest adding to the smaller order?","options":["A fruit tray or some cookies","Extra sandwiches","A pot of coffee","A second delivery later in the day"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Since the order is much smaller, Rob offers to add something else, suggesting a fruit tray or some cookies; Nadia adds a fruit tray."},{"q":"What does Nadia ask Rob to make sure of in the new email?","options":["That it shows the correct total for accounting","That it lists the team members' names","That it includes a discount code","That it is sent to her manager too"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Nadia asks that the new email show the right total because she wants to pass it to accounting."}]}],"conversation":[{"id":"listening-p2-new-apartment-balcony","title":"A Friend's New Apartment","instructions":"You will hear a conversation between two friends. Answer the questions based on what you hear.","setup":"Priya has just moved into a new apartment and is telling her coworker Dan about it over coffee.","transcript":[{"speaker":"Dan","line":"So how's the new place, Priya? You finally moved in last weekend, right?"},{"speaker":"Priya","line":"Yeah, we did. Honestly, I'm still surrounded by boxes, but it already feels like home. The best part is that it's a ten-minute walk to the LRT station now."},{"speaker":"Dan","line":"That's a huge upgrade. Weren't you taking two buses to get downtown before?"},{"speaker":"Priya","line":"Two buses and about fifty minutes each way. Now it's more like twenty-five minutes door to door. I actually get to sleep in a bit."},{"speaker":"Dan","line":"Nice. And is the apartment bigger, or did you just move for the location?"},{"speaker":"Priya","line":"It's about the same size, actually. One bedroom, but the layout is much smarter. And it has a balcony, which my old place didn't."},{"speaker":"Dan","line":"Oh, a balcony's great in the summer. Does it get any sun?"},{"speaker":"Priya","line":"That's the thing, it faces east, so I get morning sun but it's shaded by the afternoon. I was hoping for evening light, but honestly, for my plants the morning sun is probably better."},{"speaker":"Dan","line":"Fair enough. So what's the catch? New places always have one."},{"speaker":"Priya","line":"The rent is about a hundred and fifty dollars more a month than my old place. But when I add up what I'm saving on transit passes and time, it kind of balances out."},{"speaker":"Dan","line":"Makes sense. Are you planning a housewarming, or is it too soon?"},{"speaker":"Priya","line":"I want to, but not until I've unpacked and painted the living room. I'm thinking maybe early next month. I'll definitely send you an invite."},{"speaker":"Dan","line":"Perfect. I'll bring one of those big plants for your east-facing balcony."},{"speaker":"Priya","line":"Ha, please do. Just nothing that needs full afternoon sun, or it won't survive."}],"questions":[{"q":"What is the main reason Priya moved to the new apartment?","options":["To have a bigger living space","To be closer to public transit","To pay lower rent","To live with a roommate"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Priya calls the best part being a ten-minute walk to the LRT station, and she says the apartment is about the same size, so proximity to transit is the main reason, not more space (it is the same size) or lower rent (the rent is actually higher)."},{"q":"How has Priya's commute changed?","options":["It is now about half as long as before","It takes exactly the same amount of time","It got slightly longer but more comfortable","She no longer commutes downtown at all"],"answer":0,"explanation":"She used to spend about fifty minutes each way and now it is more like twenty-five minutes door to door, roughly half the time."},{"q":"What does Priya say about the balcony?","options":["It gets sun all day long","It faces east and gets morning sun","It is too small for plants","It faces west with evening light"],"answer":1,"explanation":"She says it faces east, so she gets morning sun but it is shaded by the afternoon; she had hoped for evening (west) light but did not get it."},{"q":"What is the drawback of the new apartment?","options":["It is farther from her workplace","The rent is higher than her old place","It has no outdoor space","The neighbourhood is noisy"],"answer":1,"explanation":"When Dan asks about the catch, she says the rent is about a hundred and fifty dollars more per month, though the transit savings partly balance it out."},{"q":"When does Priya plan to have a housewarming?","options":["This coming weekend","Once she has unpacked and painted, likely early next month","She does not plan to have one","As soon as Dan brings a plant"],"answer":1,"explanation":"She says she wants to wait until she has unpacked and painted the living room, thinking maybe early next month, and will send Dan an invite."}]},{"id":"listening-p2-weekend-hiking-trip","title":"Planning a Weekend Hike","instructions":"You will hear a conversation between two friends. Answer the questions based on what you hear.","setup":"Marcus and Chloe are planning a weekend hiking trip and are sorting out the details.","transcript":[{"speaker":"Chloe","line":"Hey Marcus, are we still on for the hike this Saturday? I've been checking the forecast all week."},{"speaker":"Marcus","line":"I hope so. What's it looking like? Last I saw there was a chance of rain."},{"speaker":"Chloe","line":"That was the old forecast. As of this morning it's mostly sunny, high of about twenty-two, with maybe some cloud in the late afternoon. Pretty much perfect hiking weather."},{"speaker":"Marcus","line":"Oh, that's great news. So which trail were you thinking? The lakeside loop again?"},{"speaker":"Chloe","line":"Actually, I was hoping we could try the ridge trail this time. It's longer, about fourteen kilometres, but the view from the top is supposed to be incredible."},{"speaker":"Marcus","line":"Fourteen kilometres. That's a solid day. How long do you think it'll take us?"},{"speaker":"Chloe","line":"With breaks and lunch at the summit, probably five to six hours. So I think we should leave the city by seven so we're not rushing at the end."},{"speaker":"Marcus","line":"Seven works. I'll drive, my car's got more trunk space for the packs. Do you want to split the gas?"},{"speaker":"Chloe","line":"Definitely. And I'll handle lunch, I'll make some wraps and bring trail mix. Can you bring extra water? The ridge trail doesn't have any taps."},{"speaker":"Marcus","line":"No problem. I'll fill up a couple of the big bottles. Should we tell anyone where we're going, just to be safe?"},{"speaker":"Chloe","line":"Good idea. I'll text my sister the trail name and roughly when we expect to be back. That trail can get patchy cell service."},{"speaker":"Marcus","line":"Smart. Okay, so seven a.m. Saturday, I pick you up, you've got lunch, I've got water. Anything else?"},{"speaker":"Chloe","line":"Just good boots and sunscreen. Oh, and let's grab coffee on the way out of town. I can't hike without it."},{"speaker":"Marcus","line":"Now you're speaking my language. See you Saturday."}],"questions":[{"q":"What does Chloe say about the weather for Saturday?","options":["It is now expected to be mostly sunny","There is a high chance of rain all day","It will be cold with possible snow","The forecast is still uncertain"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Chloe says the old forecast mentioned rain, but as of this morning it is mostly sunny with a high of about twenty-two, which she calls perfect hiking weather."},{"q":"Which trail do they decide to hike?","options":["The lakeside loop","The ridge trail","A trail near the city","They could not decide"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Chloe suggests trying the ridge trail this time instead of the lakeside loop, and Marcus agrees to the plan around it."},{"q":"Why does Marcus offer to drive?","options":["Chloe does not have a car","His car has more trunk space for the packs","He wants to split the gas","His car is faster on the highway"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Marcus says he will drive because his car has more trunk space for the packs; splitting the gas is a separate question he asks afterward."},{"q":"What is Marcus responsible for bringing?","options":["Lunch and trail mix","Extra water","Sunscreen and boots","Coffee for the drive"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Chloe is making lunch and trail mix, and she asks Marcus to bring extra water because the ridge trail has no taps; Marcus confirms he has the water."},{"q":"What safety step does Chloe plan to take?","options":["Bring a first-aid kit","Text her sister the trail name and return time","Hire a hiking guide","Download an offline map"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Chloe says she will text her sister the trail name and roughly when they expect to be back, since the trail can get patchy cell service."}]},{"id":"listening-p2-pottery-class","title":"Signing Up for a Pottery Class","instructions":"You will hear a conversation between two friends. Answer the questions based on what you hear.","setup":"Amir runs into his neighbour Jenna at the community centre and hears about a pottery class she just started.","transcript":[{"speaker":"Amir","line":"Jenna, hey. I didn't expect to see you here on a Tuesday night. Are you taking a class?"},{"speaker":"Jenna","line":"I am, actually. I just started the beginner pottery class. Tonight was my second session."},{"speaker":"Amir","line":"Pottery, really? I always thought that looked so hard. How's it going?"},{"speaker":"Jenna","line":"Harder than it looks, honestly. My first bowl completely collapsed on the wheel. But the instructor is really patient, and by tonight I actually made something that stayed in one piece."},{"speaker":"Amir","line":"That's progress. Is it one of those drop-in things, or did you have to commit to the whole term?"},{"speaker":"Jenna","line":"It's an eight-week course, once a week. You pay for the whole thing up front. It was ninety dollars, which includes all the clay and the firing costs, so that's not bad."},{"speaker":"Amir","line":"Ninety for eight weeks with materials? That's pretty reasonable. I've been looking for something to get me off my phone in the evenings."},{"speaker":"Jenna","line":"Then you'd love it. Honestly, when I'm at the wheel I completely forget about work and everything else. Two hours just fly by."},{"speaker":"Amir","line":"That sounds exactly like what I need. Is it too late to join your class?"},{"speaker":"Jenna","line":"This one's full, unfortunately, and we're already two weeks in. But I saw a sign-up sheet at the front desk for a new section starting next month. You should grab a spot before it fills."},{"speaker":"Amir","line":"I'll go ask right now. Do I need to bring anything, like an apron or my own tools?"},{"speaker":"Jenna","line":"Nope, they provide the tools and aprons. Just wear clothes you don't mind getting clay all over. Trust me, you will."},{"speaker":"Amir","line":"Good to know. Thanks, Jenna. Maybe I'll be showing you my collapsed bowls next month."},{"speaker":"Jenna","line":"Ha, we all start there. You'll get the hang of it faster than you think."}],"questions":[{"q":"Why is Jenna at the community centre?","options":["To sign up for a new class","To take a beginner pottery class","To meet Amir","To watch a pottery demonstration"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Jenna says she just started the beginner pottery class and that tonight was her second session; it is Amir, not Jenna, who ends up signing up for a new class."},{"q":"What does Jenna say about her experience so far?","options":["It is easier than she expected","It is hard, but she is making progress","She is thinking of quitting","The instructor is unhelpful"],"answer":1,"explanation":"She says it is harder than it looks and her first bowl collapsed, but the instructor is patient and tonight she made something that stayed in one piece, showing progress."},{"q":"What does the ninety-dollar fee include?","options":["Only the classes themselves","The clay and firing costs","An apron and tools to keep","A one-time drop-in session"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Jenna says the ninety dollars for the eight-week course includes all the clay and the firing costs; the aprons and tools are provided for use, not to keep."},{"q":"Why can't Amir join Jenna's class?","options":["It is too expensive for him","The class is full and already two weeks in","It meets on a night he is busy","He needs to buy his own tools first"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Jenna says her class is full and they are already two weeks in, but points him to a new section starting next month."},{"q":"What does Amir decide to do?","options":["Sign up for the new section starting next month","Wait until the next term to decide","Buy pottery tools and practise at home","Join a different class instead"],"answer":0,"explanation":"After Jenna mentions the sign-up sheet for the new section, Amir says he will go ask right now and grab a spot before it fills."}]},{"id":"listening-p2-coworker-vacation","title":"Back From Vacation","instructions":"You will hear a conversation between two coworkers. Answer the questions based on what you hear.","setup":"Devon returns to the office after a week off and catches up with his coworker Rita.","transcript":[{"speaker":"Rita","line":"Devon, welcome back! We missed you. How was the trip? You went out east, right?"},{"speaker":"Devon","line":"Thanks, Rita. Yeah, Nova Scotia. My partner and I spent the week driving the coast and eating way too much seafood."},{"speaker":"Rita","line":"That sounds amazing. Was it your first time out there?"},{"speaker":"Devon","line":"First time for me, second for her. She kept telling me the ocean would be freezing, and she was not wrong. I dipped my feet in once and that was enough."},{"speaker":"Rita","line":"Ha, I've heard the Atlantic is brutal even in summer. So what was the highlight?"},{"speaker":"Devon","line":"Honestly, I expected the lighthouses and the scenery to be the best part, and they were beautiful, but the real highlight was this little kitchen party we stumbled into at a pub. Live fiddle music, everyone singing along. We stayed until midnight."},{"speaker":"Rita","line":"That sounds like the kind of thing you can't plan for. Did the weather cooperate?"},{"speaker":"Devon","line":"Mostly. We had two rainy days, but honestly that was fine. We just spent them in museums and cafes. The other five were gorgeous."},{"speaker":"Rita","line":"Not bad at all. So are you totally rested, or do you need a vacation from your vacation?"},{"speaker":"Devon","line":"A bit of both. It was relaxing, but we drove almost two thousand kilometres, so my back is glad to be back at a desk, believe it or not."},{"speaker":"Rita","line":"I hear that. Well, brace yourself, your inbox is a bit of a monster. But the Henderson project got pushed to next Friday, so at least that pressure's off today."},{"speaker":"Devon","line":"Oh, that's a relief. I was dreading walking into that deadline. I'll ease in with emails this morning, then."},{"speaker":"Rita","line":"Good plan. And let's grab lunch later, I want to hear more about that kitchen party."},{"speaker":"Devon","line":"Deal. I've got about two hundred photos to bore you with."}],"questions":[{"q":"Where did Devon go on his vacation?","options":["Nova Scotia","British Columbia","Quebec","Newfoundland"],"answer":0,"explanation":"When Rita asks if he went out east, Devon confirms Nova Scotia, where he and his partner drove the coast and ate seafood."},{"q":"What was the highlight of Devon's trip?","options":["Swimming in the ocean","A spontaneous kitchen party with live music","Visiting the lighthouses","Driving along the coast"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Devon says he expected the lighthouses and scenery to be the best part, but the real highlight was a kitchen party at a pub with live fiddle music that they stumbled into."},{"q":"How did Devon and his partner spend the rainy days?","options":["Driving to another town","In museums and cafes","Resting at the hotel","Swimming despite the rain"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Devon says they had two rainy days and spent them in museums and cafes, while the other five days were gorgeous."},{"q":"Why does Devon say his back is glad to be back at a desk?","options":["He injured his back on the trip","They drove almost two thousand kilometres","He slept on an uncomfortable bed","He carried heavy luggage"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Devon says they drove almost two thousand kilometres, so his back is glad to be back at a desk, framing it as fatigue from driving rather than an injury."},{"q":"What good news does Rita share about work?","options":["Devon's inbox has been cleared","The Henderson project deadline was pushed to next Friday","Devon was given an extra day off","The Henderson project was cancelled"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Rita warns his inbox is a monster but shares that the Henderson project got pushed to next Friday, so that deadline pressure is off for today; it was delayed, not cancelled."}]}],"information":[{"id":"community-centre-pottery-orientation","title":"Pottery Studio Orientation","instructions":"You will hear a staff member giving a new member an orientation to a community centre pottery studio. Listen for the information and answer the questions.","setup":"A community centre staff member walks a newly registered member through how the pottery studio works.","transcript":[{"speaker":"Staff","line":"Welcome to the Riverside Community Centre pottery studio. I'm Dana, and I'll be running through how things work here before you get started."},{"speaker":"Staff","line":"First off, your membership gives you open-studio access, but that's separate from classes. Open studio runs Tuesday through Sunday, and we're closed Mondays for kiln maintenance."},{"speaker":"Member","line":"So if I just want to practice on my own, I can come any day except Monday?"},{"speaker":"Staff","line":"Exactly. Open-studio hours are ten to four on weekdays, but on weekends we extend to eight in the evening, which most members prefer."},{"speaker":"Staff","line":"Clay isn't included in your membership. We sell it here at eighteen dollars a bag, and one bag is usually good for four or five small pieces."},{"speaker":"Member","line":"And what about firing the pieces once they're done?"},{"speaker":"Staff","line":"Firing is included, but there's a rule: anything you want fired has to be on the glazing shelf by Thursday noon. We load the kiln Thursday afternoon and it runs over the weekend."},{"speaker":"Staff","line":"If you miss the Thursday cutoff, your piece just waits for the following week's firing. We don't do mid-week loads."},{"speaker":"Staff","line":"Every piece needs your name and member number scratched into the bottom before it dries. Unlabelled work gets set aside, and after a month we recycle it."},{"speaker":"Member","line":"That's a bit strict. What if I forget my member number?"},{"speaker":"Staff","line":"It's printed on your membership card, and it's also on the sign-in tablet by the door. You have to sign in every visit, mostly so we can track studio capacity."},{"speaker":"Staff","line":"One more thing on safety. The wheels and the slab roller are fine to use on your own, but the kiln is staff-only. Never open it, even if it looks cool and finished."},{"speaker":"Staff","line":"And please wet-mop your station when you leave. Dry sweeping kicks clay dust into the air, and that's the one thing we're really firm about here."}],"questions":[{"q":"When is the pottery studio completely closed?","options":["Sundays","Mondays","Thursday afternoons","Weekend evenings"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Dana says open studio runs 'Tuesday through Sunday, and we're closed Mondays for kiln maintenance,' so Monday is the one fully closed day."},{"q":"How do open-studio hours differ on weekends?","options":["They stay open until eight in the evening","They open earlier, at eight in the morning","They are limited to members taking classes","They close at four, the same as weekdays"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Weekday hours are 'ten to four,' but Dana says 'on weekends we extend to eight in the evening.'"},{"q":"What must a member do to have a piece fired that week?","options":["Pay an extra firing fee at the desk","Place it on the glazing shelf by Thursday noon","Load it into the kiln themselves on Thursday","Sign up for the next available class"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Firing is included, but 'anything you want fired has to be on the glazing shelf by Thursday noon,' when the kiln is loaded."},{"q":"What happens to a piece that is not labelled with a name and member number?","options":["It is fired but stored separately","It is set aside and recycled after a month","It is returned to the member by mail","It is charged a relabelling fee"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Dana says 'unlabelled work gets set aside, and after a month we recycle it.'"},{"q":"Which equipment are members NOT allowed to operate themselves?","options":["The pottery wheels","The slab roller","The kiln","The sign-in tablet"],"answer":2,"explanation":"'The wheels and the slab roller are fine to use on your own, but the kiln is staff-only.'"},{"q":"How does Dana say members should clean their station?","options":["Dry sweep the floor before leaving","Wet-mop the station to avoid clay dust","Leave cleaning to the maintenance staff","Rinse everything in the utility sink"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Dana says to 'wet-mop your station' because 'dry sweeping kicks clay dust into the air.'"}]},{"id":"transit-upass-replacement","title":"Transit Card Replacement Process","transcript":[{"speaker":"Clerk","line":"Hi there, welcome to the Metro Transit customer service centre. I understand you've lost your monthly pass card. Let's get that sorted out."},{"speaker":"Rider","line":"Yes, I think it fell out of my pocket somewhere. It still had almost the whole month left on it."},{"speaker":"Clerk","line":"Good news is that your monthly balance is tied to your account, not the plastic card itself, so we can transfer whatever was loaded onto a new card."},{"speaker":"Clerk","line":"The replacement card has a flat fee of six dollars. That's separate from your fare balance, and unfortunately we can't waive it, even for a first replacement."},{"speaker":"Rider","line":"Six dollars, okay. Do I get the new card right now, or do I have to wait for it in the mail?"},{"speaker":"Clerk","line":"You'll get a temporary paper card today, valid for seventy-two hours. The permanent plastic one is mailed and usually arrives within five business days."},{"speaker":"Clerk","line":"To process this, I'll need one piece of photo ID and the phone number linked to your account. If you registered online, we can look it up by email instead."},{"speaker":"Rider","line":"I definitely registered online when I first bought the pass. My phone number might be an old one, though."},{"speaker":"Clerk","line":"No problem, we'll use your email then. Just so you know, once I deactivate the old card, if you ever find it, it won't work anymore. Please recycle it."},{"speaker":"Clerk","line":"One important thing: any taps made on the old card before you reported it lost are non-refundable. Reporting today freezes it from this moment on."},{"speaker":"Rider","line":"So if someone used it yesterday, that money is just gone?"},{"speaker":"Clerk","line":"Correct, we can only protect the balance from the time of your report forward. That's why we always tell people to report a lost card the same day."},{"speaker":"Clerk","line":"Last step, please double-check your mailing address on this screen. If it's wrong, the permanent card goes to the old address and you'd pay the fee again for another."}],"instructions":"You will hear a customer service clerk explaining how to replace a lost transit pass. Listen for the information and answer the questions.","setup":"A rider visits a transit customer service centre to replace a lost monthly pass card.","questions":[{"q":"Why can the rider's fare balance be recovered?","options":["Because it is printed on a receipt","Because it is tied to the account, not the card","Because the clerk can read it off the lost card","Because monthly passes are automatically refunded"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The clerk says the balance 'is tied to your account, not the plastic card itself,' so it can be transferred to a new card."},{"q":"How much is the replacement card fee?","options":["It is free for the first replacement","Six dollars, which cannot be waived","Six dollars, waived for online accounts","It is deducted from the fare balance"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The clerk states there is 'a flat fee of six dollars' and 'we can't waive it, even for a first replacement.'"},{"q":"How long is the temporary paper card valid?","options":["Twenty-four hours","Seventy-two hours","Five business days","Until the plastic card arrives, however long that takes"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The clerk says the temporary paper card is 'valid for seventy-two hours'; five business days is the mailing time for the permanent card."},{"q":"Since the rider's phone number may be outdated, how will the clerk find the account?","options":["By the rider's home address","By the lost card's serial number","By the rider's email","By a new phone number the rider provides"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Because the rider registered online, the clerk says 'we'll use your email then.'"},{"q":"What happens to taps made on the old card before it was reported lost?","options":["They are fully refunded to the new card","They are non-refundable","They are refunded minus the six-dollar fee","They are transferred after five business days"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The clerk says taps before the report 'are non-refundable'; the freeze only protects the balance 'from the time of your report forward.'"},{"q":"Why does the clerk ask the rider to check the mailing address?","options":["To confirm the rider lives in the transit zone","So the permanent card is not mailed to the wrong place","To update the emergency contact on file","To qualify for a discounted fare"],"answer":1,"explanation":"If the address is wrong, 'the permanent card goes to the old address and you'd pay the fee again for another.'"}]},{"id":"museum-guided-tour-intro","title":"Museum Guided Tour Briefing","instructions":"You will hear a museum guide briefing a group before a tour begins. Listen for the information and answer the questions.","setup":"A guide gives a group of visitors instructions before starting a guided tour of a natural history museum.","transcript":[{"speaker":"Guide","line":"Good morning everyone, and welcome to the Northern Natural History Museum. My name is Priya and I'll be your guide for the next ninety minutes."},{"speaker":"Guide","line":"Before we start, a few housekeeping items. This tour covers three floors, and we'll finish up in the gift shop, but we will not be visiting the temporary dinosaur exhibit, which needs a separate ticket."},{"speaker":"Visitor","line":"Oh, I was hoping to see the dinosaurs. Can I add that on today?"},{"speaker":"Guide","line":"You can. Tickets for the dinosaur exhibit are twelve dollars and you buy them at the second-floor desk, not the main entrance. I'd suggest doing that after our tour so you don't lose the group."},{"speaker":"Guide","line":"Photography is welcome throughout, but please switch off your flash. The light damages some of the older textile and feather specimens on the third floor."},{"speaker":"Guide","line":"We have one hands-on station, the mineral touch table on floor one. Everything else is look-but-don't-touch, especially the mounted animals."},{"speaker":"Visitor","line":"Is there anywhere we can leave our bags? Mine's pretty heavy."},{"speaker":"Guide","line":"Yes, coat and bag check is just past the entrance on your left. It's free, though large backpacks are actually required to be checked before you go upstairs."},{"speaker":"Guide","line":"There are washrooms on every floor, but the only water fountain is on floor two near the elevators. Feel free to step away and catch up with us if you need to."},{"speaker":"Guide","line":"If we get separated, don't worry. We reconvene at the whale skeleton in the main atrium at eleven thirty sharp for the last part of the tour."},{"speaker":"Visitor","line":"What if we want to keep exploring on our own after the tour ends?"},{"speaker":"Guide","line":"Absolutely, your admission is good for the whole day. You can re-enter any gallery except the dinosaur exhibit as often as you like until we close at five."},{"speaker":"Guide","line":"All right, phones on silent please, and let's begin here on floor one with the mineral collection. Follow me and stay together."}],"questions":[{"q":"Which area is NOT included in the guided tour?","options":["The gift shop","The mineral touch table","The temporary dinosaur exhibit","The whale skeleton in the atrium"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Priya says 'we will not be visiting the temporary dinosaur exhibit, which needs a separate ticket'; the tour does cover the gift shop, touch table, and whale skeleton."},{"q":"Where are tickets for the dinosaur exhibit purchased?","options":["At the main entrance","At the second-floor desk","At the gift shop","At the coat and bag check"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Tickets are twelve dollars and bought 'at the second-floor desk, not the main entrance.'"},{"q":"What rule does the guide give about photography?","options":["No photography is allowed at all","Photos are fine, but flash must be turned off","Photos are only allowed on the first floor","A photo permit must be purchased"],"answer":1,"explanation":"'Photography is welcome throughout, but please switch off your flash,' which damages older specimens."},{"q":"What is required of visitors with large backpacks?","options":["They must pay a storage fee","They must carry them at all times","They must be checked before going upstairs","They are not allowed in the museum"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Bag check is free, but 'large backpacks are actually required to be checked before you go upstairs.'"},{"q":"Where and when does the group reconvene if separated?","options":["At the entrance at eleven o'clock","At the whale skeleton at eleven thirty","At the mineral touch table at noon","At the gift shop at eleven thirty"],"answer":1,"explanation":"They 'reconvene at the whale skeleton in the main atrium at eleven thirty sharp.'"},{"q":"After the tour ends, what can visitors do with their admission?","options":["Re-enter any gallery, including the dinosaur exhibit","Re-enter any gallery except the dinosaur exhibit until closing","Leave and return only once more","Access galleries only with a new ticket"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Admission is 'good for the whole day' and lets you 're-enter any gallery except the dinosaur exhibit' until closing at five."}]},{"id":"workplace-onboarding-benefits","title":"New Employee Benefits Orientation","instructions":"You will hear an HR coordinator explaining benefits to a new employee during onboarding. Listen for the information and answer the questions.","setup":"An HR coordinator walks a newly hired employee through the company's benefits and first-week logistics.","transcript":[{"speaker":"HR","line":"Hi, and welcome aboard. I'm Marcus from HR, and I'll spend about twenty minutes going over your benefits and a few first-week details."},{"speaker":"HR","line":"Let's start with health coverage. Your extended health and dental plan kicks in after a ninety-day waiting period, so mark that date on your calendar."},{"speaker":"Employee","line":"Ninety days? Is there anything I'm covered for before that?"},{"speaker":"HR","line":"Good question. Basic provincial health applies from day one, of course, but our top-up plan, things like dental, massage, and prescription coverage, only starts at the ninety-day mark."},{"speaker":"HR","line":"Once you're enrolled, the company covers eighty percent of most prescription and dental costs, and you pay the remaining twenty."},{"speaker":"HR","line":"There's also a health spending account of five hundred dollars a year for anything the main plan doesn't cover, like new glasses or physiotherapy beyond the limit."},{"speaker":"Employee","line":"That's helpful. What about vacation? I wasn't sure what I'd get starting mid-year."},{"speaker":"HR","line":"You accrue three weeks of paid vacation per year, earned at one and a quarter days per month. Since you're starting in July, you'll have roughly seven and a half days by December."},{"speaker":"HR","line":"You can't go into a negative balance, so you can only book vacation you've already accrued in your first year. After year one, we're more flexible."},{"speaker":"Employee","line":"Got it. And is there a retirement plan?"},{"speaker":"HR","line":"Yes, we match your RRSP contributions up to four percent of your salary, but you have to opt in through the portal. It's not automatic, so a lot of people miss it."},{"speaker":"HR","line":"To enrol in everything, log in to the benefits portal within your first thirty days. If you miss that window, you wait until the next annual enrolment in January."},{"speaker":"HR","line":"Last thing: your building access card is being printed and will be at the front desk tomorrow morning. For today, security will buzz you in and out."}],"questions":[{"q":"When does the extended health and dental plan begin?","options":["On the employee's first day","After a ninety-day waiting period","After thirty days","At the next January enrolment"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Marcus says the extended health and dental plan 'kicks in after a ninety-day waiting period'; only basic provincial health applies from day one."},{"q":"Once enrolled, how much of most prescription and dental costs does the company cover?","options":["One hundred percent","Eighty percent","Twenty percent","Four percent"],"answer":1,"explanation":"'The company covers eighty percent of most prescription and dental costs, and you pay the remaining twenty.'"},{"q":"What is the health spending account used for?","options":["Paying the ninety-day waiting period costs","Covering things the main plan doesn't, up to five hundred dollars a year","Matching retirement contributions","Buying the building access card"],"answer":1,"explanation":"It is 'five hundred dollars a year for anything the main plan doesn't cover, like new glasses or physiotherapy beyond the limit.'"},{"q":"How much paid vacation will the employee have accrued by December?","options":["Three full weeks","About seven and a half days","One and a quarter days","Fifteen days"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Accruing 'one and a quarter days per month' from a July start, 'you'll have roughly seven and a half days by December.'"},{"q":"What must the employee do to receive the RRSP match?","options":["Wait ninety days for automatic enrolment","Opt in through the portal","Contribute at least eight percent of salary","Request it through their manager"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The match is up to four percent, but 'you have to opt in through the portal. It's not automatic.'"},{"q":"What happens if the employee misses the thirty-day enrolment window?","options":["They lose all benefits permanently","They must wait until the next annual enrolment in January","They are automatically enrolled anyway","They can enrol at any time with a penalty"],"answer":1,"explanation":"'If you miss that window, you wait until the next annual enrolment in January.'"}]}],"news":[{"id":"riverside-flood-mitigation-news","title":"News Item: Riverside Flood Barriers","instructions":"You will hear a news report. Listen carefully, then answer the questions. You will hear the report only once.","setup":"Listen to a local news report about a community project.","transcript":[{"speaker":"Reporter","line":"Good evening. Residents of the Millbrook neighbourhood woke up this morning to the sound of heavy machinery, as the city broke ground on a long-awaited flood protection project along the Cedar River. For years, homeowners in this low-lying area have watched the river creep over its banks every spring, flooding basements and washing out the popular riverside walking trail. The new project will install a series of removable steel barriers that crews can raise within hours when water levels rise. City engineer Dana Whitfield told us the barriers were chosen over a permanent concrete wall because they preserve residents' view of the water during the dry summer months. The eighteen-million-dollar project is being funded jointly by the city and the provincial government, with construction expected to wrap up before next spring's melt. In the meantime, a stretch of Riverside Drive will be reduced to a single lane, and the walking trail will be closed until October. The city is asking drivers to add ten minutes to their commute and to watch for flaggers directing traffic near the work site. Reporting from Millbrook, I'm Alan Reyes."}],"questions":[{"q":"What problem is the new project designed to solve?","options":["Traffic congestion on Riverside Drive","Spring flooding from the Cedar River","Erosion of the riverbank in summer","A shortage of parks in Millbrook"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The reporter says homeowners have watched the river creep over its banks every spring, flooding basements, and the project installs flood barriers to address this."},{"q":"Why were removable steel barriers chosen instead of a permanent concrete wall?","options":["They are cheaper to build","They can be installed more quickly","They preserve residents' view of the water in summer","They require less government funding"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Engineer Dana Whitfield says the barriers were chosen over a concrete wall because they preserve residents' view of the water during the dry summer months."},{"q":"Who is paying for the project?","options":["The city alone","The city and the provincial government together","The federal government","Local homeowners through a special tax"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The report states the eighteen-million-dollar project is being funded jointly by the city and the provincial government."},{"q":"When is the walking trail expected to reopen?","options":["Before next spring","In October","Immediately after construction begins","Not until the following summer"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The reporter says the walking trail will be closed until October, so it reopens then."},{"q":"What can be inferred about traffic near the work site?","options":["Riverside Drive will be closed entirely","Commuters should expect some delays","Only trucks will be allowed to pass","The road work will finish within a week"],"answer":1,"explanation":"A lane reduction, the request to add ten minutes to commutes, and flaggers directing traffic all imply drivers should expect delays, though the road stays open (ruling out the 'closed entirely' option)."}]},{"id":"winter-lights-festival-news","title":"News Item: Harbourfront Winter Lights Festival","instructions":"You will hear a news report. Listen carefully, then answer the questions. You will hear the report only once.","setup":"Listen to a local news report about an upcoming event.","transcript":[{"speaker":"Reporter","line":"This is your community update. Organizers announced today that the Harbourfront Winter Lights Festival will return for its fifth year, opening this Friday evening in Lakeside Park. What began as a modest display of a few strings of bulbs has grown into one of the region's largest free winter attractions, drawing more than eighty thousand visitors last season. This year's festival features over a million energy-efficient LED lights arranged into towering archways and animated displays, all powered by a new solar battery system that organizers say cuts the event's electricity costs nearly in half. Festival director Priya Malhotra said the biggest change this year is a shift to weekend shuttle buses from three downtown parking lots, a response to the parking shortages that frustrated visitors last winter. Admission remains free, though donations to the local food bank are encouraged at the gates. The festival runs every evening from five until ten, right through to the first weekend of January. Organizers do remind guests to bundle up, as temperatures near the water can feel several degrees colder than the forecast suggests. I'm Carol Nguyen, reporting."}],"questions":[{"q":"What is the main reason shuttle buses were added this year?","options":["To reduce the festival's electricity costs","To respond to parking shortages last winter","To raise money for the local food bank","To attract more visitors from downtown"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Director Priya Malhotra says the shift to shuttle buses is a response to the parking shortages that frustrated visitors last winter."},{"q":"How is this year's light display powered?","options":["By the city's regular power grid","By a new solar battery system","By donations from local businesses","By portable diesel generators"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The report says the lights are powered by a new solar battery system that cuts electricity costs nearly in half."},{"q":"How much does admission to the festival cost?","options":["It is free","There is a small entry fee","It costs the same as last year's ticket","Only weekend visits require payment"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The reporter states admission remains free, though food bank donations are encouraged at the gates."},{"q":"When does the festival run each day?","options":["From noon until five","From five until ten in the evening","Only on weekend afternoons","From five until midnight"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The report says the festival runs every evening from five until ten."},{"q":"What can be inferred about the festival's popularity over time?","options":["It has stayed about the same size","It has grown significantly since it started","It is smaller than it used to be","It attracts mostly out-of-country tourists"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The report says it began as a modest display of a few strings of bulbs and has grown into one of the region's largest winter attractions with over eighty thousand visitors, implying significant growth."}]},{"id":"new-transit-line-opening-news","title":"News Item: Eastside Rapid Bus Line","instructions":"You will hear a news report. Listen carefully, then answer the questions. You will hear the report only once.","setup":"Listen to a local news report about a transit change.","transcript":[{"speaker":"Reporter","line":"Commuters in the city's east end have something to look forward to next month. The transit authority confirmed today that the new Eastside Rapid Bus line, known as the R7, will begin service on the fourth of August. The R7 will run in a dedicated lane separated from regular traffic, allowing buses to bypass the congestion that has long plagued Elmwood Avenue during rush hour. Transit officials estimate the new line will shave up to twenty minutes off the trip between the Eastgate neighbourhood and the downtown core. Buses will arrive every six minutes during peak periods, and every fifteen minutes in the evenings and on weekends. To encourage people to try the service, the transit authority is offering free rides on the R7 for the entire first week. Spokesperson Mark Delaney noted that the project came in slightly under budget, thanks to reusing existing roadway rather than widening the street. He added that if ridership targets are met, the authority hopes to extend the dedicated lane further east by the end of next year. For now, riders are encouraged to download the updated schedule from the transit website. Reporting downtown, I'm Sophie Tran."}],"questions":[{"q":"What is the main advantage of the R7 line?","options":["It is cheaper than other bus lines","It runs in a dedicated lane to avoid traffic","It travels farther than any existing route","It uses electric buses only"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The report says the R7 runs in a dedicated lane separated from regular traffic, letting buses bypass the congestion on Elmwood Avenue."},{"q":"When will the new line begin service?","options":["The fourth of August","The end of next year","Immediately","Next weekend"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The transit authority confirmed the R7 will begin service on the fourth of August (the end of next year refers only to a possible future extension)."},{"q":"What is being offered to encourage people to try the service?","options":["A permanent discount on fares","Free rides for the first week","A free transit pass for a month","Prizes for regular riders"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The report says the transit authority is offering free rides on the R7 for the entire first week."},{"q":"Why did the project come in under budget?","options":["Fewer buses were purchased than planned","Existing roadway was reused instead of widening the street","The government provided extra funding","Construction was delayed to save money"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Spokesperson Mark Delaney says the project came in slightly under budget thanks to reusing existing roadway rather than widening the street."},{"q":"What can be inferred about the future of the R7 line?","options":["It will be cancelled if it is unpopular","It may be extended farther east if ridership is strong","It will replace all other east-end bus routes","Its fares will increase after the first year"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The report says if ridership targets are met, the authority hopes to extend the dedicated lane further east, implying expansion depends on strong ridership."}]},{"id":"community-garden-heatwave-news","title":"News Item: Community Garden and the Heat Wave","instructions":"You will hear a news report. Listen carefully, then answer the questions. You will hear the report only once.","setup":"Listen to a local news report about a community response to hot weather.","transcript":[{"speaker":"Reporter","line":"As the region endures its third straight week of record-breaking heat, one neighbourhood is turning a challenge into an opportunity. Volunteers at the Fairview Community Garden have launched a new watering program to keep their vegetable plots alive through the drought, and to share the harvest with those who need it most. With water restrictions now in place across the city, the garden has installed several large rain barrels and a drip irrigation system that delivers water slowly to the roots, using far less than a garden hose would. Volunteer coordinator Fatima Osman explained that the efficient system lets the garden keep growing food even under the tightest restrictions. The garden has also opened a shaded rest area with cold water for anyone in the neighbourhood looking to escape the afternoon sun. Perhaps most notably, the group has pledged to donate a third of everything it grows this summer to the community centre's meal program, which has seen demand rise sharply during the heat. Osman says the garden proves that even a small plot of land can make a real difference. Environment Canada expects the heat to finally break by the weekend. I'm Devon Clarke, reporting."}],"questions":[{"q":"What is the main purpose of the new watering program?","options":["To win a gardening competition","To keep the garden alive during the drought and share the harvest","To reduce the community centre's water bill","To attract new volunteers to the garden"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The report says volunteers launched the program to keep vegetable plots alive through the drought and to share the harvest with those who need it most."},{"q":"Why did the garden install a drip irrigation system?","options":["It waters the plants faster than a hose","It uses far less water than a garden hose","It was donated for free by the city","It requires no volunteers to operate"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The report says the drip system delivers water slowly to the roots using far less than a garden hose would, which matters under the city's water restrictions."},{"q":"What has the garden done for people in the neighbourhood during the heat?","options":["Handed out free vegetables at the gate","Opened a shaded rest area with cold water","Set up a public swimming pool","Offered free gardening classes"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The report says the garden opened a shaded rest area with cold water for anyone looking to escape the afternoon sun."},{"q":"How much of the summer harvest will be donated to the meal program?","options":["All of it","About a third of it","Half of it","None of it"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The group pledged to donate a third of everything it grows this summer to the community centre's meal program."},{"q":"What can be inferred about demand at the community centre's meal program?","options":["It has fallen because of the heat","It has increased during the hot weather","It has stayed exactly the same","It only serves garden volunteers"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The report says the meal program has seen demand rise sharply during the heat, implying more people need it."}]}],"discussion":[{"id":"community-garden-expansion-planning","title":"Planning the Community Garden Expansion","instructions":"Listen to the discussion, then answer the questions. Choose the best answer for each question.","setup":"Three members of a community garden committee meet to decide how to spend a grant on expanding their garden plots.","transcript":[{"speaker":"Narrator","line":"You will hear three members of a community garden committee discussing how to use a new grant. First you have 30 seconds to read the questions."},{"speaker":"Priya","line":"Thanks for coming out, everyone. So we've finally got confirmation on the city grant. It's four thousand dollars, and the deadline to submit our plan is the end of next month."},{"speaker":"Daniel","line":"That's great news. My first thought is we should put most of it toward building a dozen new raised beds. We've had a waiting list of nearly thirty people for two years now."},{"speaker":"Marisol","line":"I hear you, Daniel, but I'd be careful about spending it all on beds. The truth is, half our current plots dry out because the irrigation system is falling apart. If we add more beds without fixing the water lines, we're just creating more problems."},{"speaker":"Priya","line":"That's a fair point. Marisol, how much do you think a new irrigation setup would run us?"},{"speaker":"Marisol","line":"I got a rough quote last week. A proper drip system for the whole site would be around twenty-five hundred. So it would take a big chunk, but it would serve everyone, not just the new members."},{"speaker":"Daniel","line":"Twenty-five hundred is a lot. That would only leave us fifteen hundred for beds, which is maybe four or five, not twelve. The waiting list is my main worry, honestly."},{"speaker":"Priya","line":"I understand both of you. But I actually lean toward Marisol's view here. If the existing members are frustrated because their plants keep dying, adding newcomers won't look good to the city when they review how we spent the money."},{"speaker":"Daniel","line":"Okay, but what if we didn't do the full drip system? Could we repair just the worst sections and save the rest for beds?"},{"speaker":"Marisol","line":"We could patch it, sure, but patching has been our approach for three years and it keeps breaking. I'd rather do it right once. Although... I'm not completely against a smaller number of beds this round."},{"speaker":"Priya","line":"Here's a thought. What if we do the full irrigation system now, add four raised beds with the remaining money, and then apply for a second grant next spring specifically for more beds?"},{"speaker":"Daniel","line":"That's actually not bad. The waiting list won't clear this year, but at least it starts moving, and next year we'd have reliable water for everything we build."},{"speaker":"Marisol","line":"I'd support that. It fixes the core problem first and still gives the newcomers something."},{"speaker":"Priya","line":"Great. So let's lock it in: full drip irrigation, four new beds this round, and I'll draft a proposal for a follow-up grant in the spring. Daniel, can you contact the people on the waiting list and let them know four spots are opening?"},{"speaker":"Daniel","line":"Sure, I'll email them this week. I'll make it clear more are coming next year."},{"speaker":"Marisol","line":"And I'll get the formal irrigation quote in writing so we can attach it to the grant paperwork."},{"speaker":"Priya","line":"Perfect. Let's meet again once we have the numbers confirmed."}],"questions":[{"q":"What is Daniel's main concern at the start of the discussion?","options":["The grant deadline is too soon to prepare a plan","There is a long waiting list of people wanting garden plots","The irrigation system is too expensive to repair","The city might reject their spending plan"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Daniel opens by pushing for a dozen new raised beds because there has been a waiting list of nearly thirty people for two years, and he later calls the waiting list his 'main worry.'"},{"q":"Why does Marisol argue against spending all the money on new beds?","options":["The new beds would cost more than the grant provides","Half the current plots dry out because the irrigation is failing","The city grant cannot legally be used for construction","There is not enough space on the site for more beds"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Marisol says half the current plots dry out because the irrigation system is falling apart, so adding beds without fixing the water lines just creates more problems."},{"q":"Whose view does Priya say she leans toward during the discussion?","options":["Daniel's, because clearing the waiting list is the priority","Marisol's, because fixing the water problem should come first","Neither, because she wants to split the money evenly","Both equally, because she cannot decide"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Priya explicitly says 'I actually lean toward Marisol's view here,' reasoning that adding newcomers while existing members' plants die would look bad to the city."},{"q":"What compromise does Daniel eventually accept?","options":["Repairing only the worst sections of the irrigation this year","Building twelve beds and delaying all irrigation work","Fixing the full irrigation now and adding only four beds this round","Returning the grant and reapplying for a larger amount"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Daniel warms to Priya's plan of full irrigation now plus four beds this round, saying the waiting list at least starts moving and next year they'll have reliable water for everything they build."},{"q":"What is the final decision the group reaches?","options":["Install full drip irrigation, add four beds, and apply for another grant in spring","Split the grant evenly between beds and irrigation repairs","Spend the entire grant on twelve new raised beds","Patch the irrigation and use the rest for as many beds as possible"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Priya locks it in: full drip irrigation, four new beds this round, and a follow-up grant proposal for the spring."},{"q":"What task does Priya ask Daniel to do?","options":["Get a written quote for the irrigation system","Draft the follow-up grant proposal","Contact the waiting-list members about the four openings","Meet with the city to confirm the grant terms"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Priya asks Daniel to contact the people on the waiting list about the four opening spots; Marisol takes the written quote and Priya herself drafts the follow-up proposal."}]},{"id":"office-move-logistics-meeting","title":"Deciding on the Office Relocation Date","instructions":"Listen to the discussion, then answer the questions. Choose the best answer for each question.","setup":"Three coworkers meet to plan when and how their team will move to a new office on another floor.","transcript":[{"speaker":"Narrator","line":"You will hear three coworkers planning their team's move to a new office. First you have 30 seconds to read the questions."},{"speaker":"Trevor","line":"Okay, so facilities confirmed the new space on the eighth floor is ready. We just need to decide when we actually move and how we handle it without shutting down the whole team."},{"speaker":"Naomi","line":"My preference would be a weekend move. If we do it on a Saturday, the movers come in, everything's set up, and people walk into a working desk on Monday. No lost productivity."},{"speaker":"Karim","line":"A weekend does keep things clean, but weekend rates for the moving company are almost double. Our budget for this is pretty tight. I'd rather do it on a slow weekday, maybe a Friday, and just accept a bit of disruption."},{"speaker":"Trevor","line":"How much of a difference are we talking, Karim?"},{"speaker":"Karim","line":"The quote for a Saturday was about sixteen hundred. The same crew on a weekday is closer to nine hundred. That's a real gap when we're watching every dollar this quarter."},{"speaker":"Naomi","line":"I get the cost issue, but think about what a Friday move does. Half the team can't work because their computers are boxed up, and the help desk gets swamped Monday when nothing's plugged in right. That lost time has a cost too, it's just harder to see."},{"speaker":"Trevor","line":"Both of those are valid. Naomi, is there any version of a weekday move that avoids the productivity hit?"},{"speaker":"Naomi","line":"Honestly, not really. If people are in the building, they'll try to work, and it'll be chaos. The only clean weekday option is asking everyone to work from home that day, but not everyone can."},{"speaker":"Karim","line":"Wait, that might actually solve it. What if we pick a Friday, and make it a mandatory work-from-home day for the whole team? The movers get an empty office, we pay the weekday rate, and nobody's productivity takes a hit because they're all working remotely."},{"speaker":"Naomi","line":"Huh. That's clever. As long as IT sets up remote access in advance, that could genuinely work. I'd be on board with that."},{"speaker":"Trevor","line":"I like it too. It gets us Karim's lower cost and Naomi's no-downtime goal. The one thing I want to confirm is that IT can have everyone's remote access ready before that Friday."},{"speaker":"Karim","line":"I can check with IT this week. If they say they need more lead time, we push the date back a week rather than risk it."},{"speaker":"Trevor","line":"Agreed. So the plan is a Friday move, whole team works from home that day, contingent on IT confirming remote access. Naomi, can you put together the communication to the team once we've got a firm date?"},{"speaker":"Naomi","line":"Absolutely. I'll draft it but hold off sending until Karim hears back from IT."},{"speaker":"Trevor","line":"Great. And I'll let facilities know we're leaning toward a Friday so they can pencil in the movers."}],"questions":[{"q":"What does Naomi prefer at the beginning of the discussion?","options":["Moving on a weekday to save money","Moving on a Saturday so no work time is lost","Delaying the move until the next quarter","Having each person move their own desk"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Naomi's stated preference is a weekend move, specifically a Saturday, so people walk into a working desk Monday with no lost productivity."},{"q":"Why does Karim object to Naomi's initial proposal?","options":["The new office will not be ready on a weekend","The movers are not available on Saturdays","Weekend moving rates are nearly double the weekday rate","The team would have to come in on their day off"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Karim says weekend rates are almost double, citing about sixteen hundred for Saturday versus nine hundred on a weekday, and the budget is tight this quarter."},{"q":"What downside of a weekday move does Naomi emphasize?","options":["It would damage the team's equipment","It would cause lost productivity and overwhelm the help desk","It would take longer than a weekend move","It would require hiring a second moving crew"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Naomi argues a Friday move means half the team can't work with boxed-up computers and the help desk gets swamped Monday, a hidden cost."},{"q":"Who proposes the idea that resolves the disagreement?","options":["Trevor suggests postponing the move","Naomi suggests hiring more movers","Karim suggests a Friday move with everyone working from home","Naomi suggests splitting the move over two days"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Karim proposes a Friday move made a mandatory work-from-home day, giving the weekday rate while avoiding the productivity hit."},{"q":"What condition must be met for the plan to go ahead?","options":["The budget must be increased for this quarter","IT must confirm remote access is ready before that Friday","Facilities must repaint the eighth-floor office","The whole team must agree to come in on Saturday"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The plan is contingent on IT confirming everyone's remote access is ready before the Friday; otherwise they push the date back a week."},{"q":"What does Naomi agree to do?","options":["Check with IT about remote access","Draft the team communication but wait to send it","Notify facilities to book the movers","Negotiate a lower rate with the moving company"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Naomi agrees to draft the team communication but hold off sending it until Karim hears back from IT. Karim checks with IT; Trevor notifies facilities."}]},{"id":"library-teen-program-budget","title":"Budgeting for the New Teen Program","instructions":"Listen to the discussion, then answer the questions. Choose the best answer for each question.","setup":"Three staff members at a public library discuss how to divide a small budget for a new after-school program for teenagers.","transcript":[{"speaker":"Narrator","line":"You will hear three library staff members planning the budget for a new teen program. First you have 30 seconds to read the questions."},{"speaker":"Gwen","line":"So the board approved three thousand dollars for the teen after-school program this fall. We need to figure out where it goes. I've been thinking the biggest need is new laptops for the coding club."},{"speaker":"Anthony","line":"Laptops would be nice, but they eat up a budget fast. Three decent ones and we've already spent most of the three thousand. I think what actually gets teens through the door is snacks and a comfortable space. Kids come for the food and the hangout, then they stay for the programs."},{"speaker":"Reema","line":"I've seen that too, Anthony. When I ran the summer reading nights, attendance doubled the week we started offering pizza. But I don't think it's either-or. We could do a modest amount on both."},{"speaker":"Gwen","line":"The problem is, if we spread it thin, we can't run a real coding club. You need actual computers for that, and the ones we have now are ancient. They can barely open a browser."},{"speaker":"Anthony","line":"That's true, they are slow. But do we need brand-new laptops? The IT department mentioned they're retiring a batch of machines that are only three years old. We might be able to get those refurbished for almost nothing."},{"speaker":"Gwen","line":"Wait, really? If those are available, that changes everything. Three-year-old machines would be a huge upgrade from what we've got."},{"speaker":"Reema","line":"That could free up most of the budget. So then the question is what we do with the three thousand if the laptops are basically free."},{"speaker":"Anthony","line":"I'd put a chunk into a weekly snack budget and some comfortable furniture, beanbags, that kind of thing. That's what builds the regular crowd."},{"speaker":"Reema","line":"I agree with the snacks, but I'd also want to set aside something for a few paid workshop leaders. A volunteer-only model burned us out last year. Even a small stipend keeps good instructors coming back."},{"speaker":"Gwen","line":"That's a good point, Reema. The program's only as good as the people running it. Okay, I'm coming around. If IT comes through on the laptops, I'd be happy putting the money toward snacks, some furniture, and workshop stipends."},{"speaker":"Anthony","line":"Same. That covers the space, the draw, and the quality all at once."},{"speaker":"Reema","line":"So it all hinges on those refurbished machines. Anthony, can you confirm with IT whether we can actually have them and how many?"},{"speaker":"Anthony","line":"Yeah, I'll talk to them tomorrow and find out the count and condition."},{"speaker":"Gwen","line":"And if for some reason IT can't give us the laptops, we go back to the drawing board, because then the computers have to come first."},{"speaker":"Reema","line":"Agreed. I'll sketch out a draft budget for both scenarios so we're ready either way."},{"speaker":"Gwen","line":"Perfect. Let's reconvene once Anthony has an answer from IT."}],"questions":[{"q":"What does Gwen initially think is the biggest need for the program?","options":["Snacks to attract more teenagers","New laptops for the coding club","Paid workshop leaders","Comfortable furniture for the space"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Gwen opens by saying the biggest need is new laptops for the coding club, because the current computers are ancient and can barely open a browser."},{"q":"What does Anthony believe actually draws teens to the program?","options":["The latest technology and equipment","Snacks and a comfortable place to hang out","A wide range of scheduled workshops","Free transportation to the library"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Anthony argues that what gets teens through the door is snacks and a comfortable space; they come for the food and hangout, then stay for the programs."},{"q":"What key piece of information changes the direction of the discussion?","options":["The board approved more money than expected","IT is retiring three-year-old machines that could be refurbished cheaply","A local company offered to donate new laptops","The coding club was cancelled for the fall"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Anthony reveals IT is retiring a batch of only three-year-old machines that could be refurbished for almost nothing, which Reema notes could free up most of the budget."},{"q":"What does Reema add that the others had not raised?","options":["Setting aside money for paid workshop leaders","Buying brand-new laptops after all","Charging teens a small membership fee","Moving the program to a larger room"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Reema argues for setting aside money for paid workshop leaders, noting a volunteer-only model burned them out last year."},{"q":"What does the group's final plan depend on?","options":["The board approving additional funds","Whether IT can provide the refurbished laptops","Reema finding enough volunteers","The teens signing up in advance"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Reema says it all hinges on the refurbished machines, and Gwen adds that if IT can't provide them the computers must come first."},{"q":"What will happen if IT cannot supply the laptops?","options":["The program will be postponed until next year","They will spend the budget on snacks and furniture anyway","They will go back to the drawing board and prioritize computers","They will ask the board for a second grant"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Gwen says if IT can't give them the laptops, they go back to the drawing board because then the computers have to come first."}]},{"id":"staff-holiday-party-planning","title":"Organizing the Staff Holiday Party","instructions":"Listen to the discussion, then answer the questions. Choose the best answer for each question.","setup":"Three members of a workplace social committee meet to decide the format and timing of this year's staff holiday party.","transcript":[{"speaker":"Narrator","line":"You will hear three members of a social committee planning a staff holiday party. First you have 30 seconds to read the questions."},{"speaker":"Lena","line":"Alright, the holiday party. Last year we did the fancy dinner downtown and, honestly, the feedback was mixed. Let's figure out what we're doing differently this time."},{"speaker":"Omar","line":"The main complaint I heard was the timing. A Friday evening downtown meant people with kids or long commutes just skipped it. Turnout was maybe sixty percent. I'd push for a lunchtime party during a workday instead, right in the office."},{"speaker":"Chantelle","line":"A daytime party would definitely get more people, but it loses something. Part of what makes it feel special is that it's an evening event, people dress up, they can bring a partner. An office lunch feels more like a longer meeting with cake."},{"speaker":"Lena","line":"That's the tension, isn't it? Evening feels festive but excludes people; daytime is inclusive but less special. Omar, what was the turnout issue exactly?"},{"speaker":"Omar","line":"Right around sixty percent came last year, and the ones who didn't were mostly parents and folks commuting from out of town. If we want the whole team to feel included, the evening slot works against us."},{"speaker":"Chantelle","line":"I don't dispute the numbers. I just don't want to strip away the celebration entirely. There's got to be a middle ground."},{"speaker":"Lena","line":"What if we did an afternoon event that starts during work hours and flows into the early evening? Say, a party from three to six, on-site or somewhere close. People who need to leave for pickup can catch the first part, and those who want to stay and celebrate can."},{"speaker":"Omar","line":"That's a smart split. Starting in work hours means people don't have to make a special trip back, and a three o'clock start is a lot easier for parents than seven."},{"speaker":"Chantelle","line":"And a three-to-six window still lets us do it properly, catered food, maybe a venue with some atmosphere rather than the break room. I could get behind that. It keeps the festive feel without the late-night barrier."},{"speaker":"Lena","line":"Great, so we're aligned on an afternoon-into-evening party, roughly three to six, at an off-site venue that's close by. Now, budget. Last year's dinner cost us over four thousand and people still complained."},{"speaker":"Omar","line":"An afternoon reception with appetizers instead of a full plated dinner should come in well under that. Maybe half."},{"speaker":"Chantelle","line":"That works. I'd rather spend less on the food and put a little toward a nicer space and some decorations. Presentation goes a long way."},{"speaker":"Lena","line":"Sounds like a plan. Chantelle, since you care about the atmosphere, would you scout two or three nearby venues and get quotes?"},{"speaker":"Chantelle","line":"Happy to. I'll have options by the end of next week."},{"speaker":"Omar","line":"And I'll send out a save-the-date so people can block off the afternoon early."},{"speaker":"Lena","line":"Perfect. I'll handle the catering shortlist once Chantelle picks the venue."}],"questions":[{"q":"According to Omar, what was the main problem with last year's party?","options":["The food was disappointing","The Friday evening timing kept many people from attending","The venue was too small for the whole team","It went over budget"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Omar says the main complaint was the timing; a Friday evening downtown meant parents and long-commute staff skipped it, with turnout around sixty percent."},{"q":"Why does Chantelle initially resist Omar's proposal for a daytime party?","options":["It would cost more than an evening event","It would be harder to schedule around work","An office lunch feels less special than a festive evening event","Fewer people would be able to attend"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Chantelle worries a daytime office lunch loses the special feel, saying it would feel like a longer meeting with cake rather than a real celebration."},{"q":"What compromise does Lena propose?","options":["Holding two separate parties, one daytime and one evening","An afternoon party from about three to six that starts in work hours","Keeping the downtown dinner but on a different night","Cancelling the party and giving gift cards instead"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Lena suggests an afternoon-into-early-evening party, roughly three to six, so parents can catch the start and others can stay to celebrate."},{"q":"Why does Omar think a three o'clock start is better than seven?","options":["The venue is cheaper in the afternoon","It is easier for parents and avoids a special trip back","More catering options are available earlier","The office is quieter at that time"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Omar notes that starting in work hours means people don't make a special trip back, and a three o'clock start is much easier for parents than seven."},{"q":"What do the three agree to do about the budget compared to last year?","options":["Spend the same amount but on a bigger venue","Spend more to improve the food quality","Spend less by serving appetizers instead of a plated dinner","Ask staff to contribute to the cost"],"answer":2,"explanation":"They agree an afternoon reception with appetizers rather than a full plated dinner should cost about half of last year's four-thousand-dollar dinner."},{"q":"What task does Lena assign to Chantelle?","options":["Sending out the save-the-date notice","Scouting nearby venues and getting quotes","Preparing the catering shortlist","Collecting feedback from last year's attendees"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Because Chantelle cares about atmosphere, Lena asks her to scout two or three nearby venues and get quotes. Omar sends the save-the-date; Lena handles catering."}]}],"viewpoints":[{"id":"viewpoints-backyard-hens","title":"Listening to Viewpoints: Backyard Chickens in the City","instructions":"You will hear a radio segment in which a host discusses a local issue and presents differing viewpoints. Listen carefully, then answer the questions. You may take notes.","setup":"This is a segment from a community affairs radio program discussing a proposed change to a city bylaw.","transcript":[{"speaker":"Host","line":"Welcome back to City Corner. Tonight we're looking at a proposal before council that would let residents keep a small number of backyard hens, up to four birds, on residential lots. It's a topic that has really divided our listeners, and I've been reading through your emails all week. Supporters say fresh eggs and a hands-on lesson in where food comes from are worth celebrating. One woman wrote that her kids now understand food waste because the hens eat the scraps. Community garden groups have jumped in too, arguing that hens fit naturally with the push to grow more food close to home."},{"speaker":"Host","line":"But the opposition is just as vocal, and honestly, some of their points are hard to dismiss. The most common worry isn't noise, since the bylaw would ban roosters anyway. It's about rats and other pests being drawn to the feed, and whether the city has the inspectors to enforce coop standards. A retired veterinarian emailed to warn about disease spreading if coops aren't cleaned properly. And a few neighbours simply don't want the smell drifting over the fence on a hot July afternoon."},{"speaker":"Host","line":"Where do I land? I'll admit the enforcement question gives me pause. The health and pest concerns can be managed with good rules, but rules only work if someone checks on them, and our bylaw office is already stretched thin. So I'd support a small pilot program in one neighbourhood first, rather than opening it up city-wide overnight. Let's prove it can be done responsibly before we scale it up. That's my two cents. The line is open, so give us a call."}],"questions":[{"q":"What is the main topic of this segment?","options":["A proposed bylaw allowing residents to keep backyard hens","A new community garden opening in the neighbourhood","A city plan to reduce household food waste","A debate about noise complaints from farm animals"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The host opens by stating the proposal before council would let residents keep up to four backyard hens on residential lots, which frames the entire segment."},{"q":"According to supporters, what is one benefit of keeping backyard hens?","options":["They increase the resale value of homes","They teach children where food comes from and reduce food waste","They provide a source of income for families","They keep pests away from gardens"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The host cites a listener whose children now understand food waste because the hens eat scraps, and mentions the hands-on lesson in where food comes from."},{"q":"Why does the host say noise is NOT the main concern of opponents?","options":["Because hens are naturally quiet animals","Because the coops would be soundproofed","Because the bylaw would ban roosters","Because the birds would be kept indoors"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The host explicitly says the most common worry isn't noise, since the bylaw would ban roosters anyway."},{"q":"What concern did the retired veterinarian raise?","options":["That hens would attract predators like coyotes","That disease could spread if coops aren't cleaned properly","That the birds would suffer in cold weather","That eggs from backyard hens are unsafe to eat"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The host says a retired veterinarian emailed to warn about disease spreading if coops aren't cleaned properly."},{"q":"What is the host's own view on the proposal?","options":["He fully supports allowing hens across the whole city right away","He opposes the proposal entirely because of health risks","He supports trying a small pilot program in one neighbourhood first","He is completely undecided and takes no position"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The host says he would support a small pilot program in one neighbourhood first rather than opening it up city-wide overnight."},{"q":"What does the host identify as the issue that most gives him pause?","options":["The cost of the birds and feed for families","Whether the city can enforce the coop standards","The smell drifting over neighbours' fences","The risk of the hens escaping into the streets"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The host says the enforcement question gives him pause, because rules only work if someone checks on them and the bylaw office is already stretched thin."}]},{"id":"viewpoints-four-day-week","title":"Listening to Viewpoints: The Four-Day Work Week","instructions":"You will hear a podcast segment in which a host discusses a workplace trend and presents differing viewpoints. Listen carefully, then answer the questions. You may take notes.","setup":"This is an episode of a workplace-issues podcast examining a trend that some Canadian employers have been testing.","transcript":[{"speaker":"Host","line":"On today's episode of Working Hours, we're digging into the four-day work week. The idea is simple: employees work Monday to Thursday, take Friday off, and still collect their full salary, as long as they hit the same targets in fewer hours. A handful of Canadian companies ran trials this past year, and the results have people talking. Managers who backed the change told us productivity actually held steady or even climbed, because staff wasted less time in long meetings and came back on Monday genuinely rested. One tech firm in Waterloo reported that sick days dropped by nearly a third."},{"speaker":"Host","line":"Not everyone is sold, though. Some business owners I spoke with, especially in retail and healthcare, say the model just doesn't fit their world. A store can't close its doors an extra day when customers still show up seven days a week. Others worry that cramming five days of work into four simply burns people out faster, trading a relaxing Friday for four exhausting days. And one manager made a fair point: the trials that succeeded were mostly at desk jobs where output is easy to measure. It's much harder to apply the same math to a nurse or a bus driver."},{"speaker":"Host","line":"My take? I'm cautiously optimistic, but I don't think one size fits all. For office teams with clear deliverables, the evidence looks promising, and I'd love to see more employers give it an honest trial. But I'd be careful about treating it as a magic fix for every industry. The real lesson, I think, isn't the number four. It's that we should be measuring people by what they accomplish, not by how many hours they sit at a desk. Anyway, that's where I've landed. What about you?"}],"questions":[{"q":"What is the main topic of this podcast segment?","options":["How to reduce the number of meetings at work","The four-day work week and whether it works","Why sick days are rising in Canadian workplaces","The difference between office jobs and retail jobs"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The host opens by saying the episode is digging into the four-day work week and spends the segment weighing whether it works."},{"q":"According to the host, how is the four-day week supposed to work?","options":["Employees work fewer hours for reduced pay","Employees work four days but must work longer weekends","Employees take Friday off and keep full pay if they hit their targets","Employees rotate which day off they take each week"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The host says employees work Monday to Thursday, take Friday off, and still collect full salary as long as they hit the same targets."},{"q":"What specific result did the Waterloo tech firm report?","options":["Sick days dropped by nearly a third","Profits doubled within a year","Staff turnover fell to zero","Productivity dropped slightly"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The host states that one tech firm in Waterloo reported sick days dropped by nearly a third."},{"q":"Why do some retail and healthcare business owners say the model doesn't fit them?","options":["Their employees prefer working five days","Customers still need service seven days a week, so they can't close an extra day","They cannot afford to pay full salaries","Their staff already work only four days"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The host explains that a store can't close its doors an extra day when customers still show up seven days a week."},{"q":"What concern did one manager raise about the successful trials?","options":["They were too short to be reliable","They only involved very small companies","They were mostly at desk jobs where output is easy to measure","They ignored employee satisfaction"],"answer":2,"explanation":"A manager pointed out that the trials that succeeded were mostly desk jobs where output is easy to measure, unlike the work of a nurse or bus driver."},{"q":"What is the host's overall position?","options":["Every industry should adopt the four-day week immediately","The four-day week is a failed experiment","He is cautiously optimistic but doesn't think one size fits all","He believes hours worked matter more than results"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The host says he is cautiously optimistic but doesn't think one size fits all, favouring it for office teams while being careful about other industries."}]},{"id":"viewpoints-transit-fare-free","title":"Listening to Viewpoints: Free Public Transit","instructions":"You will hear a radio segment in which a host discusses a city proposal and presents differing viewpoints. Listen carefully, then answer the questions. You may take notes.","setup":"This is a current-affairs radio segment discussing a proposal that city council will vote on next month.","transcript":[{"speaker":"Host","line":"Good morning, and thanks for tuning in to The Commute. Next month, council votes on something that would touch nearly everyone in this city: making public transit completely free. No more fares, no more monthly passes, just hop on the bus or the light rail and go. The council members pushing the idea say it would get cars off the road, cut our emissions, and give a real break to people on tight budgets who spend a big chunk of their pay just getting to work. A local advocacy group added that free transit would especially help seniors and students, two groups that ride often but earn little."},{"speaker":"Host","line":"The critics aren't against transit, and that's important to understand. Their question is about the money. Fares cover roughly a third of the system's operating costs, so if that revenue disappears, it has to come from somewhere, most likely higher property taxes. Some also warn that free rides could flood the buses beyond what the current fleet can handle, making service worse, not better, unless the city buys more vehicles first. And one transit planner cautioned that without fare revenue, the agency might delay buying the new low-floor buses that riders with mobility issues really depend on."},{"speaker":"Host","line":"So where do I sit on this? I think the goals are worth chasing, but the timing worries me. Before we make it free, we need to know we can actually run more buses more often, because a free ride you have to wait forty minutes for isn't much of a gift. I'd rather see the city first invest in frequency and reliability, then talk about dropping fares once the system can handle the crowds. Get the buses running well, and the rest will follow. That's my read. Lines are open."}],"questions":[{"q":"What proposal is this segment about?","options":["Building a new light rail line across the city","Making public transit completely free","Raising transit fares to fund new buses","Reducing the number of bus routes"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The host says council will vote on making public transit completely free, with no fares or monthly passes."},{"q":"According to supporters, what are two benefits of free transit?","options":["Faster buses and cleaner stations","More jobs and lower property taxes","Fewer cars on the road and help for people on tight budgets","Shorter routes and newer vehicles"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Supporters say it would get cars off the road, cut emissions, and give a real break to people on tight budgets."},{"q":"Which two groups does the advocacy group say would especially benefit?","options":["Seniors and students","Drivers and cyclists","Tourists and commuters","Business owners and workers"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The advocacy group said free transit would especially help seniors and students, who ride often but earn little."},{"q":"What is the critics' main concern?","options":["That people don't actually want to ride transit","That the lost fare revenue would have to be replaced, likely through higher taxes","That free transit would increase pollution","That drivers would refuse to work without fares"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Critics point out that fares cover about a third of operating costs, so the lost revenue would have to come from somewhere, most likely higher property taxes."},{"q":"What did the transit planner specifically warn about?","options":["That buses would break down more often","That fares would eventually have to return","That the agency might delay buying new low-floor buses needed by riders with mobility issues","That drivers would need to be retrained"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The transit planner cautioned that without fare revenue the agency might delay buying the new low-floor buses that riders with mobility issues depend on."},{"q":"What does the host recommend?","options":["Making transit free immediately","Rejecting the proposal completely","Investing in frequency and reliability first, then considering free fares","Raising fares to buy more buses"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The host says he'd rather the city first invest in frequency and reliability, then talk about dropping fares once the system can handle the crowds."}]},{"id":"viewpoints-homework-ban","title":"Listening to Viewpoints: Should Elementary Schools Ban Homework?","instructions":"You will hear a podcast segment in which a host discusses an education debate and presents differing viewpoints. Listen carefully, then answer the questions. You may take notes.","setup":"This is an episode of an education podcast examining a policy that some local school boards are considering.","transcript":[{"speaker":"Host","line":"Welcome to Class Notes. Today's question is one that comes up at nearly every parent-teacher night: should elementary schools do away with homework altogether? A couple of local boards are seriously weighing a no-homework policy for kids up to grade six. The teachers who back it point to research suggesting that homework does little for academic results at that age. They argue that young children learn more from unstructured play, family time, and simply reading for fun than from worksheets at the kitchen table. One grade-three teacher told me she'd rather her students spend the evening outside than filling in math drills."},{"speaker":"Host","line":"On the other side, plenty of parents and educators aren't ready to let go. Some worry that a little nightly homework builds the routines and self-discipline kids will need later in high school, and that dropping it entirely leaves them unprepared. Others raised an equity angle I hadn't considered: for children who don't get much academic support at home, a short assignment can be a valuable bridge to the classroom, and homework at least keeps parents in the loop about what's being taught. A few also pointed out that reading logs, which many parents love, are technically homework too."},{"speaker":"Host","line":"So where do I come down? I'm sympathetic to the no-homework camp, but I don't think it's all or nothing. The evidence against piles of worksheets for little kids is pretty convincing, and I'd happily see those disappear. But I wouldn't scrap everything. Twenty minutes of reading a night is homework I'll defend to the end, because that habit pays off for a lifetime. So my vote is: cut the busywork, keep the reading. That feels like the sensible middle ground to me. What do you think? Send us a message."}],"questions":[{"q":"What is the main question this segment explores?","options":["Whether elementary schools should ban homework","Whether children should start school at a younger age","How much reading children should do each day","Whether high schools give too much homework"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The host opens by asking whether elementary schools should do away with homework altogether for kids up to grade six."},{"q":"What do teachers who support the ban argue?","options":["That homework should be replaced with online lessons","That young children learn more from play, family time, and reading for fun","That homework should be assigned only on weekends","That parents should teach the material at home instead"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Supporting teachers argue young children learn more from unstructured play, family time, and reading for fun than from worksheets."},{"q":"What equity concern did some parents and educators raise?","options":["That homework costs money for supplies","That some children have no quiet place to study","That homework can be a valuable bridge for children who lack academic support at home","That wealthier families hire tutors"],"answer":2,"explanation":"They raised the point that for children who don't get much academic support at home, a short assignment can be a valuable bridge to the classroom."},{"q":"According to the segment, why do some argue a little homework is useful?","options":["It builds routines and self-discipline for high school","It raises test scores dramatically","It reduces screen time at home","It gives teachers less marking to do"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Some worry that a little nightly homework builds the routines and self-discipline kids will need later in high school."},{"q":"What point was made about reading logs?","options":["They should be graded more strictly","They are technically a form of homework too","They are unpopular with parents","They replace all other assignments"],"answer":1,"explanation":"A few people pointed out that reading logs, which many parents love, are technically homework too."},{"q":"What is the host's own conclusion?","options":["Ban all homework, including reading","Keep homework exactly as it is now","Cut the busywork but keep nightly reading","Leave the decision entirely to parents"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The host concludes his vote is to cut the busywork worksheets but keep twenty minutes of reading a night, which he calls the sensible middle ground."}]}]},"writing":{"email":[{"id":"noisy-upstairs-neighbour-complaint","kind":"email","title":"Complaint About a Noisy Upstairs Neighbour","prompt":"You have lived in your apartment for two years and have recently had trouble sleeping because of loud noise from the unit above you late at night. You have spoken to the neighbour once, but nothing has changed. Write an email to your building manager, Ms. Diaz.","bullets":["Explain the problem and how it is affecting you","Describe what you have already done to try to solve it","State what you would like the manager to do next"],"timeMin":27,"wordRange":"150-200","modelAnswer":"Dear Ms. Diaz,\n\nI am writing to report an ongoing noise problem in my unit, Apartment 305. For the past three weeks, I have been kept awake almost every night by loud footsteps, furniture being dragged, and music coming from the unit directly above mine, often between midnight and 2 a.m.\n\nI have already tried to resolve this on my own. Two weeks ago, I spoke politely with the tenant in Apartment 405 and explained that the noise was disturbing my sleep. He was friendly at the time, but unfortunately the noise has continued without any real change.\n\nBecause I work early mornings, the lost sleep is now seriously affecting my health and my ability to concentrate at my job. I would appreciate it if you could formally remind the tenant of the building's quiet hours and, if possible, follow up with me afterward to confirm the issue has been addressed.\n\nThank you for your attention to this matter. I look forward to your reply.\n\nSincerely,\nJordan Mills","rubricTips":["Keep a firm but polite, semi-formal tone — you want cooperation, not conflict.","Open with a clear one-sentence statement of purpose and your unit number.","Use specific details (times, dates, type of noise) to make the complaint credible.","Show you acted reasonably first, so the manager sees you as fair.","End with a concrete, actionable request plus a request for follow-up.","Avoid insulting or blaming language about the neighbour; describe behaviour, not character."]},{"id":"request-shift-swap-coworker","kind":"email","title":"Requesting a Shift Swap With a Coworker","prompt":"You work part-time at a grocery store and are scheduled to work this Saturday, but you need that day off for a family event. A coworker named Priya has told you she is usually free on weekends. Write an email to Priya asking her to switch shifts with you.","bullets":["Explain why you need Saturday off","Ask Priya to swap shifts and give the details","Offer to do something in return"],"timeMin":27,"wordRange":"150-200","modelAnswer":"Hi Priya,\n\nI hope you're having a good week! I'm writing to ask a favour, and I completely understand if you can't help out.\n\nI'm scheduled to work this Saturday from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m., but my sister is having her wedding that afternoon, and I really don't want to miss it. I remembered you mentioning that weekends usually work well for you, so I thought I'd check.\n\nWould you be willing to take my Saturday shift? In exchange, I'd be happy to cover one of your shifts next week — I'm free on Tuesday and Thursday, or any weekday that suits you better. Just let me know what works.\n\nIf you're able to swap, I'll email our supervisor, Mr. Chen, right away so it's approved and updated in the schedule well before the weekend.\n\nThanks so much for considering it, Priya. I really appreciate it, and I owe you one either way!\n\nTalk soon,\nSam","rubricTips":["Use a warm, informal tone appropriate for a friendly coworker.","Lead with a soft opening so the request doesn't feel demanding.","Give exact shift details (day, time) so the swap is unambiguous.","Always include a genuine offer in return — reciprocity is a scored requirement here.","Mention getting supervisor approval to sound responsible and realistic.","Keep sentences natural; contractions (I'm, don't) fit this informal register."]},{"id":"apology-missed-book-club","kind":"email","title":"Apologizing for Missing a Commitment","prompt":"You promised to host your neighbourhood book club at your home last Thursday, but you forgot and were not there when members arrived. Several people showed up to a locked door. Write an email to the book club organizer, Helen, to apologize.","bullets":["Apologize and explain what happened","Acknowledge how it affected the other members","Offer to make things right"],"timeMin":27,"wordRange":"150-200","modelAnswer":"Dear Helen,\n\nI owe you and the whole book club a sincere apology for last Thursday. I had promised to host our meeting at my home, but I completely lost track of the date and was out running errands when everyone arrived. I feel terrible that several members drove over only to find a locked door.\n\nThere is really no good excuse. It has been a hectic few weeks, and I failed to add the meeting to my calendar the way I usually do. I know that everyone sets aside time for these evenings, and it was unfair to waste it because of my carelessness.\n\nTo make things right, I would like to host the next meeting and provide coffee and dessert for the group. I have already put the date in my calendar and set two reminders so this will not happen again.\n\nPlease pass along my apologies to the other members. I hope you will all give me the chance to make it up to you.\n\nWarm regards,\nMarcus","rubricTips":["Take clear responsibility early; avoid over-explaining or making excuses.","Acknowledge the specific inconvenience you caused others — this shows empathy.","Offer a concrete remedy (host next time, provide refreshments).","Use a sincere, slightly warm-formal tone suited to a friendly community group.","Reassure the reader it won't recur by naming a small preventive step.","Close by asking to pass on the apology and to rebuild goodwill."]},{"id":"invitation-retirement-party-colleague","kind":"email","title":"Inviting a Colleague to a Retirement Party","prompt":"A long-serving member of your team, Mr. Watson, is retiring at the end of the month. You are organizing a surprise party and want to invite a former colleague, Rachel, who now works at another company. Write an email inviting her.","bullets":["Invite Rachel and explain the occasion","Give the important details of the event","Ask her to keep it a surprise and to reply"],"timeMin":27,"wordRange":"150-200","modelAnswer":"Hi Rachel,\n\nIt's been far too long! I hope things are going well at your new job. I'm writing with some news and an invitation I think you'll love.\n\nMr. Watson is finally retiring at the end of this month after twenty-five years with our team, and a few of us are throwing him a surprise party to celebrate. Since you worked so closely with him for years, it wouldn't feel complete without you there.\n\nHere are the details: the party is on Friday, June 27th, at 6 p.m. at the Riverside Community Centre on Maple Street. We're planning a buffet dinner, and there's plenty of parking on site. Feel free to bring a card or a favourite memory to share during the toasts.\n\nOne important thing — it's a surprise, so please don't mention anything if you happen to run into him! Could you let me know by June 20th whether you can make it, so we have an accurate headcount?\n\nHope to see you there!\n\nBest,\nDana","rubricTips":["Reconnect briefly at the top since the reader is a former colleague.","State the occasion and why her presence matters personally.","List event details clearly: date, time, place, and any extras.","Explicitly stress the surprise element — it's a listed requirement.","Ask for an RSVP with a deadline to make the request actionable.","Keep the tone friendly and upbeat, fitting a celebration."]},{"id":"request-refund-damaged-delivery","kind":"email","title":"Requesting a Refund for a Damaged Delivery","prompt":"You ordered a new coffee table online from a furniture company. When it arrived yesterday, the tabletop was badly scratched and one leg was cracked. Write an email to the company's customer service department to resolve the problem.","bullets":["Describe the item and the damage","Explain what solution you want","Ask how the company will handle the return"],"timeMin":27,"wordRange":"150-200","modelAnswer":"Dear Customer Service Team,\n\nI am writing regarding an order I received yesterday that arrived in damaged condition. On June 3rd, I purchased a walnut coffee table (Order #48217) from your website, and it was delivered to my home the following week.\n\nUnfortunately, when I unpacked the table, I found that the tabletop had several deep scratches across the surface, and one of the legs was cracked near the base. The outer box showed no signs of damage, so I suspect the item was flawed before shipping. I have taken clear photos and can send them at your request.\n\nGiven the condition of the product, I would like a full refund rather than a replacement, as I now need the table sooner than a reorder would allow. I have kept all of the original packaging so the item can be returned.\n\nCould you please let me know how you would like to arrange the pickup or return, and how long the refund will take to process? I appreciate your prompt assistance.\n\nSincerely,\nLian Zhou","rubricTips":["Use a formal, businesslike tone for a company you don't know personally.","Include the order number and purchase date to help them locate the file.","Describe the damage precisely and offer proof (photos) to strengthen your case.","State your preferred resolution clearly and give a brief reason.","Ask specific procedural questions (pickup, timeline) so the reply is actionable.","Stay courteous — a polite complaint gets faster cooperation than an angry one."]},{"id":"workplace-note-remote-work-request","kind":"email","title":"Requesting to Work From Home","prompt":"Your city is expecting a major snowstorm tomorrow, and your commute involves a long bus ride that is often cancelled in bad weather. You would like to work from home for the day. Write an email to your supervisor, Mr. Okafor.","bullets":["Explain why you are making the request","Reassure your supervisor about your work","Ask for his approval"],"timeMin":27,"wordRange":"150-200","modelAnswer":"Dear Mr. Okafor,\n\nI am writing to request permission to work from home tomorrow, Thursday, due to the major snowstorm forecast for our area. My commute depends on the number 12 bus, which is often delayed or cancelled during heavy snow, and I am concerned I may not be able to get to the office safely or on time.\n\nI want to assure you that working remotely would not affect my productivity. I have my laptop and secure access to all the files I need, and my main task this week — finishing the quarterly report — can be done entirely from home. I will also be available on email and Teams throughout regular hours in case anything comes up.\n\nWould it be possible for you to approve this arrangement for tomorrow? If you would prefer, I am happy to check in with you first thing in the morning to confirm my progress.\n\nThank you for considering my request. Please let me know if you need any additional information.\n\nBest regards,\nAmara Bello","rubricTips":["Adopt a respectful, professional tone for a direct supervisor.","Give a clear, reasonable justification tied to safety and reliability.","Proactively address the manager's likely concern: your output won't drop.","Name the specific task and tools to make remote work sound seamless.","Ask directly for approval rather than assuming it.","Offer a small compromise (a morning check-in) to make yes easier to say."]},{"id":"community-concern-unsafe-crosswalk","kind":"email","title":"Raising a Community Safety Concern","prompt":"There is a busy crosswalk near an elementary school in your neighbourhood where cars frequently fail to stop for pedestrians. You are worried a child could be hurt. Write an email to your city councillor, Councillor Tran, to ask for action.","bullets":["Describe the problem and where it is","Explain why it is serious","Suggest what the city could do about it"],"timeMin":27,"wordRange":"150-200","modelAnswer":"Dear Councillor Tran,\n\nI am a resident of the Elmwood neighbourhood, and I am writing to raise an urgent safety concern about the crosswalk on Birch Avenue, directly in front of Elmwood Public School. Every school day, I see drivers speed through this crossing without stopping for children and parents who are waiting to cross.\n\nThis is a serious problem because the crosswalk is used by dozens of young children during the busy morning and afternoon rush. The road curves just before the crossing, so drivers often do not see pedestrians until it is too late. It feels like only a matter of time before someone is seriously injured.\n\nI would respectfully ask the city to consider a few measures: installing a flashing pedestrian signal, adding clearer road markings, and arranging for a crossing guard during school hours. Increased police presence to enforce the speed limit would also help.\n\nI would be grateful if you could look into this before an accident occurs. Thank you for your attention, and I look forward to hearing what steps can be taken.\n\nSincerely,\nDaniel Roy","rubricTips":["Use a formal, civic tone appropriate for an elected official.","Identify yourself as a local resident to establish standing.","Pinpoint the exact location so the issue can be investigated.","Explain the risk concretely (who is affected, why the road is dangerous).","Offer specific, realistic solutions rather than just complaining.","Close with a polite call to action and a note of urgency."]},{"id":"thank-you-community-centre-volunteer","kind":"email","title":"Thanking a Volunteer Coordinator","prompt":"You recently attended a free weekend cooking program for newcomers at your local community centre, and it helped you a great deal. You want to thank the volunteer coordinator, Ms. Petrov, and share how it helped. Write an email to her.","bullets":["Thank her and say what the program was","Explain how it helped you","Offer to help or stay involved in the future"],"timeMin":27,"wordRange":"150-200","modelAnswer":"Dear Ms. Petrov,\n\nI wanted to take a moment to thank you for organizing the free weekend cooking program for newcomers at the Lakeshore Community Centre. I attended all six sessions this spring, and it turned out to be one of the best experiences I have had since moving to Canada last year.\n\nThe program helped me in ways I did not expect. Beyond learning to cook affordable, healthy meals, I was able to practise my English in a relaxed setting and make friends with other newcomers in my area. Before the classes, I often felt isolated, but now I feel much more connected to my community and confident going out and meeting people.\n\nI would love to give something back. If you ever need a volunteer to help set up, translate for Russian-speaking participants, or assist new students, please count me in. I have some free time on weekends and would be glad to support future programs however I can.\n\nThank you again for everything you do. It truly makes a difference.\n\nWarm regards,\nElena Novak","rubricTips":["Use a warm, sincere tone — this is a genuine thank-you note.","Name the specific program and your involvement so the thanks feels real.","Give concrete examples of the benefit, not just vague praise.","Make the offer to help specific (tasks you can do, your availability).","Vary your sentence openings to keep the writing lively at CLB 8-10.","Close with a brief, heartfelt final line rather than a generic sign-off."]}],"survey":[{"id":"community-centre-weekend-hours","kind":"survey","title":"Community Centre Weekend Programming","prompt":"Your local community centre has extra funding to expand its weekend schedule and is surveying residents. The board can only afford to add ONE of the two proposed programs and wants members to share their preference. Read the two options below and choose the one you think would benefit the community more. Explain your reasons.","bullets":["Option A: A free drop-in family gym and swim on Saturday mornings for parents and young children","Option B: A subsidized evening skills workshop series (resume writing, budgeting, computer basics) for adults","Choose ONE option and give reasons to support your choice"],"timeMin":26,"wordRange":"150-200","modelAnswer":"I would strongly support Option B, the subsidized evening skills workshop series for adults, because it addresses a genuine gap in our neighbourhood. Many residents here are newcomers or people changing careers, and free classes in resume writing, budgeting, and computer basics could have a lasting impact on their lives. Unlike recreational activities, these workshops build practical skills that help people find better jobs and manage their finances more confidently.\n\nAnother reason I prefer Option B is the timing. Evening sessions allow working adults to attend after their shifts, whereas Saturday morning programs mainly serve families who are already at home. In this way, the workshops reach a group that is often overlooked.\n\nI understand that the family gym and swim would be popular and would encourage healthy habits in children, which is valuable. However, our area already has two public pools and several playgrounds, so recreation is well covered. What we lack is affordable adult education. For these reasons, I believe the skills workshops would provide the greater long-term benefit to our community.","rubricTips":["State your chosen option clearly in the opening sentence and never waver from it","Support your choice with at least two distinct reasons, each developed with a concrete example","Use linking words such as 'another reason', 'in this way', and 'for these reasons' to guide the reader","Briefly acknowledge the trade-off by conceding a strength of the option you rejected, then explain why your choice still wins","Aim for 150-200 words and keep the tone polite and community-minded"]},{"id":"office-remote-work-policy","kind":"survey","title":"Workplace Remote Policy Survey","prompt":"Your employer is updating its work-from-home policy and has asked staff to complete a short survey. Management will choose ONE of the two arrangements below for the coming year based on employee feedback. Read the options and indicate which one you prefer, giving reasons for your choice.","bullets":["Option A: Employees work from the office three fixed days a week and from home two days","Option B: Employees choose their own schedule and work from home whenever they wish, as long as the work is done","Choose ONE option and give reasons to support your choice"],"timeMin":26,"wordRange":"150-200","modelAnswer":"After considering both arrangements, I would choose Option A, the three fixed office days with two days at home. My main reason is that a predictable schedule helps teams collaborate. When everyone knows we will all be in the office on the same days, we can plan meetings, training, and brainstorming sessions without endless back-and-forth emails trying to find a time that works.\n\nSecondly, this hybrid model still protects work-life balance. Two guaranteed days at home let me focus on tasks that require concentration and save me several hours of commuting each week, which reduces stress.\n\nI can see the appeal of Option B, since complete flexibility sounds attractive and treats employees like responsible adults. However, in my experience, fully flexible schedules can make it difficult to reach colleagues and can leave newer staff feeling isolated with no one around to ask for help.\n\nFor these reasons, I believe the structured three-and-two arrangement offers the best balance between teamwork and personal flexibility, and I hope management adopts it.","rubricTips":["Open with a clear, unambiguous statement of the option you support","Give two or three separate reasons and expand each with detail rather than listing them briefly","Connect ideas with transitions like 'secondly', 'however', and 'for these reasons'","Address the competing option directly and explain its weakness to strengthen your position","Maintain a professional register suitable for addressing management"]},{"id":"apartment-shared-space-conversion","kind":"survey","title":"Apartment Building Shared Space","prompt":"The management of your apartment building has an empty ground-floor room and is surveying tenants about how to use it. Only ONE of the two options below can be funded this year. Read the choices and tell the building committee which one you would prefer, explaining your reasons.","bullets":["Option A: Convert the room into a shared laundry lounge with additional washers, dryers, and seating","Option B: Convert the room into a quiet co-working space with desks, Wi-Fi, and printing facilities","Choose ONE option and give reasons to support your choice"],"timeMin":26,"wordRange":"150-200","modelAnswer":"I would prefer Option A, converting the empty room into a shared laundry lounge with extra machines. The most important reason is that our current laundry room is far too small. On weekends, tenants often wait forty minutes just for a free washer, and I have seen neighbours arguing over machines. Adding washers, dryers, and comfortable seating would solve a daily frustration that affects almost every household in the building.\n\nIn addition, a laundry lounge benefits everyone equally. Whether someone is a student, a retiree, or a family with children, they all need to do laundry, so the investment would serve the entire community rather than one group.\n\nOption B, the co-working space, is a thoughtful idea, and I know a few residents work from home. However, most of us already have internet and a desk in our units, so the demand would be limited. A laundry lounge, by contrast, responds to a problem we experience every single week. For this reason, I strongly encourage the committee to choose Option A.","rubricTips":["Name your preferred option in the first sentence so your position is instantly clear","Back up your choice with vivid, believable examples such as wait times or crowding","Use connectors like 'in addition' and 'by contrast' to organize your reasons","Concede a merit of the rejected option, then show why the need is smaller","Keep within 150-200 words and address the building committee respectfully"]},{"id":"transit-improvement-priority","kind":"survey","title":"City Transit Improvement Survey","prompt":"Your city's transit authority has a limited budget and is asking residents to help set priorities. It can fund only ONE of the two improvements below. Read the options and choose the one you think would be more valuable for commuters, giving reasons for your decision.","bullets":["Option A: Increase bus frequency on existing routes so buses arrive every ten minutes instead of every twenty","Option B: Build several new heated, sheltered bus stops with real-time arrival screens","Choose ONE option and give reasons to support your choice"],"timeMin":26,"wordRange":"150-200","modelAnswer":"If the transit authority can fund only one project, I firmly believe it should choose Option A, increasing bus frequency to every ten minutes. The primary reason is that frequency affects every rider on every trip. When buses come twice as often, commuters spend less time waiting, miss fewer connections, and are far more likely to arrive at work or school on time. This reliability is the single biggest factor that encourages people to leave their cars at home.\n\nFurthermore, more frequent service reduces overcrowding. During rush hour, our buses are often packed, and a ten-minute schedule would spread passengers across more vehicles, making the ride safer and more comfortable.\n\nHeated shelters with arrival screens, as described in Option B, would certainly make waiting in our cold winters more pleasant. Still, a comfortable shelter does not help much if you must wait twenty minutes in it. I would rather wait briefly at a simple stop than stand comfortably for a long time. Therefore, improving frequency offers the greatest overall benefit to commuters.","rubricTips":["Declare your chosen option clearly and commit to it throughout","Develop two strong reasons, linking each to real commuter benefits like reliability or comfort","Signal structure with words such as 'furthermore', 'still', and 'therefore'","Handle the trade-off by admitting the appeal of shelters, then reframing why frequency matters more","Write 150-200 words in a persuasive but reasonable tone"]},{"id":"school-parent-fundraising","kind":"survey","title":"School Fundraising Priority","prompt":"The parent council at your child's elementary school has raised money and is surveying families about how to spend it. Only ONE of the two options below can be chosen this year. Read the choices and tell the council which you would prefer, explaining your reasons.","bullets":["Option A: Purchase new tablets and updated software for the school computer lab","Option B: Upgrade the outdoor playground with new equipment and a shaded seating area","Choose ONE option and give reasons to support your choice"],"timeMin":26,"wordRange":"150-200","modelAnswer":"As a parent, I would choose Option B, upgrading the outdoor playground with new equipment and a shaded seating area. My first reason is that children today spend far too much time indoors and in front of screens. A safe, engaging playground encourages physical activity, which supports both their health and their ability to concentrate in class afterward. Recess is often the highlight of a child's day, and better equipment would make it more enjoyable for everyone.\n\nSecondly, a shaded seating area protects students from the strong summer sun and gives them a comfortable place to rest, which matters greatly during hot months when heat warnings are common.\n\nI recognize that new tablets, as proposed in Option A, would support learning, and technology is important. However, our school already received a set of laptops two years ago, so the computer lab is reasonably equipped. The playground, on the other hand, has not been updated in over a decade and some equipment is worn. For these reasons, I believe investing in the playground would benefit our children most.","rubricTips":["State your preferred option plainly at the start and stay consistent","Offer two developed reasons tied to children's wellbeing and daily experience","Use transitions such as 'secondly' and 'on the other hand' to link points","Acknowledge the value of the other option, then justify why your choice is the greater need","Keep the response within 150-200 words and use a warm, parental tone"]},{"id":"grocery-store-loyalty-feature","kind":"survey","title":"Grocery Store Customer Survey","prompt":"A local grocery chain is redesigning its customer loyalty program and is surveying shoppers. It can add only ONE of the two features below. Read the options and choose the one you would find more useful, giving reasons for your choice.","bullets":["Option A: Instant discounts on your total bill every time you shop, applied automatically at checkout","Option B: Points that accumulate and can later be redeemed for larger rewards such as free groceries or gift cards","Choose ONE option and give reasons to support your choice"],"timeMin":26,"wordRange":"150-200","modelAnswer":"Between these two features, I would choose Option A, the instant discounts applied automatically at every checkout. My main reason is simplicity. With an immediate discount, I can see my savings right away without tracking a balance, remembering to redeem anything, or worrying about points expiring. For busy shoppers like me, that convenience is genuinely valuable.\n\nSecondly, instant savings help households manage tight budgets. Grocery prices have risen sharply, and a small discount on every trip provides steady, predictable relief that families can count on week after week, rather than a single large reward months later.\n\nI understand that Option B, accumulating points for bigger rewards, can feel exciting, and some shoppers enjoy saving up for a free grocery haul. However, in my experience these programs often have complicated rules, and many people forget to redeem their points before they expire, losing the benefit entirely. An automatic discount guarantees that everyone benefits, effortlessly. For these reasons, I believe instant discounts would be the more useful and fairer feature for your customers.","rubricTips":["Identify your chosen option in the opening sentence without hedging","Provide two clear reasons, each supported with a relatable example like budgeting or convenience","Use linking phrases such as 'secondly', 'however', and 'for these reasons'","Address the rejected option's appeal, then explain its practical drawback","Stay between 150-200 words in a clear, everyday tone"]},{"id":"library-space-redesign","kind":"survey","title":"Public Library Renovation Survey","prompt":"Your public library is renovating one section and has asked patrons for input through a survey. Because of budget limits, only ONE of the two ideas below can go ahead. Read the options and tell the library board which you would prefer, explaining your reasons.","bullets":["Option A: Create a dedicated quiet study zone with individual desks, power outlets, and soft lighting","Option B: Create a children's activity area with a reading corner, craft tables, and interactive displays","Choose ONE option and give reasons to support your choice"],"timeMin":26,"wordRange":"150-200","modelAnswer":"I would recommend Option B, creating a children's activity area with a reading corner, craft tables, and interactive displays. My strongest reason is that this space would help develop a lifelong love of reading in young children. When kids associate the library with fun stories and hands-on activities, they are far more likely to keep visiting as they grow. Investing in children is really an investment in the library's future.\n\nIn addition, a children's area supports local families. Many parents are looking for free, safe, and educational places to bring their children, especially during long winters when outdoor play is difficult. This space would meet a clear community need.\n\nI do see the value of Option A, the quiet study zone, since students and remote workers need somewhere calm to focus. However, our library already has several quiet tables on the upper floor, whereas there is currently nothing designed for children. Because the gap is greater for young families, I believe the children's activity area would make the most meaningful difference and I hope the board selects it.","rubricTips":["Announce your preferred option at once and hold that position throughout","Support your choice with two reasons developed through concrete community benefits","Guide the reader with connectors like 'in addition' and 'however'","Concede the merit of the other option, then point to why your choice fills a bigger gap","Write 150-200 words and address the library board courteously"]},{"id":"workplace-wellness-benefit","kind":"survey","title":"Employee Wellness Benefit Survey","prompt":"Your company is introducing a new wellness benefit and has surveyed staff to decide how to spend the budget. Only ONE of the two options below can be offered this year. Read the choices and indicate which you would prefer, giving reasons to support your decision.","bullets":["Option A: A subsidized gym and fitness class membership for all employees","Option B: A monthly mental-health day of paid leave that employees can take whenever they need it","Choose ONE option and give reasons to support your choice"],"timeMin":26,"wordRange":"150-200","modelAnswer":"Of the two proposals, I would choose Option B, the monthly mental-health day of paid leave. My primary reason is that stress and burnout are among the biggest challenges facing employees today. A guaranteed day to rest, recover, or handle personal matters allows staff to return to work refreshed and more productive. Unlike a gym membership, this benefit directly addresses the emotional pressures that build up over a demanding month.\n\nFurthermore, a paid mental-health day is inclusive. Not everyone enjoys or is able to use a gym, but every single employee can benefit from time to reset. In this way, the company's investment reaches the entire team fairly.\n\nI acknowledge that Option A, the subsidized fitness membership, promotes physical health, and exercise certainly reduces stress for many people. However, employees who are already exhausted often lack the energy to attend classes, so the membership may go unused. A day off, by contrast, is something everyone can take advantage of immediately. For these reasons, I believe the monthly mental-health day would do the most good for our staff.","rubricTips":["State your chosen option clearly and never contradict it later","Build two solid reasons, each expanded with realistic workplace examples","Use transitions such as 'furthermore', 'in this way', and 'however' to organize ideas","Tackle the trade-off by praising the other option, then exposing its limitation","Keep to 150-200 words and use a thoughtful, professional voice"]}]},"speaking":{"t1":[{"id":"advice-job-offer-out-of-province","taskNo":1,"type":"Giving Advice","title":"A Job Offer in Another Province","prompt":"Your cousin just received a full-time job offer in Calgary, but it means leaving Toronto, where all of her family and friends live. She's excited about the higher salary but nervous about moving so far away on her own. She's called to ask what you think she should do. Give her your advice.","prepSec":30,"speakSec":90,"template":["Opening: acknowledge the situation and reassure your cousin (e.g., \"Hey, I know this is a huge decision, so let's talk it through.\")","Advice 1 + reason: suggest one concrete step and explain why (e.g., compare the cost of living, not just the salary).","Advice 2 + reason: offer a second piece of advice with a benefit (e.g., ask the company about relocation support or a trial period).","Advice 3 / reassurance: address her worry about being alone (e.g., how to build a social circle, visits home).","Closing: encourage her and remind her you'll support her decision either way."],"modelAnswer":"Hey, first off, congratulations, that's a big deal! I can tell you're torn, so let's just talk it through. Honestly, I think you should take a really close look at the numbers before anything else. The salary sounds great, but rent and everyday costs in Calgary are different from Toronto, so sit down and compare what you'd actually keep at the end of the month. If you'd come out ahead and still have money to fly home, that tells you a lot. Second, I'd call the company back and ask whether they offer any relocation help, and maybe whether you can start with a bit of a trial arrangement. A lot of employers cover moving costs, and it never hurts to ask, right? That way you're not carrying all the risk yourself. And about being far from everyone, I really wouldn't worry too much. Calgary's got a huge community scene, so join a gym, a hiking group, whatever you're into, and you'll meet people fast. Plus, flights aren't that long, and we can video call all the time. At the end of the day, this is your call, and I'll back you no matter what you decide. But if it were me? A good job and a fresh adventure at your age, I'd probably go for it. Just promise you'll let me help you pack!","tips":["Use warm, spoken language and contractions (I'd, you're, wouldn't) to sound natural and supportive.","Give at least two or three distinct pieces of advice, and back each one with a clear reason or benefit.","Directly address the specific worry in the prompt (moving away from family) so it doesn't sound generic.","Close by respecting that it's her decision — the task rewards balanced, encouraging advice over ordering her around."]},{"id":"advice-adopt-dog-small-apartment","taskNo":1,"type":"Giving Advice","title":"Adopting a Dog in a Small Apartment","prompt":"Your roommate is thinking about adopting a large dog from the local shelter. You both live in a one-bedroom apartment downtown, and your roommate works long shifts at the hospital. He's asked for your honest opinion before he fills out the application. Give him your advice.","prepSec":30,"speakSec":90,"template":["Opening: react positively but signal there are things to think about first.","Advice 1 + reason: address the size of the apartment and the dog's exercise needs.","Advice 2 + reason: raise the issue of his long shifts and who cares for the dog.","Advice 3 + reason: suggest a practical alternative or middle step (e.g., fostering, a smaller breed, checking the lease).","Closing: encourage a responsible decision and offer your help."],"modelAnswer":"Oh, I love that you're thinking about giving a shelter dog a home, that's a really kind thing to do. But since you asked for my honest take, let me lay a few things out. First, I'd think hard about the space. A big dog in a one-bedroom downtown can work, but only if it gets out a lot, so you'd need to be walking it a couple of times a day, rain or shine. Without a yard, that's on you every single day. Second, and this is the big one, your shifts are brutal. Twelve hours is a long time to leave any dog alone, especially a large one that needs activity. So before you apply, I'd figure out the plan: could we split walks, or would you hire a dog walker? Because that adds up cost-wise. Honestly, my suggestion would be to start by fostering instead of adopting outright. That way you find out if it fits your schedule without a lifetime commitment, and you're still helping the shelter. Oh, and double-check our lease, some buildings have weight limits on pets. Look, I'm totally on board to help walk it and share the load, so I'm not trying to talk you out of it. Just let's make sure it's fair to the dog too. Whatever you decide, I've got your back.","tips":["Balance enthusiasm with honesty — the prompt asks for your honest opinion, so name the real challenges.","Anchor each piece of advice to a specific detail (small apartment, long shifts) to show you understood the scenario.","Offer a concrete middle-ground option, like fostering, to show problem-solving rather than just a yes or no.","Keep a friendly roommate tone and end by offering to share the responsibility."]},{"id":"advice-online-vs-inperson-course","taskNo":1,"type":"Giving Advice","title":"Online or In-Person Course","prompt":"Your friend wants to upgrade her skills by taking an accounting course this fall. She can't decide between a fully online course she can do from home and an in-person class at the local community college two evenings a week. She works full-time and has two young kids. She's asked which option you'd recommend. Give her your advice.","prepSec":30,"speakSec":90,"template":["Opening: recognize that both options are good and that it depends on her life.","Advice 1 + reason: point out the flexibility of online given her kids and job.","Advice 2 + reason: note the benefits of in-person (focus, networking, set schedule) as a fair comparison.","Advice 3 + reason: give a recommendation tailored to her situation and suggest a way to test it.","Closing: reassure her that either path moves her forward and offer support."],"modelAnswer":"That's awesome that you want to level up your skills, good for you! Both options are solid, so it really comes down to your day-to-day life. Here's how I'd think about it. Given that you're working full-time and running after two little ones, the online course has a big edge on flexibility. You could study after the kids are in bed or on your lunch break, and you're not paying for a sitter two nights a week or fighting fall traffic. That's a real saver, both money and stress. That said, in-person has its perks too. When you physically show up to a class, it's easier to focus, you can ask the instructor questions on the spot, and you meet people in the field, which can help down the road with jobs. So it's a genuine trade-off. Honestly, for your situation right now, I'd lean toward online, but I'd suggest one thing first: email the college and ask if you can sit in on one class or see a sample of the online lessons. That way you get a feel for it before you commit your money. And remember, whichever you pick, you're still moving forward, so you can't really go wrong. If you go online, I'm happy to watch the kids some evenings so you get quiet study time. Just say the word!","tips":["Compare both options fairly before recommending one — a balanced answer sounds more thoughtful than a one-sided one.","Tie your reasons to her real constraints (full-time work, two young kids) to keep it relevant.","Give a clear final recommendation plus a low-risk way to test the choice, which shows practical thinking.","Finish warmly with concrete support, and use natural contractions throughout to sound conversational."]}],"t2":[{"id":"speaking-t2-power-outage-storm","taskNo":2,"type":"Talking about a Personal Experience","title":"A Time You Dealt with an Unexpected Problem at Home","prompt":"Describe a time when something unexpected went wrong at your home and you had to deal with it. When did it happen? What was the problem, and what did you do about it? How did you feel during and after the experience?","prepSec":30,"speakSec":60,"template":["Set the scene: when it happened, where you were living, and what you were doing.","Explain what went wrong and why it caught you off guard.","Describe the steps you took to handle the problem.","Share how you felt at the time and how you feel about it now, and why it stuck with you."],"modelAnswer":"This happened about two winters ago, when I was living in a small apartment in Winnipeg. It was late on a Friday evening, and there was a huge ice storm outside. I was just settling in to watch a movie when suddenly the power went out across the whole building. At first I thought it would come back in a few minutes, but after half an hour it was still pitch black and getting cold fast. I felt a little anxious, honestly, because it was minus twenty outside. So I grabbed my phone flashlight, dug out some candles and an extra blanket, and I texted my neighbour across the hall. We ended up sitting in the hallway with a couple of other tenants, sharing snacks and just chatting to pass the time. The power finally came back around midnight. Looking back, I actually feel kind of grateful for it, because that was the night I really got to know my neighbours. It turned a stressful situation into a memory I still smile about.","tips":["Anchor the story with a clear time and place in the first sentence so the listener can picture the scene.","Stay firmly in the past tense and use time signals like 'at first', 'after half an hour', and 'finally' to show sequence.","Do not rush to list only facts — spend a few seconds on your emotions, since the task specifically asks how you felt.","End with a short reflection on why the experience was memorable to give your answer a natural conclusion."]},{"id":"speaking-t2-lost-wallet-transit","taskNo":2,"type":"Talking about a Personal Experience","title":"A Time a Stranger Helped You","prompt":"Talk about a time when a stranger did something kind or helpful for you. Where and when did this happen? What did the person do? Explain why this experience was meaningful to you.","prepSec":30,"speakSec":60,"template":["Set the scene: when and where it happened and what you were doing.","Describe the situation you were in and the kind thing the stranger did.","Explain how you reacted and what happened next.","Reflect on how it made you feel and why it left a lasting impression."],"modelAnswer":"A couple of years ago, I was rushing to catch the SkyTrain in Vancouver on my way to a job interview. I was so nervous that I paid my fare, hopped off at my stop, and only then realized I had left my whole wallet on the seat. My heart just sank, because my ID and bank cards were all in there. About ten minutes later, my phone rang. A woman who had been sitting next to me had found my wallet, seen my student card, and tracked down my number online. She actually waited at the next station and handed it back to me with everything still inside. I was so relieved I almost teared up, and I thanked her about five times. I offered to buy her a coffee, but she just smiled and said to pass the kindness on. That experience really stuck with me because it reminded me that most people are genuinely good. Ever since then, I try to help strangers whenever I can, just like she did for me.","tips":["Choose one specific, simple event rather than a general habit, so you can add vivid details in the time you have.","Use natural spoken phrases like 'my heart just sank' and 'I almost teared up' to make your feelings sound authentic.","Keep a clear beginning, middle, and end so the story is easy to follow within 60 seconds.","Connect the ending to a broader lesson or change in you — this answers the 'why meaningful' part directly."]},{"id":"speaking-t2-first-canadian-winter-hike","taskNo":2,"type":"Talking about a Personal Experience","title":"A Time You Tried Something New","prompt":"Describe an occasion when you tried an activity for the very first time. What was the activity, and when did you try it? Who were you with? Explain how you felt before, during, and after the experience.","prepSec":30,"speakSec":60,"template":["Set the scene: the activity, when you tried it, and who you were with.","Describe how you felt going into it and why it was new for you.","Walk through what actually happened during the activity.","Reflect on how you felt afterward and why the experience was memorable."],"modelAnswer":"Last February, some coworkers invited me to go ice skating on the Rideau Canal in Ottawa, and it was my very first time on skates. Before we went, I was honestly pretty nervous, because I had never even worn skates and I was sure I would fall flat on my face in front of everyone. When we got there, my ankles were wobbling all over the place, and I spent the first ten minutes clinging to the railing. But my friend Priya was really patient and skated slowly beside me, holding my hand until I found my balance. After a while, something just clicked, and I managed to glide on my own for a whole stretch of the canal. I was grinning like a little kid. By the end of the afternoon, I was exhausted but so proud of myself. That day really stands out for me because it pushed me out of my comfort zone, and it showed me that trying something scary can turn into one of the best days of the season.","tips":["Contrast your feelings 'before, during, and after' clearly, since the prompt explicitly asks for all three stages.","Include one small vivid moment, like clinging to the railing, to make the story feel real rather than generic.","Use a mix of simple and slightly complex past-tense verbs to show range: 'invited', 'was wobbling', 'had never worn'.","Close with what the experience taught you or why you are proud, which naturally wraps up the 60 seconds."]}],"t3":[{"id":"describe-scene-community-skating-rink","taskNo":3,"type":"Describing a Scene","title":"Winter Skating Rink","prompt":"Imagine a photo taken on a cold, bright winter afternoon at an outdoor community skating rink in a city park. In the foreground, a young girl in a red toque and puffy jacket is holding onto the boards, taking careful first steps on her skates. Just behind her, a father is crouched down with his arms out, ready to catch a wobbling toddler. Across the ice, a group of teenagers is playing a casual game of pickup hockey, their sticks and a bright orange puck visible on the surface. Along the wooden boards on the right, several people sit on a bench lacing up their skates, with backpacks and boots piled beside them. In the background, snow-covered evergreen trees and a small warming hut with smoke rising from its chimney are visible under a pale blue sky. Describe this photo in detail to a friend who cannot see it.","prepSec":30,"speakSec":60,"template":["Overview: say what the photo shows and the overall setting/season","Foreground: describe the closest people and what they are doing","Middle ground: the hockey players and people on the bench","Background: trees, warming hut, sky and weather","Details and mood: colours, clothing, and the feeling of the scene"],"modelAnswer":"So this is a photo of an outdoor skating rink in a city park, and it looks like a really cold but sunny winter afternoon. In the very front of the picture, there's a little girl wearing a red toque and a puffy jacket, and she's holding onto the boards, taking her first careful steps on her skates. Right behind her, a dad is crouched down with his arms stretched out, getting ready to catch a wobbly toddler. Over on the ice, a bit further back, a group of teenagers is playing a casual game of pickup hockey — you can see their sticks and a bright orange puck. On the right side, along the wooden boards, a few people are sitting on a bench, lacing up their skates, and there are backpacks and boots piled up beside them. In the background, there are snow-covered evergreen trees and a little warming hut with smoke coming out of the chimney. The sky is a pale blue. Overall, it feels really cheerful and busy, like a typical Canadian winter day where families come out to skate together.","tips":["Use location phrases like 'in the foreground', 'behind her', 'on the right', and 'in the background' to guide your listener.","Keep verbs in the present continuous — 'she is holding', 'they are playing' — since you're describing an ongoing moment.","Mention colours and clothing (red toque, orange puck) to make the scene vivid for someone who can't see it.","End with a sentence about the mood or atmosphere to round off your description naturally."]},{"id":"describe-scene-farmers-market-morning","taskNo":3,"type":"Describing a Scene","title":"Saturday Farmers' Market","prompt":"Imagine a photo of a busy outdoor farmers' market on a sunny Saturday morning in late summer. In the foreground, a vendor wearing a green apron is standing behind a wooden stall stacked with baskets of red tomatoes, corn, and leafy greens, handing a paper bag to a smiling customer. To the left, a woman is pushing a stroller and pointing at a display of fresh flowers while her small child reaches toward the bouquets. In the middle of the scene, shoppers with cloth tote bags and reusable coffee cups are strolling between rows of white canopy tents. On the right, a musician is sitting on a stool playing an acoustic guitar, with an open guitar case for tips in front of him. In the background, you can see brick buildings, a few leafy trees, and a banner strung between two poles that reads 'Community Market.' The sky is clear and blue. Describe this photo in detail to someone who cannot see it.","prepSec":30,"speakSec":60,"template":["Overview: introduce the market, the day, and the season/weather","Foreground: the main vendor and the customer at the stall","Left side: the woman with the stroller and the flower display","Middle and right: shoppers walking and the musician playing","Background and mood: buildings, banner, sky, and overall atmosphere"],"modelAnswer":"This is a photo of a busy outdoor farmers' market, and it looks like a sunny Saturday morning in late summer. In the foreground, there's a vendor wearing a green apron standing behind a wooden stall. The stall is stacked with baskets of red tomatoes, corn, and leafy greens, and he's handing a paper bag to a customer who's smiling. Over on the left, a woman is pushing a stroller and pointing at a display of fresh flowers, while her little kid is reaching out toward the bouquets. In the middle of the scene, lots of shoppers are strolling between rows of white canopy tents, carrying cloth tote bags and reusable coffee cups. On the right, there's a musician sitting on a stool, playing an acoustic guitar, and he's got an open case in front of him for tips. In the background, you can see brick buildings, some leafy trees, and a banner strung between two poles that says 'Community Market.' The sky is clear and blue. Overall, it feels lively, friendly, and really relaxed.","tips":["Group the scene into zones — foreground, left, middle, right, background — so your description stays organized and easy to follow.","Use present continuous verbs throughout to show the action is happening right now.","Include specific details like the vendor's green apron and the 'Community Market' banner to paint a clear picture.","Don't rush; describe two or three things well rather than listing everything quickly."]},{"id":"describe-scene-transit-station-commute","taskNo":3,"type":"Describing a Scene","title":"Rainy Evening at the Transit Station","prompt":"Imagine a photo taken during the evening rush hour on a covered outdoor platform at a light-rail transit station, on a rainy day. In the foreground, a man in a grey business suit is standing under a black umbrella, glancing down at his phone while holding a briefcase. Next to him, a young woman wearing headphones and a yellow raincoat is looking up at a digital arrival board that shows the next train coming in two minutes. In the middle of the platform, a train is pulling in, its doors not yet open, and a small crowd of commuters is waiting near the edge behind the yellow safety line. On the left, a parent is holding a child's hand and carrying a folded stroller. Puddles have formed on the pavement, and rain is streaking down the glass shelter. In the background, blurry car headlights and tall office buildings with lit windows are visible through the mist. Describe this photo in detail to a friend who cannot see it.","prepSec":30,"speakSec":60,"template":["Overview: describe the station, the time of day, and the rainy weather","Foreground: the businessman and the woman in the yellow raincoat","Middle: the arriving train and the waiting crowd","Left side: the parent with the child and stroller","Background and details: puddles, rain on the glass, city lights, and mood"],"modelAnswer":"So this photo is taken at a light-rail transit station during evening rush hour, and it's a rainy day. The platform is covered, but you can tell it's really wet outside. In the foreground, there's a man in a grey business suit standing under a black umbrella. He's glancing down at his phone and holding a briefcase. Right next to him, there's a young woman in a yellow raincoat wearing headphones, and she's looking up at a digital arrival board that says the next train is coming in two minutes. In the middle of the platform, a train is pulling in, but the doors aren't open yet, and a small crowd of commuters is waiting near the edge, behind the yellow safety line. On the left, a parent is holding a child's hand and carrying a folded stroller. There are puddles on the pavement, and you can see rain streaking down the glass shelter. In the background, through the mist, there are blurry car headlights and tall office buildings with lit-up windows. Overall, it feels busy and a little tired, like the end of a long workday.","tips":["Set the scene first — time of day and weather — before moving into the specific people and actions.","Use spatial signposts such as 'next to him', 'in the middle', and 'in the background' so your listener can follow along.","Describe sensory details like rain on the glass and puddles to make the rainy atmosphere come alive.","Finish with the overall feeling or mood of the scene to give your description a natural conclusion."]}],"t4":[{"id":"predict-farmers-market-rain","taskNo":4,"type":"Making Predictions","title":"Predicting: Outdoor Farmers' Market Before a Storm","prompt":"Look at this scene. It is a Saturday morning at an outdoor farmers' market in a downtown square. Vendors are standing behind tables covered with fresh vegetables, baked goods, and flowers. Shoppers with cloth bags are browsing between the stalls. In the background, the sky has turned dark grey and heavy clouds are moving in. A few vendors are glancing up at the sky, and one is starting to reach for a folded tarp. Describe what you think will happen next.","prepSec":30,"speakSec":60,"template":["Say what is happening right now (market is busy, clouds are gathering).","Prediction 1 with a future form: the vendors will probably...","Prediction 2: the shoppers are going to...","Prediction 3: use 'likely' for what happens once the rain starts.","Wrap up with what the market will look like a bit later."],"modelAnswer":"So in this picture, it's a busy Saturday morning at an outdoor farmers' market, and you can see the sky is getting really dark. There are heavy clouds rolling in, so I think it's going to rain very soon. My first prediction is that the vendors will probably start covering their tables. That one guy is already reaching for a tarp, so they'll likely pull out plastic sheets to protect the vegetables and the baked goods before they get wet. My second prediction is that a lot of the shoppers are going to finish up quickly. They'll grab whatever they came for, pay fast, and then head for cover, maybe under an awning or into a nearby coffee shop. And once the rain actually starts, the square is likely going to empty out pretty fast. Some vendors will probably decide to pack up early and close their stalls for the day. So overall, in about fifteen minutes, I think this lively market is going to look almost deserted, with just a few people waiting for the storm to pass.","tips":["Open by describing the present scene, then shift clearly into future forms — that shift is what the task is testing.","Mix your future forms: use 'will', 'going to', and 'likely' so you don't repeat the same structure three times.","Point to a detail in the scene (the tarp, the dark sky) as evidence for each prediction — it makes your guesses sound logical.","Give three separate predictions and keep talking until near 60 seconds; a short pause is fine, but don't stop at 30."]},{"id":"predict-bus-stop-late-commuter","taskNo":4,"type":"Making Predictions","title":"Predicting: A Crowded Bus Stop on a Cold Morning","prompt":"Look at this scene. It is a cold winter morning at a city bus stop. A small crowd of people is waiting under the shelter, bundled up in heavy coats, scarves, and toques. One young woman near the front keeps checking her phone and then looking down the street, and she is holding a coffee cup and a work bag. A bus is just coming into view a block away, but it already looks quite full through the windows. Snow is lightly falling. Describe what you think will happen next.","prepSec":30,"speakSec":60,"template":["Describe the present situation (people waiting, bus approaching, it looks full).","Prediction 1: when the bus arrives, the people are going to...","Prediction 2: the crowded bus will probably...","Prediction 3: use 'likely' for the woman who is in a hurry.","Close with a guess about her commute or the rest of the morning."],"modelAnswer":"In this scene, it's a freezing winter morning and a group of people is waiting at a bus stop while snow is falling. There's a young woman near the front who keeps checking her phone and looking down the street, so I'd guess she's running a little late for work. A bus is coming, but it already looks pretty full. My first prediction is that when the bus pulls up, everyone is going to crowd toward the doors and try to squeeze on. Since it's cold, nobody's going to want to wait for the next one. My second prediction is that the bus will probably be too packed for everyone to fit, so a few people at the back of the line are likely going to get left behind. As for the woman in front, she'll most likely manage to get on because she's close to the doors, but she'll have to stand and hold her coffee carefully so it doesn't spill. And finally, I think she'll relax a bit once she's on board, check the time, and maybe text her office to say she's on her way. By the next stop, the bus will be even more crowded than it is now.","tips":["Set the scene in one or two sentences, then spend most of your time on the predictions themselves.","Use the small details (checking the phone, the full windows) to justify why you think something will happen.","Vary your grammar: 'is going to crowd', 'will probably be', 'is likely to get left behind' all sound more advanced than repeating 'will'.","Track one person through the scene, like the woman in front — following a character makes your answer feel connected, not like a list."]},{"id":"predict-community-centre-setup","taskNo":4,"type":"Making Predictions","title":"Predicting: Setting Up for a Community Centre Event","prompt":"Look at this scene. It is late afternoon inside a community centre gymnasium. A group of volunteers in matching t-shirts is setting up for an evening event. Some are unfolding rows of chairs, others are arranging snacks and drinks on long tables at the side, and two people are testing a microphone on a small stage. A banner that reads 'Welcome' is half hung on the back wall. Through the windows you can see it is starting to get dark outside, and a few early guests are gathering near the front doors. Describe what you think will happen next.","prepSec":30,"speakSec":60,"template":["Describe what the volunteers are doing right now.","Prediction 1: they will finish the setup by...","Prediction 2: the guests at the door are going to...","Prediction 3: use 'likely' for how the event itself will begin.","Wrap up with what the gym will be like once the event starts."],"modelAnswer":"In this picture, a group of volunteers is setting up a community centre gym for some kind of evening event. Some are putting out chairs, others are laying out snacks and drinks, and two people are testing the microphone on the stage. It's getting dark outside and a few guests are already waiting by the doors, so I think the event is going to start pretty soon. My first prediction is that the volunteers will finish the setup in the next few minutes. They'll straighten the last rows of chairs and hang up the rest of that 'Welcome' banner before anyone comes in. My second prediction is that once everything's ready, someone is going to open the front doors and the early guests are going to walk in, grab a drink, and find a seat. My third prediction is that a host or an organizer will likely step up to the microphone to welcome everyone and explain the program for the evening. And after that, I imagine the gym is going to fill up with people, the seats will be full, and it'll turn into a lively, noisy event with everyone chatting before the main part begins.","tips":["Start in the present tense to describe the setup, then move confidently into future forms for your predictions.","Sequence your predictions with time words like 'first', 'once everything's ready', and 'after that' so it flows in order.","Mix 'will', 'going to', and 'likely' — examiners reward a range of future structures, not just one.","Don't rush; you have a full 60 seconds, so add a small detail to each prediction and finish with a clear closing sentence."]}],"t5":[{"id":"t5-two-family-vacations-banff-quebec","taskNo":5,"type":"Comparing and Persuading","title":"Choosing a Family Vacation","prompt":"Your family has one week off in July and you want to plan a trip together. You have narrowed it down to two options and need to convince your sister to agree with your pick.\n\nOption A: A road trip to Banff, Alberta. Cabin rental at $180 per night, lots of hiking, lakes, and wildlife. A 12-hour drive each way, so you'd split the driving.\n\nOption B: A flight to Quebec City. Downtown hotel at $220 per night, historic Old Town, restaurants, and museums. A short 2-hour flight, but flights cost about $400 per person.\n\nChoose ONE option and persuade your sister to agree.","prepSec":60,"speakSec":60,"template":["State your choice clearly: \"I really think we should go with...\"","Compare on cost: explain how your option saves money or gives better value.","Compare on the experience: what everyone will actually enjoy and remember.","Address the downside of the other option honestly.","Persuade and conclude: end with a warm call to action."],"modelAnswer":"Okay, hear me out, but I really think we should do the Banff road trip this year. First, let's talk money. The cabin is only a hundred and eighty a night, and with no plane tickets, we'd save around sixteen hundred dollars for the four of us. That's huge. Second, think about what the kids will actually remember. In Banff they can hike, canoe on the lake, and maybe spot some elk. That beats sitting in museums, no offense. I know the twelve-hour drive sounds brutal, but that's the fun part, honestly. We split the driving, load up on snacks, sing terrible songs, and it becomes part of the trip. Quebec would be lovely, sure, but those four-hundred-dollar flights add up fast and we'd be stuck to a tight schedule. Come on, let's grab that cabin before it books up. Trust me, this one's going to be the trip we talk about for years. What do you say?","tips":["Pick one option in your first sentence and never waver — CELPIP rewards a firm, confident choice.","Use concrete numbers from the prompt (the savings, the nightly rate) to make your persuasion feel real.","Acknowledge the weakness of your choice, then reframe it as a positive ('the long drive becomes part of the fun').","End with a friendly call to action and a question that invites agreement."]},{"id":"t5-two-apartments-condo-vs-basement","taskNo":5,"type":"Comparing and Persuading","title":"Choosing an Apartment to Rent","prompt":"You and your partner are moving to a new city for work and need to sign a lease this weekend. You have toured two places and want to convince your partner to choose the one you prefer.\n\nOption A: A one-bedroom condo on the 15th floor downtown. $1,950 per month, in-suite laundry, gym, and a 10-minute walk to both your offices. Small balcony, no parking included.\n\nOption B: A two-bedroom basement suite in a quiet suburb. $1,600 per month, a private backyard, free parking, but a 40-minute bus commute each way.\n\nChoose ONE option and persuade your partner to agree.","prepSec":60,"speakSec":60,"template":["State your choice up front and sound decided.","Compare on the daily commute and how it affects your quality of life.","Compare on cost versus what you actually get for the money.","Concede one real drawback and explain why it's manageable.","Wrap up by urging your partner to sign before someone else does."],"modelAnswer":"Honestly, I think we should take the downtown condo. Yes, it's three-fifty more a month, but hear me out. The biggest thing is the commute. Ten minutes on foot versus forty minutes on the bus, both ways — that's over an hour of our lives back every single day. Imagine sleeping in, walking to work, and coming home for lunch. You can't put a price on that. Second, we save on transit passes and we'd both skip the winter bus stops, which, in this weather, is a real gift. I know the basement suite has the backyard and free parking, and I get why that's tempting. But we don't even own a car yet, and a backyard we're too tired to use isn't worth a long commute. The condo also has the gym and in-suite laundry, so no more hauling clothes to a laundromat. Let's call the landlord tonight and put down the deposit before it's gone. Trust me, we'll be so glad we did. Deal?","tips":["Lead with your decision so the examiner immediately knows your position.","Turn an abstract benefit into a vivid daily picture ('walk to work, come home for lunch').","Fairly name the other option's strengths, then neutralize them with your own logic.","Close with urgency plus a one-word check-in like 'Deal?' to sound natural and persuasive."]},{"id":"t5-two-birthday-gifts-tablet-vs-classes","taskNo":5,"type":"Comparing and Persuading","title":"Choosing a Gift for Grandma","prompt":"Your grandmother is turning 70 next month and the whole family is chipping in for one gift. You want to convince your brother to agree with your choice.\n\nOption A: A tablet with a large screen and simple set-up, about $350. She could video-call the family, read books, and look at photos, but she isn't very comfortable with technology.\n\nOption B: A season pass to a nearby botanical garden plus a monthly gardening class, about $300 total. She loves plants and being outdoors, but the garden is a 25-minute drive away.\n\nChoose ONE option and persuade your brother to agree.","prepSec":60,"speakSec":60,"template":["Open by naming your chosen gift with confidence.","Compare on how well the gift matches Grandma's real interests.","Compare on cost and how much lasting joy it gives.","Address the practical concern with the other choice.","Finish by encouraging your brother to go in on it with you today."],"modelAnswer":"You know what, I really think the botanical garden pass is the perfect gift for Grandma. Think about who she actually is. She's happiest with her hands in the soil, out in the fresh air, chatting with people. A gardening class every month gives her something to look forward to, new friends, and a reason to get out of the house. That's priceless at seventy. Compare that to the tablet — I love the idea of video calls, but honestly, she gets flustered by her own remote control. We'd end up on the phone every week troubleshooting it, and it might just sit in a drawer. The garden pass is also fifty bucks cheaper, and it keeps giving all season long, not just on her birthday. I know the twenty-five-minute drive is a bit of a hassle, but we can take turns driving her, and that's extra time with her anyway. Let's put our share in today so we can surprise her. Come on, she's going to absolutely love this one. You in?","tips":["Anchor your whole argument in the person's genuine interests — it makes persuasion feel caring, not pushy.","Contrast 'lasting joy all season' against a one-time gift to strengthen the value point.","Handle the drawback (the drive) by offering a shared solution rather than dismissing it.","End with warmth and a light question ('You in?') to invite your brother to say yes."]}],"t6":[{"id":"task6-double-booked-shift-birthday","taskNo":6,"type":"Dealing with a Difficult Situation","title":"A Double-Booked Weekend","prompt":"Two weeks ago, you promised your best friend that you would help set up and host her surprise birthday party this Saturday afternoon. You are basically the co-organizer, and she is counting on you. This morning, your manager sent a group message asking you to cover an urgent inventory shift on the exact same Saturday afternoon. A big client audit was moved up, and the store is short-staffed. Your manager has hinted that people who help out this weekend will be considered first for the upcoming full-time position you have been hoping to get. You can only be in one place. Choose whether to call your friend or your manager, and explain what you decide to say.","prepSec":60,"speakSec":60,"template":["Acknowledge the conflict and how you feel about it","State who you have decided to call and why","Explain your reason politely and honestly","Propose a concrete solution or compromise","End on a warm, reassuring note"],"modelAnswer":"Okay, so I've got a real conflict here, and honestly I feel torn because both things matter to me. After thinking it over, I've decided to call my manager first. Here's my reasoning: my friend planned this birthday party around me being there as the co-host, and letting her down at the last minute could genuinely hurt her. A job shift, on the other hand, is something I can try to work around. So I'd say to my manager, \"Hi Dave, thanks so much for thinking of me for the audit shift. I really want to be a strong candidate for that full-time role, but I made a commitment to a close friend weeks ago that I can't back out of now.\" Then I'd propose a compromise. I'd offer to come in early Saturday morning before the party, or take an extra shift on Sunday to help prep for the audit. That way I'm still showing I'm reliable and eager. I'd finish by saying I hope he understands, and that I'm happy to help in any other way this week. I think being honest and offering an alternative is the most respectful approach for everyone involved.","tips":["Pick ONE person to call and commit to it — don't waffle between both, as that wastes your 60 seconds.","Show empathy for the side you disappoint; a phrase like 'I completely understand this is short notice' softens the message.","Always offer a concrete alternative (an earlier shift, a Sunday, another helper) so you sound solution-oriented, not just apologetic.","Use polite, natural phrasing and a warm closing to keep the relationship intact."]},{"id":"task6-wrong-size-gift-sweater","taskNo":6,"type":"Dealing with a Difficult Situation","title":"The Gift That Doesn't Fit","prompt":"For your birthday last week, your aunt gave you an expensive wool sweater that she put a lot of thought into choosing. Unfortunately, it is two sizes too small, the colour isn't one you would ever wear, and it's a bit itchy. She kept the receipt and mentioned you could exchange it if needed, but she also seemed really proud and said she 'had a feeling it would be perfect for you.' You want to be honest so you can get something you'll actually use, but you don't want to hurt her feelings. Decide whether to tell her directly or handle the exchange quietly, and explain what you would say to her.","prepSec":60,"speakSec":60,"template":["Acknowledge her kindness and the awkwardness","State your decision — tell her directly or handle it discreetly","Explain your reasoning tactfully","Propose how you'll handle the exchange without offending her","Close with genuine appreciation"],"modelAnswer":"This is a delicate one, because my aunt clearly put a lot of love into this gift. I've decided to talk to her directly rather than quietly exchanging it behind her back, because she already knows what she bought, and if she noticed I never wore it, she might feel hurt anyway. So I'd call her and start with genuine warmth: \"Auntie, thank you so much for the sweater — it means a lot that you thought of me.\" Then I'd be gentle and honest: \"I have to admit, it's just a little snug on me, and I'd hate for such a beautiful piece to sit unused in my closet.\" I'd frame it around the fit, not her taste, so she doesn't feel criticized. Then I'd propose a solution that keeps her involved: \"Would you be up for going to the store together this weekend so I can exchange it for the next size? I'd love your help picking the right one.\" That way she stays part of the process and still feels appreciated. I'd end by saying how touched I was that she remembered my birthday. I think honesty wrapped in gratitude is the kindest route here.","tips":["Lead with sincere thanks before raising any problem — gratitude cushions the honesty that follows.","Blame the fit or a neutral factor, never her taste, so she doesn't feel personally judged.","Invite her into the solution (exchanging it together) to keep her feeling valued.","Keep your tone warm and light; a small situation like this shouldn't sound like a serious complaint."]},{"id":"task6-roommate-noisy-guest-exam","taskNo":6,"type":"Dealing with a Difficult Situation","title":"A Roommate's Late-Night Guests","prompt":"You share a two-bedroom apartment with a roommate you generally get along with. For the past two weeks, your roommate's partner has been staying over almost every night, and they stay up late in the living room watching movies and talking loudly. You have an important certification exam in three days and you badly need sleep and quiet study time. You don't want to seem unwelcoming or start a fight, but the situation is affecting you. Decide whether to talk to your roommate in person or send a message, and explain how you would raise the issue and what you would propose.","prepSec":60,"speakSec":60,"template":["Acknowledge the situation and your relationship with the roommate","State whether you'll talk in person or message, and why","Explain your need calmly without blaming","Propose a fair, specific compromise","End on a cooperative, friendly note"],"modelAnswer":"So I really value getting along with my roommate, and I don't want this to turn into a conflict. I've decided to talk to her in person rather than texting, because a message about noise can come across as passive-aggressive, whereas a face-to-face chat feels friendlier and lets me read her reaction. I'd wait for a calm moment and say something like, \"Hey, can I talk to you for a sec? I've really enjoyed having your partner around, but I wanted to be honest — I've got this big certification exam on Thursday, and I'm struggling to sleep and study with the late-night movies.\" I'd keep it about my situation, not about accusing them. Then I'd propose a specific compromise: \"Would you two mind keeping things in your room or turning the volume down after around ten this week? It's really just until Thursday.\" I might even offer to spend an evening at the library so they have the space too. I'd finish by saying I appreciate them being understanding, and that once my exam's done, things go back to normal. I think a direct, respectful conversation with a clear ask is the best way to protect both the friendship and my sleep.","tips":["Choose in-person for tone-sensitive topics; explain briefly why you avoided a text.","Use 'I' statements ('I'm struggling to sleep') instead of 'you' accusations to prevent defensiveness.","Make your request specific and time-limited ('after ten, just until Thursday') so it feels reasonable.","Offer a small give of your own to show goodwill and keep the request balanced."]}],"t7":[{"id":"opinion-city-transit-fares-free","taskNo":7,"type":"Expressing Opinions","title":"Free Public Transit","prompt":"Your city is considering making all public transit free for residents, paid for through property taxes. Do you agree or disagree with this idea? Explain your opinion, giving reasons and examples to support it.","prepSec":30,"speakSec":90,"template":["State your opinion clearly (agree or disagree).","Give your first reason and support it with an example.","Give your second reason and support it with an example.","Restate your opinion in a slightly different way to close."],"modelAnswer":"I strongly agree that our city should make public transit free for residents. My first reason is that it would take a lot of cars off the road, which helps with both traffic and air quality. For example, on days when my bus is packed during rush hour, I can only imagine how much worse the highways would be if all those people were driving instead. If transit were free, even more people would leave their cars at home. My second reason is fairness. A lot of lower-income families rely on the bus to get to work, medical appointments, and grocery stores, and the fares really add up over a month. I have a neighbour who works two part-time jobs, and she spends almost two hundred dollars a month just getting around. Free transit would put that money back in her pocket. Yes, property taxes might go up a little, but I think spreading the cost across everyone is a reasonable trade-off. So overall, I believe free public transit is a smart, fair investment for our whole community.","tips":["Pick your side in the first sentence and never switch — examiners reward a clear, consistent position.","Use one concrete personal or observed example per reason so your answer sounds real rather than abstract.","Briefly acknowledge the downside (higher taxes) and explain why it's worth it — this shows balanced thinking.","Watch your pacing: two developed reasons in 90 seconds is plenty, so don't rush to add a third."]},{"id":"opinion-employers-remote-work-choice","taskNo":7,"type":"Expressing Opinions","title":"Choosing to Work From Home","prompt":"Some people believe employees should have the right to work from home whenever they want, while others think employers should decide. What is your opinion? Explain your reasons with examples.","prepSec":30,"speakSec":90,"template":["State your opinion clearly.","Give your first reason with a specific example.","Give your second reason with a specific example.","Wrap up by restating your position."],"modelAnswer":"In my opinion, employees should have a strong say in whether they work from home, though I'd stop short of saying it should be entirely their choice with no limits. My first reason is productivity. A lot of people simply focus better without the constant interruptions of an open office. When I worked on a big report last winter, I got far more done at my kitchen table in two quiet mornings than I would have with people dropping by my desk all day. My second reason is work-life balance, especially for parents. A coworker of mine has two young kids, and being able to work from home a few days a week means she can drop them at daycare and skip a long, stressful commute. That flexibility keeps her happy and loyal to the company. That said, I understand some roles genuinely need people on site, so I think the fairest approach is a default of flexibility with the employer setting reasonable exceptions. Overall, I believe giving employees real choice about working from home leads to happier, more productive teams.","tips":["A nuanced middle position is fine on Task 7 — just make your main leaning obvious and stick to it.","Signal your structure with phrases like 'My first reason' and 'My second reason' so the rater can follow easily.","Anchor each reason to a specific story ('last winter', 'a coworker of mine') to sound natural and confident.","Save about ten seconds for a clean restatement so your answer doesn't get cut off mid-thought."]},{"id":"opinion-community-centre-programs-seniors-youth","taskNo":7,"type":"Expressing Opinions","title":"Community Centre Funding Priorities","prompt":"Your local community centre has extra funding for one new program and must choose between activities for seniors or activities for teenagers. Which group should the funding go to? State your opinion and support it with reasons and examples.","prepSec":30,"speakSec":90,"template":["State which group you'd fund and why, up front.","Give your first reason with an example.","Give your second reason with an example.","Restate your choice to finish."],"modelAnswer":"If the community centre can only fund one new program, I believe the money should go to activities for teenagers. My first reason is that teens really need safe, supervised places to spend their free time, especially after school and in the evenings. In my own neighbourhood, there isn't much for them to do, so a lot of kids just end up hanging around the plaza. A drop-in program with sports, music, or homework help would give them somewhere positive to go and keep them out of trouble. My second reason is that these are the habits that shape their whole future. For example, my younger cousin joined a coding club at his local centre, and it completely changed his path — he's now planning to study computer science. Programs like that can open doors that many families couldn't afford on their own. I do have a lot of respect for seniors' programs, and ideally the centre would fund both. But if I have to choose, I'd invest in teenagers, because supporting young people early pays off for the whole community for years to come.","tips":["Commit to one group in your opening sentence — Task 7 punishes fence-sitting when the prompt forces a choice.","You can respect the other option ('I have a lot of respect for seniors' programs') without weakening your stance.","Make examples vivid and personal ('my younger cousin', 'in my own neighbourhood') to boost your vocabulary and fluency scores.","Close by tying your choice to a bigger benefit ('pays off for the whole community') for a strong finish."]}],"t8":[{"id":"cat-on-roomba-cowboy-hat","taskNo":8,"type":"Describing an Unusual Situation","title":"The Vacuum-Riding Cat","prompt":"You took a photo at your friend's apartment and want to describe it to another friend over the phone so they can picture it. In the photo, a large orange tabby cat is sitting perfectly upright on top of a round robot vacuum as it rolls across the living-room floor. The cat is wearing a tiny knitted cowboy hat held on with a chin strap, and it looks completely calm, almost proud, as if it is riding a horse. A small dog is chasing behind the vacuum, and a coffee mug is teetering on the edge of the table it is about to bump into. Describe what is happening in the picture, and explain why it is so unusual.","prepSec":30,"speakSec":60,"template":["Open by telling your friend you have to describe a hilarious photo: 'You will not believe this picture I took...'","Give the overview: what the main subject is and what it is doing (the cat riding the robot vacuum).","Add the odd details: the tiny cowboy hat with the chin strap, the cat's proud expression, the dog chasing behind, the wobbling mug.","Explain why it is unusual and how it makes you feel (cats normally hate vacuums, it looks staged, it's funny).","Close with a reaction: 'I honestly could not stop laughing.'"],"modelAnswer":"Okay, you have to hear about this photo I just took at Priya's place. So right in the middle of the living room, there's this big orange tabby cat, and it is sitting straight up on top of one of those round robot vacuums while it rolls across the floor. The best part is the cat is wearing a tiny little knitted cowboy hat with a strap under its chin, and it looks totally calm, honestly kind of proud, like it's riding a horse into town. Meanwhile there's a small dog running along behind, chasing the vacuum, and there's a coffee mug sitting right on the edge of the table that the vacuum is about to bump into. What makes it so strange is that cats usually run away from vacuums, right? They hate the noise. But this one is just chilling, going for a ride like it does this every day. I could not stop laughing. You really have to see it to believe it.","tips":["Start with the overall scene before the small details so your listener can build the picture in their head.","Use spatial and sequencing words like 'on top of', 'behind', and 'about to' to make the action easy to follow.","Emphasize the contrast that makes it unusual (cats normally fear vacuums) to directly answer 'why is it odd?'.","Keep a light, conversational tone with natural reactions like 'you won't believe this' since you are talking to a friend."]},{"id":"businessman-canoe-flooded-street","taskNo":8,"type":"Describing an Unusual Situation","title":"Commuting by Canoe","prompt":"You snapped a picture on your way to work and want to describe it to a friend on the phone. In the photo, a man in a full business suit and tie is calmly paddling a red canoe down a flooded city street after a heavy rainstorm. He has a leather briefcase balanced on his lap and a takeaway coffee cup wedged beside him. Behind him, cars are stuck bumper to bumper with water halfway up their doors, and a couple of pedestrians on a dry patch of sidewalk are pointing and taking photos. The man looks perfectly relaxed, as if this is his normal morning commute. Describe the scene to your friend, and explain why it is so unusual.","prepSec":30,"speakSec":60,"template":["Grab attention: 'You have to picture what I saw on my way in this morning...'","Overview: a man in a business suit paddling a canoe down a flooded street.","Details: the briefcase on his lap, the coffee cup, the stranded cars, the people taking photos, his calm face.","Why it's unusual: mixing formal office clothes with a canoe, treating a flood like a normal commute.","Wrap up with your reaction and what it says about the weather."],"modelAnswer":"So I have to tell you what I saw walking to work this morning after all that rain. Picture this: there's a guy in a full business suit and tie, and he is calmly paddling a bright red canoe right down the middle of the street. The road is completely flooded from the storm. He's got his leather briefcase balanced on his lap and a takeout coffee tucked in beside him, totally relaxed, like this is just his normal way to get to the office. Behind him all the cars are stuck bumper to bumper with water up to their doors, and a few people on the dry part of the sidewalk are pointing and snapping photos. What makes it so bizarre is the mix, right? You expect someone in a suit to be sipping coffee on a train, not steering a canoe through downtown like nothing is wrong. Only in Canada after a rainstorm, I guess. I had to send you this one.","tips":["Anchor the picture with the biggest contrast first: a suited professional in a canoe.","Describe the background (stranded cars, onlookers) to show scale and make it vivid.","Point out the man's calm attitude, because his reaction is a big part of why the scene is funny and strange.","Use casual connectors like 'so', 'right?', and 'I guess' to sound natural on a phone call with a friend."]},{"id":"penguins-community-centre-lineup","taskNo":8,"type":"Describing an Unusual Situation","title":"Penguins in the Lobby","prompt":"You are at your local community centre and take a photo to send to a friend, then decide to describe it over the phone instead. In the picture, a neat line of about six penguins is waddling across the lobby, following a staff member who is holding a bucket of fish. They are lined up single file behind the front desk, right next to a poster advertising the weekend swim lessons. A few children in the waiting area have dropped their snacks and are staring with their mouths open, and one penguin has stopped to inspect a stray mitten on the floor. The receptionist is carrying on as if nothing strange is happening. Describe the scene to your friend, and explain why it is so unusual.","prepSec":30,"speakSec":60,"template":["Hook: 'You will never guess what is happening at the community centre right now...'","Overview: a line of penguins waddling through the lobby behind a staff member with a fish bucket.","Details: the single-file line, the swim-lesson poster, the stunned kids with dropped snacks, the penguin poking at a mitten.","Why it's unusual: penguins belong in an aquarium or zoo, not a rec-centre lobby, and everyone is oddly calm.","Close with a guess about why they might be there and your own reaction."],"modelAnswer":"Okay, you will never guess what is going on at the community centre right now. I'm standing in the lobby, and there is an actual line of penguins, maybe six of them, waddling single file across the floor. They're following a staff member who's holding a bucket of fish, and they line up right behind the front desk, next to that poster for the weekend swim lessons, which honestly makes it even funnier. A bunch of kids in the waiting area have dropped their snacks and they're just staring with their mouths wide open. One of the penguins has stopped to poke at a little mitten someone left on the floor. And the receptionist? She's typing away like this is a completely normal Tuesday. That's what makes it so bizarre, right? You expect penguins at an aquarium or a zoo, definitely not marching through a rec centre. I'm guessing it's some kind of special event, but I had to call and tell you.","tips":["Lead with the single strangest fact (a line of penguins indoors) before filling in the smaller details.","Use counting and ordering words like 'about six', 'single file', and 'behind the desk' to help your listener visualize the layout.","Highlight the calm receptionist versus the shocked kids, since that contrast is what makes it unusual.","Finish with a reasonable guess about why it is happening to show you can speculate naturally in English."]}]}};
